{"term":"1961","caseName":"Organized Village of Kake v. Egan","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1961/3","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 14, 1961 (Part 1)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren7/oral_argument_audio/23574","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Metlakatla Indian Community, Annette Islands Reserve, Appellant, versus Egan, Governor of -- of Alaska and Number 3, Organized Village of Kake versus Egan, Governor of Alaska.","start":0,"stop":17.76,"duration":17.76},{"text":"Mr. Schifter.","start":17.76,"stop":18.872,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":18.872,"stop":23.451,"duration":4.58},{"text":"The last question yesterday by Mr. Justice Brennan is the matter which I would like to discuss a little bit more fully than I did yesterday.","start":23.451,"stop":31.407,"duration":7.96},{"text":"The background relating of the Metlakatla Community is the following.","start":31.407,"stop":39.123,"duration":7.72},{"text":"The Tsimshian Indians of British Columbia and of an area of British Columbia which actually spilled over in the Southeast Alaska had been the recipients -- or a group of them had been the recipients of the benefits of a missionary by the name of William Duncan in the second half of the 19th Century.","start":39.123,"stop":61.963,"duration":22.84},{"text":"Mr. Duncan, the late missionary, had organized a community of Metlakatla in British Columbia, but had run into difficulties with the Dominion Government and with the Missionary Society which he represented and had led.","start":61.963,"stop":77.164,"duration":15.2},{"text":"At that time, Dr. Henry Ward Beecher and other outstanding personalities in the United States became very much interested in the matter and interested President Grover Cleveland in the situation at Metlakatla. Father Duncan came to Washington and presented his case -- his problems to the United States Government and the invitation to this group to come to Alaska resulted from it.","start":77.164,"stop":110.361,"duration":33.2},{"text":"As indicated, Father Duncan, with a group of members of the Metlakatla Indian Community in British Columbia then moved -- and moved on a short distance, 70 miles to Southeast Alaska and established the community on the Annette Islands Reserve.","start":110.361,"stop":128.973,"duration":18.61},{"text":"The Annette Islands were originally set aside by executive action but because a question as to legality of that arose, the Congress in 1891 had an act which set aside the Annette Island specifically by Congressional action as a reservation, as a United States Reservation for the Metlakatla Indians and such Indians as may join them later which incidentally it was typical language for a good number of Indian Reservation statutes in the law code of the United States.","start":128.973,"stop":160.048,"duration":31.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you, how about the invitational was extended, was the -- extended by the President or was it through an act of Congress?","start":160.048,"stop":170.01,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"It was originally -- I'm not certain -- first of all it was not by an act of Congress initially.","start":170.01,"stop":173.906,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not by--","start":173.906,"stop":174.514,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not by an act of Congress. These people settled in 1887, four years prior to the first action by Congress.","start":174.514,"stop":182.305,"duration":7.79},{"text":"Because of an Attorney General's opinion which raised a question as to whether all of these can be done by executive action, Congress then passed this 1891 Act.","start":182.305,"stop":193.891,"duration":11.59},{"text":"The -- as far as this 1891 Act is concerned and there is certain language in it that is absolutely crucial to the discussion that we -- of that the State of Alaska, well, made later on, the language of the Act specifically provides that the use of this reservation shall be subject to the rules and regulations and restrictions imposed by the Secretary of the Interior.","start":193.891,"stop":221.66,"duration":27.77},{"text":"Now, following the passage of 1891 Act, this community developed at Metlakatla.","start":221.66,"stop":228.533,"duration":6.87},{"text":"Father Duncan was extremely active in strengthening its commercial -- strengthening the economy of the group.","start":228.533,"stop":239.225,"duration":10.69},{"text":"He got this Indian group very quickly involved in commercial fishing which just began around the 1890s as a commercial fishing exploitation of Alaska.","start":239.225,"stop":249.751,"duration":10.53},{"text":"It was started there and this particular group really got in on the ground floor and one of the first things that happened and this was in the 1890s, a cannery was established in Alaska -- in -- at Metlakatla owned by the community.","start":249.751,"stop":266.8,"duration":17.05},{"text":"This cannery has continued in existence since then on and off, it burned down at one time in the early 20th Century and was rebuilt and has -- un-interruptibly in existence since, I believe, around 1915 or roughly 46 years.","start":266.8,"stop":284.503,"duration":17.7}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"May I interrupt just once more please?","start":284.503,"stop":286.785,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":286.785,"stop":289.396,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"My question is prompted by the fact you said they came from so close a distance from Canada, 70 miles as I understand --","start":289.396,"stop":296.671,"duration":7.27}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":296.671,"stop":296.954,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you say, I'm wondering if in this land they were brought to, and this reservation was a part of their ancient lands that they roamed or used or in some other manner occupied?","start":296.954,"stop":312.403,"duration":15.45}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the -- the actual area was uninhabited.","start":312.403,"stop":317.454,"duration":5.05},{"text":"I believe that it is part of -- considered part of the aboriginal area of the Haidas which is -- or the Tlingits which is somewhat different from the Tsimshians.","start":317.454,"stop":327.001,"duration":9.55},{"text":"The Tsimshians were the next-door neighbors --","start":327.001,"stop":329.428,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":329.428,"stop":329.865,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- right over there.","start":329.865,"stop":333.486,"duration":3.62},{"text":"The -- as I indicated the cannery became one of the key elements in economic development of the community and this is really is of great significance in connection with the fish trap situation.","start":333.486,"stop":349.06,"duration":15.57},{"text":"The fact is, that fishing alone by and large has not been able to sus -- to sustain a village or any community in Alaska on an economically sound basis.","start":349.06,"stop":363.092,"duration":14.03},{"text":"The reason why Metlakatla as distinct from other communities has been able to develop a viable economy has been this interaction between fishing and the cannery.","start":363.092,"stop":375.375,"duration":12.28},{"text":"This cannery has always been owned by the Metlakatlans.","start":375.375,"stop":378.737,"duration":3.36},{"text":"The members of the community first of all work in the cannery and thereby, the community is therefore -- the income from fishing is supplemented by the income from the payroll at the cannery.","start":378.737,"stop":391.529,"duration":12.79},{"text":"And furthermore, its profit is derived from cannery and this is really the most substantial benefit of this fishing economy, the profit in cannery and that has been over the years plowed back into the community through various community projects which the community engages in the off season.","start":391.529,"stop":410.303,"duration":18.77},{"text":"In other words, the fishermen are then employed in building roads and doing various other things during the off season and the profit of the cannery is used in this manner and it is in this fashion that the Metlakatla Indian Community as distinct from some other fishing communities in Alaska was able to establish a viable economy.","start":410.303,"stop":432.297,"duration":21.99},{"text":"Now, one of the --","start":432.297,"stop":432.969,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"How about (Inaudible) in this legal question though?","start":432.969,"stop":439.444,"duration":6.48}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor I -- it relates to a question which was in the Court's opinion in to the 1950 -- in 1959 term namely the relevant factors of a -- concerning --","start":439.444,"stop":454.794,"duration":15.35}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"If we -- if we were the Secretary of the Interior and we have authority to regulate these things, those things would be very, very relevant, but the question is whether the Secretary of Interior now has anymore authority, isn't that it?","start":454.794,"stop":468.246,"duration":13.45}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":468.246,"stop":468.592,"duration":0.35},{"text":"I'm trying to explain as a matter of fact what made the Secretary -- I believe at the last argument Justice Frankfurter made the point that I have not put in a flesh on the legal bones of the argument and I wanted to --","start":468.592,"stop":480.442,"duration":11.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So you have a hard time, don't you?","start":480.442,"stop":483.344,"duration":2.9},{"text":"Do you have a hard time in this crossfire, don't you? [Laughter]","start":483.344,"stop":493.469,"duration":10.13}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The fact that the United States Government was aware of the -- of this economic problem is illustrated then by the specific action of the President, President Wilson in 1916, in spelling out the boundaries of the Reserve with particular reference to the fishing area.","start":493.469,"stop":518.044,"duration":24.57},{"text":"And the specific decision that was made in by the President in 1916 is to define the boundaries as extending 3000 feet into the ocean.","start":518.044,"stop":529.428,"duration":11.38},{"text":"This was an exclusive fishing reserve as spelled out by President Wilson's proclamation in 1916.","start":529.428,"stop":537.191,"duration":7.76},{"text":"If there ever was any question as to the President's power to issue this proclamation, it was later addressed -- addressed in 1934 when the Congress passed a specific statute which specifically confirmed previous presidential action in this matter.","start":537.191,"stop":553.555,"duration":16.36},{"text":"What was, therefore, done was the setting aside of a -- of a water reservation of fifty-six-and-a-half square miles subject to the control of the Secretary of the Interior.","start":553.555,"stop":566.145,"duration":12.59},{"text":"This reservation was considered by this Court in the Alaska Pacific Fisheries case in 1918 and it was at that time confirmed.","start":566.145,"stop":576.647,"duration":10.5},{"text":"It was also mentioned in the case of Hynes versus Grimes by the Supreme Court in 1949 and as Mr. Justice Douglas raised the question at the last argument concerning Hynes versus Grimes, I just want to emphasize that there were two distinct holdings in Hynes versus Grimes.","start":576.647,"stop":595.78,"duration":19.13},{"text":"The first holding was that and that was in connection with the Karluk Reservation that reservations of this type are valid that they may be established and this particular reservation of Metlakatla Reservation was referred to in the decision of the Court at that time.","start":595.78,"stop":613.449,"duration":17.67},{"text":"The Court then went on to say that the criminal sanctions of the White Act do not protect such a reservation that this second holding of the Hynes -- in Hynes versus Grimes has no real bearing on the facts in this case.","start":613.449,"stop":627.56,"duration":14.11},{"text":"The first holding, namely that the reservation maybe maintained is crucial.","start":627.56,"stop":633.806,"duration":6.25},{"text":"Since Hynes versus Grimes, the Congress had acted in two ways which may have bearing on the --","start":633.806,"stop":640.135,"duration":6.33}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't suppose you go as far as to say that these rights of the Indian and such whatever they may be is contensible, are contensible?","start":640.135,"stop":648.044,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not suggesting it in this case and in this instance.","start":648.044,"stop":655.422,"duration":7.38},{"text":"Congress has acted twice since Hynes versus Grimes.","start":655.422,"stop":659.617,"duration":4.19},{"text":"In the first instance, it amended Public Law 280 of the 83rd Congress which was discussed yesterday in another case in 1958, to include Alaska as one of the States subject to the state jurisdiction.","start":659.617,"stop":677.411,"duration":17.79},{"text":"But, when it took this action, one has to note that the Public Law 280 specifically provides that Indians are not to be deprived of right, privileges or immunities afforded under federal statutes with respect to fishing or the control, licensing and regulation thereon.","start":677.411,"stop":695.979,"duration":18.57},{"text":"And this is a very crucial Section in all this Public Law 280 situation that is that with regard to Indian Reservations that are covered by Public Law 280, hunting and fishing is maintained under federal (Voice Overlap) in the case maybe.","start":695.979,"stop":715.605,"duration":19.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where -- where is the text of that statute set forth please?","start":715.605,"stop":723.505,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I've set out the specific Section in our replied brief, the green brief, bottom of page 3, going over to page 4.","start":723.505,"stop":733.322,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":733.322,"stop":734.241,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, bottom of page 3 and continuing to page 4.","start":734.241,"stop":747.602,"duration":13.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the date of enactment (Inaudible)","start":747.602,"stop":749.652,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The amendment was in 1958 extending it to Alaska.","start":749.652,"stop":755.338,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I mean the original.","start":755.338,"stop":757.06,"duration":1.72},{"text":"The --","start":757.06,"stop":758.439,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"1953 Act.","start":758.439,"stop":759.372,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"1953 and this is 19 --","start":759.372,"stop":761.242,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"1958.","start":761.242,"stop":765.274,"duration":4.03},{"text":"The other congressional action and this is the one I presume the State bases its argument on or at least it hopes that this is the time when the State actually obtained authority to move in, is the Statehood Act.","start":765.274,"stop":779.163,"duration":13.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it that any rights under federal treaty, agreement or statute would cover such discretionally power that the Secretary has on the Statute if it's their right to recognize it.","start":779.163,"stop":794.622,"duration":15.46}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct Your Honor.","start":794.622,"stop":795.581,"duration":0.96},{"text":"The 1891 Act says that.","start":795.581,"stop":797.134,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Says that.","start":797.134,"stop":797.812,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":797.812,"stop":799.071,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":799.071,"stop":802.009,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I would now like to turn to the Statehood Act and specifically to Section 4 of the Statehood Act.","start":802.009,"stop":808.228,"duration":6.22},{"text":"What the Court may wish to note is that there are two distinct clauses in this Statehood -- in Section 4.","start":808.228,"stop":814.859,"duration":6.63},{"text":"One is, a disclaimer by the State of Alaska as to any right and title to native properly including fishing rights and then second, the provision --","start":814.859,"stop":825.857,"duration":11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that -- where is that set forth?","start":825.857,"stop":829.258,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The entire --","start":829.258,"stop":830.688,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I notice -- I notice that the Statehood Act was prior in time for the amendment of the right -- that is right.","start":830.688,"stop":841.834,"duration":11.15}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, about the same time, both in 1958.","start":841.834,"stop":844.81,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":844.81,"stop":846.416,"duration":1.61},{"text":"If one has to go --","start":846.416,"stop":846.903,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"A few days.","start":846.903,"stop":847.658,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it becomes a material the Statehood Act proceeding, is that right?","start":847.658,"stop":852.28,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"It preceded but bring into effect later.","start":852.28,"stop":857.763,"duration":5.48},{"text":"Congress adopted the Statehood Act, I believe a few weeks prior to the amendment of Public Law 280, but Public 280 immediately went into effect and Statehood had to ratified and --","start":857.763,"stop":867.827,"duration":10.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I am not drawing inferences.","start":867.827,"stop":869.242,"duration":1.41},{"text":"I just want to follow this (Voice Overlap)","start":869.242,"stop":871.131,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Section 4 of the Statehood Act Your Honor is set forth in our grey brief pages 58, 59.","start":871.131,"stop":881.722,"duration":10.59},{"text":"As I say, there are two distinct clauses, one the disclaim of right and title, the other one -- and this is a crucial in its connection, the reservation to the United States of absolute jurisdiction and control over these property rights, including fishing rights.","start":881.722,"stop":899.672,"duration":17.95},{"text":"I would like to cite the -- I would like to cite six reasons for the contention that the phrase absolute jurisdiction and control of the United States supports the Secretary of Interior's action in this case in outlawing -- in refusing to admit the outlawing of fish traps on the Metlakatla Reservation.","start":899.672,"stop":922.713,"duration":23.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that's -- isn't the adjective absolute rather unusual in these reservation clauses?","start":922.713,"stop":928.899,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe Your Honor is also in the -- in the other -- in the clauses in the other Statehood Act.","start":928.899,"stop":934.258,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In all the Statehood Act, really?","start":934.258,"stop":934.965,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":934.965,"stop":940.949,"duration":5.98},{"text":"The -- first of all, I want to emphasize that the words themselves absolute jurisdiction and control indicate the power that the United States intended to exercise.","start":940.949,"stop":951.741,"duration":10.79},{"text":"Second, if we -- that we want to examine the Omnibus Act passed by Congress a year later, in 1959, to correct this particular Section.","start":951.741,"stop":966.728,"duration":14.99},{"text":"It took a specific step to reemphasize the meaning of absolute jurisdiction and control as far as reservation -- as far as reserving rights to the United States with regard to Indian land is concerned and that is this.","start":966.728,"stop":982.33,"duration":15.6},{"text":"Section 4 as initially phrased applied both to Indian land and to the Government's own land -- U.S. Government land.","start":982.33,"stop":994.072,"duration":11.74},{"text":"When Congress amended the Statehood Act through the Omnibus Act of 1959, it went out of its way to emphasize that the phrase absolute jurisdiction and control shall not -- shall not apply to its own land, but only to Indian land.","start":994.072,"stop":1009.508,"duration":15.44}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that in your brief?","start":1009.508,"stop":1012.852,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- it's on page 47 of the main brief, the grey brief and the legislative history is explained here and the -- and a quotation from the Senate report and the House report it says, “This is to make clear that the absolute jurisdiction and control of the United States does not apply generally to land held by the United States in Alaska, but only land and property held by natives or by the United States and trust of natives.”","start":1012.852,"stop":1042.974,"duration":30.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The only burden of this case is the native man, but would you mind in -- for instance is to say what -- what was left because that's -- with reference the public, the governmental domain other than in the --","start":1042.974,"stop":1056.766,"duration":13.79}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right and title.","start":1056.766,"stop":1059.187,"duration":2.42},{"text":"In other words, as far as public domain land was concerned, the United States made it clear in Section 4 had right and title but not absolute jurisdiction and control.","start":1059.187,"stop":1066.878,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that mean we're not concerned with the -- just curiosity, would that mean that so called police power of Alaska can extend -- extend to Government land?","start":1066.878,"stop":1073.781,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1073.781,"stop":1074.901,"duration":1.12},{"text":"That's the way I understand it Your Honor.","start":1074.901,"stop":1076.285,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1076.285,"stop":1077.88,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg your pardon?","start":1077.88,"stop":1078.698,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1078.698,"stop":1080.517,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":1080.517,"stop":1082.044,"duration":1.53},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, this was the very reason why this clarification took place in the Omnibus Act to make -- make certain that the police power would extend over the -- over United States land, but make it quite clear that it does not apply to the up -- to these rights reserved by the second clause of Section --","start":1082.044,"stop":1101.517,"duration":19.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But once an amendment does really amend, doesn't it?","start":1101.517,"stop":1104.938,"duration":3.42},{"text":"I say, for once an amendment does --","start":1104.938,"stop":1107.396,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well it was oversized--","start":1107.396,"stop":1108.041,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of a territory.","start":1108.041,"stop":1109.042,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"It was oversight perhaps Your Honor in the first kind of was drafted and being too all inclusive and then they narrowed it.","start":1109.042,"stop":1116.526,"duration":7.48},{"text":"I've also set forth citations from the legislative reports over the eight years which indicated very clearly the intention of Congress to reserve absolute jurisdiction and control over these fishing rights to it.","start":1116.526,"stop":1134.885,"duration":18.36},{"text":"The problem before Congress as explained by the legislative history was that the United -- that the Congress did not want to see itself burdened at the time, it was legislating with regard to Statehood with the problem of Indian rights.","start":1134.885,"stop":1153.988,"duration":19.1},{"text":"It did not want to change it in anyway and there was this very strong insistence by the Congress to freeze everything regarding Indian rights in status quo and let the matter of Indian rights be determined after the statehood had been obtained.","start":1153.988,"stop":1168.278,"duration":14.29},{"text":"Advocates of Statehood at the same time recognized go well that if they did get themselves embroiled in argument over Indian rights, Statehood might possibly be defeated both in Congress and possibly in the State itself.","start":1168.278,"stop":1183.422,"duration":15.14},{"text":"As far as action in Congress is concerned, we have quoted in particular a statement by Senator Anderson who emphasized that the members of the Committee that wrote the legislation all came from the State with substantial Indian populations and therefore we're aware of the political reality as far as they were concerned in making sure that Indian rights were protected.","start":1183.422,"stop":1203.278,"duration":19.86},{"text":"And throughout this period, there was a strong pro-Indian lobby which saw it that Section 4 was in no way weakened and we have a citation in --","start":1203.278,"stop":1214.674,"duration":11.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I ought to know but I don't Mr. Schifter, what is the Indian population relation in total, for the White population so called White population?","start":1214.674,"stop":1222.062,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of Alaska?","start":1222.062,"stop":1222.7,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1222.7,"stop":1224.517,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The figure which the State office with regard to fishermen is 42%.","start":1224.517,"stop":1228.478,"duration":3.96},{"text":"I presume it's less with regards to others.","start":1228.478,"stop":1231.865,"duration":3.39},{"text":"I believe there about 30,000 to 35,000 natives in Alaska and -- and the total population 37,000 out of 226,000.","start":1231.865,"stop":1244.559,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You have it --","start":1244.559,"stop":1245.277,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"37,000 out of --","start":1245.277,"stop":1246.265,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- out of 226,000.","start":1246.265,"stop":1247.827,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"A White man, although born in Alaska currently is not a native man.","start":1247.827,"stop":1250.961,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1250.961,"stop":1253.828,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"The 37,000 is all natives, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts or any of them all.","start":1253.828,"stop":1259.313,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Indian, Eskimos and Aleuts all put together and in that connection, may I emphasize that we claim no right as far as Metakatla is concerned, no special right outside the reserve, as state hasn't briefed occasionally, suggested that we might be claiming rights all over.","start":1259.313,"stop":1275.923,"duration":16.61},{"text":"We do not.","start":1275.923,"stop":1276.752,"duration":0.83},{"text":"We claim only within these fifty-six-and-a-half square miles.","start":1276.752,"stop":1283.196,"duration":6.44},{"text":"Finally in terms of statutory interpretation, I would like to call attention to the Secretary of the Interior's immediate action following the passage of the Statehood Act in promulgating -- promulgating regulations which specifically authorized the use of fish traps.","start":1283.196,"stop":1301.08,"duration":17.88},{"text":"And this is particularly important again against the background to the fact that the Secretary of the Interior was instrumental in the drafting of not only the Statehood Act but particularly Section 4.","start":1301.08,"stop":1313.456,"duration":12.38},{"text":"And we have a statement by Senator Anderson in the brief emphasizing the fact that the Secretary of the Interior and his representatives react – they participated in drafting the Section 4.","start":1313.456,"stop":1323.552,"duration":10.1},{"text":"So there in the department, there was no doubt immediately after the Statehood Act passed, they promulgated regulations which permitted the operation of these fish traps.","start":1323.552,"stop":1330.912,"duration":7.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh but, there was very distinguish men partaking of this oversize, is that right?","start":1330.912,"stop":1337.276,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes Your Honor.","start":1337.276,"stop":1339.581,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you going to talk about Section 16?","start":1339.581,"stop":1346.394,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the Statehood Act Your Honor?","start":1346.394,"stop":1347.965,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1347.965,"stop":1349.172,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"No I'm not.","start":1349.172,"stop":1351.047,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that's -- is that all relevant to our problem?","start":1351.047,"stop":1355.106,"duration":4.06},{"text":"Because apparently, the Secretary of the Interior, the reason I mention this because you refer to the Department of the Interior and its regulations, but under Section 6 (e) as I understand --","start":1355.106,"stop":1369.337,"duration":14.23}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, 6 (e) I'm sorry.","start":1369.337,"stop":1370.251,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I understood 16.","start":1370.251,"stop":1371.418,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"6 (e)?","start":1371.418,"stop":1372.229,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"6 (e), yes.","start":1372.229,"stop":1373.872,"duration":1.64},{"text":"That referred to fishing -- the one unique feature about Alaska fishing Your Honor was that both Indian and non-Indian fishing was under the control of the Secretary of the Interior and under Section 6 (e), the Sec -- the Secretary of Interior transferred to the new State control over non-Indian fishing.","start":1373.872,"stop":1397.048,"duration":23.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well here, it was over the whole of Alaska into states.","start":1397.048,"stop":1399.657,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1399.657,"stop":1399.975,"duration":0.32},{"text":"But Your Honor, in some other States though, the territorial Government, they --","start":1399.975,"stop":1404.94,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I mean as to Alaska; that was all governed from the Interior department.","start":1404.94,"stop":1408.355,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"There was some self-Government.","start":1408.355,"stop":1410.016,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, never get it but --","start":1410.016,"stop":1411.321,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"And but not with regard to fishing.","start":1411.321,"stop":1412.854,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Fishing was handled directly by the Secretary of the Interior and that --","start":1412.854,"stop":1415.872,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How far is the Central Government, the United States Government and oversize of Alaska, it was the positive (Inaudible) Secretary of Interior.","start":1415.872,"stop":1422.517,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"If that's not there -- that's not the problem of 6 -- of 6 (e) is whether as I understand it, whether not the certificate issued pursuant to Section 6 (e), it give or should have given the State of Alaska full jurisdiction over -- says fish and wildlife resources, doesn't it?","start":1422.517,"stop":1449.784,"duration":27.27},{"text":"Are those the words?","start":1449.784,"stop":1451.057,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"But these were -- these did not -- the way the Congress always made it clear in its legislative history was that this Section 6 (e) was to accept Indian resources.","start":1451.057,"stop":1465.131,"duration":14.07}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's possible because that's one of the questions we have to decide.","start":1465.131,"stop":1468.654,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1468.654,"stop":1468.915,"duration":0.26},{"text":"I just want to emphasize Your Honor that the legislative history makes it quite clear whenever they explained Section 6 (e) and its -- and its connection to Section 4 in the reports, they made it clear that there is a transfer of all fishing rights except those reserved to Indian and the specific phrase is you know, our green brief on page 6 to accept from transfer to the State those fisheries and wildlife which are included within the reserve of native right.","start":1468.915,"stop":1499.892,"duration":30.98},{"text":"This is in both in -- in the Senate report in 1950.","start":1499.892,"stop":1502.849,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's Section 4.","start":1502.849,"stop":1503.452,"duration":0.6},{"text":"I was wondering -- I was wondering, the laws adopted by -- Alaska adopted laws in 1959 after Statehood to regulate fishing generally, isn't it, by everybody?","start":1503.452,"stop":1519.109,"duration":15.66}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":1519.109,"stop":1520.915,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And the Secretary thereupon made this certificate as -- that the effect of Alaska had taken over the field of regulation of wildlife and fishing, didn't he?","start":1520.915,"stop":1531.246,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, when that -- that's correct but when the State passed that law, it said it shall not be construed to conflict with Section 4.","start":1531.246,"stop":1538.9,"duration":7.65},{"text":"Now, that was one of the questions which was still open, which the Alaska Supreme is not closed.","start":1538.9,"stop":1542.819,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not suggesting that that precludes. I just want to kind of run out the picture of what happened.","start":1542.819,"stop":1546.934,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1546.934,"stop":1547.345,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, am I wrong that 6 (e) had as primary purpose, provided opportunity to the State of Alaska.","start":1547.345,"stop":1557.529,"duration":10.18},{"text":"They passed regulatory laws which satisfactory to the Secretary of the Interior would then make possible certification which he did make after the 1959 laws were adopted which became effective 90 days after something like that, wasn't that idea?","start":1557.529,"stop":1574.195,"duration":16.67}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe Mr. Justice Brennan the basic intention of Congress was to provide through a transition period.","start":1574.195,"stop":1578.407,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1578.407,"stop":1578.96,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and make certain though that after that period, the State of Alaska (Voice Overlap) responsibility.","start":1578.96,"stop":1581.584,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it wasn't -- it wasn't (Voice Overlap).","start":1581.584,"stop":1583.15,"duration":1.57},{"text":"I just have some recollection at the time that application per se was before me that there was a suggestion that this transition was necessary.","start":1583.15,"stop":1593.458,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe it --","start":1593.458,"stop":1593.918,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in part to allow the Secretary to be satisfied with the laws that in -- were adopted, would not be in consistent with the general pattern of regulation.","start":1593.918,"stop":1603.813,"duration":9.9}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I rather assume Mr. Justice Brennan that the intention was to permit the state of Alaska to get its -- its enforcement apparatus set up.","start":1603.813,"stop":1611.482,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":1611.482,"stop":1612.242,"duration":0.76},{"text":"But wasn't it to some idea that the enforcement apparatus before the certificate would be granted had to be satisfactory to --","start":1612.242,"stop":1619.246,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the enforcement apparatus not necessarily regulations but the enforcement apparatus, yes that the people are ready to start enforcing.","start":1619.246,"stop":1625.325,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But he had to be satisfied that they were consistent with the protection of -- of wildlife --","start":1625.325,"stop":1630.892,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as enforcement apparatus is concerned.","start":1630.892,"stop":1632.24,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":1632.24,"stop":1632.918,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1632.918,"stop":1635.78,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it doesn't -- doesn't quite say that.","start":1635.78,"stop":1638.886,"duration":3.11},{"text":"It says it has made adequate provision for the administration management in conservation of fish and wildlife.","start":1638.886,"stop":1647.044,"duration":8.16}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe these words Your Honor do mean that the -- do reflect the intention of Congress to delay only until the Secretary of the State of Alaska is able to -- to carry on a system of conservation.","start":1647.044,"stop":1665.452,"duration":18.41},{"text":"I do not think it was the intention of Congress to have the Secretary of -- of the Interior dictate in a way that the State of Alaska exactly what enforcement -- what enforcement (Inaudible) to pass but mainly to have a --","start":1665.452,"stop":1679.499,"duration":14.05}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But certainly the words administration management and conservation of fish would include the regulation -- I would assume it would include regulations concerning trapping of fish.","start":1679.499,"stop":1690.592,"duration":11.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, indeed, what was the name of the chap whose name was given to this proviso?","start":1690.592,"stop":1694.533,"duration":3.94},{"text":"It was called the --","start":1694.533,"stop":1694.956,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Westland, Westland proviso.","start":1694.956,"stop":1695.641,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Westland proviso and he was -- he was very concerned that Alaska might do things which were not in the national interest --","start":1695.641,"stop":1703.237,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1703.237,"stop":1704.057,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in matters of conservation and such, wasn't it?","start":1704.057,"stop":1706.941,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, yeah.","start":1706.941,"stop":1707.255,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was he a great sportsman or something I forgot.","start":1707.255,"stop":1708.783,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and of State of Washington.","start":1708.783,"stop":1710.919,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"He was the national golf champion –","start":1710.919,"stop":1712.657,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, that's right.","start":1712.657,"stop":1729.926,"duration":17.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Cragun.","start":1729.926,"stop":1731.26,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court.","start":1731.26,"stop":1735.039,"duration":3.78},{"text":"I speak here for the Organized Village of Kake and the Angoon Community Association.","start":1735.039,"stop":1741.343,"duration":6.3},{"text":"Unlike the Metlakatla people who came from Canada, these are the people who were always there.","start":1741.343,"stop":1749.657,"duration":8.31},{"text":"The Court acclaims tells us in a suit they filed there that they have been there since time immemorial that they lived by fishing and that they traded in fish, weighing up surplus goods was an important feature of their economy.","start":1749.657,"stop":1768.592,"duration":18.94},{"text":"Now, these people --","start":1768.592,"stop":1769.948,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you -- you're covered also by the Secretary of Interior's Regulation?","start":1769.948,"stop":1774.898,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1774.898,"stop":1775.679,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in 1960?","start":1775.679,"stop":1776.74,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1776.74,"stop":1778.97,"duration":2.23},{"text":"There are several trap sites which belong to Kake and to Angoon which were purchased along with cannery equipment from White operators in 1948 and 1950 by the Secretary of the Interior.","start":1778.97,"stop":1791.829,"duration":12.86}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you within the -- was it a technically reservation also?","start":1791.829,"stop":1795.055,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir.","start":1795.055,"stop":1796.282,"duration":1.23},{"text":"The only thing that these Indians can point to is that they have always been fisherman.","start":1796.282,"stop":1800.824,"duration":4.54},{"text":"They've always lived in this area.","start":1800.824,"stop":1803.363,"duration":2.54},{"text":"They're in their aboriginal area and they only have the protection with such things as the trading with Russia guaranteed to be accorded to natives in their own property.","start":1803.363,"stop":1816.379,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that treaty still enforced?","start":1816.379,"stop":1818.314,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1818.314,"stop":1818.609,"duration":0.29},{"text":"It's never been the denounced that I know of.","start":1818.609,"stop":1820.97,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Again an organized community (Inaudible)","start":1820.97,"stop":1823.344,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1823.344,"stop":1824.347,"duration":1},{"text":"Both are organized under the Indian Reorganization Act of 1934 both also have corporate charters in accordance with Section 16 and 17 of that Act.","start":1824.347,"stop":1836.403,"duration":12.06},{"text":"Those charters, I was able to get only a couple of -- a copy of each, were handed up to the court in previous argument and I suppose are with the clerk.","start":1836.403,"stop":1846.988,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Refresh my recollection, what's your total population?","start":1846.988,"stop":1850.279,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"The total population of Kake is alleged in the complaint to be 400.","start":1850.279,"stop":1859.739,"duration":9.46},{"text":"The total population of Angoon -- this is 1959 that this complaint was filed, there maybe some change since, was stated to be 306.","start":1859.739,"stop":1871.257,"duration":11.52},{"text":"These people have only the throb left of their original rights, which represents their continuous fishing.","start":1871.257,"stop":1880.333,"duration":9.08},{"text":"White people have been in there.","start":1880.333,"stop":1882.676,"duration":2.34},{"text":"They have exploited the fisheries and the Indians have left only what is covered by the Secretary's regulations.","start":1882.676,"stop":1891.063,"duration":8.39},{"text":"Now, the posture of this case comes down to this.","start":1891.063,"stop":1893.262,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Alaska says that its statute, in spite of what I thought were pretty plain reservations, prohibit this Indian trap fishing.","start":1893.262,"stop":1903.94,"duration":10.68},{"text":"The Secretary of the Interior by his regulation says they're entitled to fish there and one or the other has got to fall.","start":1903.94,"stop":1910.885,"duration":6.94},{"text":"This Court has no alternative and neither to say Section 4 of a Statehood Act which says that the absolute jurisdiction and control of these Indian fishing rights shall be and remain with the United States until dispose by it is, is out, it's unconstitutional because as Alaska says, the conflict with the equal footing doctrine or for some of the other reasons I guess or you must hold that those Alaska's statutes fall before the federal act of Congress reserving absolute jurisdiction and control.","start":1910.885,"stop":1945.609,"duration":34.72},{"text":"The fact is that when this complaint was filed, when the Alaska Statehood Act was passed, these people were fishing there under regulations promulgated by the Secretary of the Interior.","start":1945.609,"stop":1959.609,"duration":14},{"text":"The United States in Section 4 of the Statehood Act gave to the new State the power and jurisdiction over fishing subject to they're getting regulatory machinery and shape under Section 6 (e) which had been adverted to and then they said that excludes Indian property rights including fishing rights which are reserved under the absolute jurisdiction and control of the United States.","start":1959.609,"stop":1993.91,"duration":34.3},{"text":"I submit that the Unites States have the power to make that provision at the time notwithstanding the state court's views as to the invalidity of Section 4.","start":1993.91,"stop":2007.216,"duration":13.31},{"text":"Now before I pass on to whether Section 4 is invalid, I would like to associate myself with something I was sorry Mr. Schifter didn't get to deal with in his brief.","start":2007.216,"stop":2017.949,"duration":10.73},{"text":"I -- I thought it was quite a lended credence as to the obvious anxiety with which matters of fish traps are dealt with by Alaska and its Supreme Court.","start":2017.949,"stop":2034.144,"duration":16.19},{"text":"You will find better hostility in this long opinion of the Supreme Court of Alaska towards the fish trap.","start":2034.144,"stop":2041.157,"duration":7.01},{"text":"Mr. Schifter has documented that beautifully in his brief.","start":2041.157,"stop":2045.485,"duration":4.33},{"text":"The fish trap in Alaska is hated symbol of colonialism, Alaska colonialism.","start":2045.485,"stop":2052.503,"duration":7.02},{"text":"Freight operators out of Seattle mostly running these big fish traps, recruiting their crews in Alaska, Alaska didn't even get the cigarette money that that the crews spent.","start":2052.503,"stop":2065.844,"duration":13.34},{"text":"It is an intense emotional issue with Alaska and it does enable us to understand the -- the attitude and approach of state officials and state court.","start":2065.844,"stop":2077.047,"duration":11.2},{"text":"Now, to pass that because it is fully covered and fully documented by Mr. Schifter, I would like to go to the reasons which the state court gives in this lengthy opinion for the invalidity of Section 4.","start":2077.047,"stop":2090.395,"duration":13.35},{"text":"It's -- Section 4 has got to fall, it reaches the point directly.","start":2090.395,"stop":2094.241,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Cragun, before you get to that, may I ask this question.","start":2094.241,"stop":2097.837,"duration":3.6},{"text":"If you prevail, is there any territorial limit at all to the right of your people to establish these fish traps?","start":2097.837,"stop":2109.687,"duration":11.85}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly.","start":2109.687,"stop":2110.541,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What that (Voice Overlap)","start":2110.541,"stop":2111.579,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"These -- these people never had rights outside their own area and these rights are within that extremely limited area.","start":2111.579,"stop":2122.39,"duration":10.81},{"text":"It's mapped by the Court of Claims.","start":2122.39,"stop":2125.51,"duration":3.12},{"text":"It's in the federal supplement.","start":2125.51,"stop":2126.885,"duration":1.38},{"text":"I regret the big fold-out map that's in the pamphlet opinion of the Court of Claims sprightly reduced but it can be seen with a magnifying glass.","start":2126.885,"stop":2135.494,"duration":8.61},{"text":"No, they have no rights outside their aboriginal area and they have no rights except those which are accorded by federal regulation.","start":2135.494,"stop":2142.828,"duration":7.33},{"text":"They were accorded by federal regulation at the time the Statehood Act was passed and that is what was reserved to these people and all it's reserved to the notion that is advanced in the State brief that somehow rather while the Secretary could say, “Alright fellows, you can range all over Alaska” is I think reading far too much into our argument.","start":2142.828,"stop":2166.598,"duration":23.77},{"text":"What was done was reserved something to the absolute jurisdiction and control of the United States and what was reserved was what there and what was there was set forth in federal regulations which are set out in the complaint.","start":2166.598,"stop":2180.288,"duration":13.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And are there rights strictly, closely restricted from your point of view.","start":2180.288,"stop":2187.287,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Very much --","start":2187.287,"stop":2187.945,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) existent at the time of the Act.","start":2187.945,"stop":2191.449,"duration":3.5},{"text":"In other words, could he oppose -- suppose some other fishing devices were invented?","start":2191.449,"stop":2198.388,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Electronic device.","start":2198.388,"stop":2199.745,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"An electronic device, could the -- could the Secretary of the Interior confer new opportunities to your people?","start":2199.745,"stop":2208.087,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, I think so.","start":2208.087,"stop":2209.854,"duration":1.77},{"text":"It's within his area.","start":2209.854,"stop":2213.095,"duration":3.24},{"text":"It's the old problem I have -- Mr. Justice Van Devanter had a phrase for it in the -- I believe it was the Sandoval case.","start":2213.095,"stop":2225.558,"duration":12.46},{"text":"The fact that a combine harvester is invented neither enlarges nor reduces the right for the Indian in his land.","start":2225.558,"stop":2236.329,"duration":10.77},{"text":"I think within these areas which are set out by federal regulation, they can fish if the Secretary says so perhaps only with a hook and line or with gillnets or purse seines or traps or if a new device is invented electronically beats the trap.","start":2236.329,"stop":2255.559,"duration":19.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Power to fix to the land.","start":2255.559,"stop":2257.877,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes (Voice Overlap)","start":2257.877,"stop":2258.558,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) fix to the land.","start":2258.558,"stop":2259.614,"duration":1.06},{"text":"I think that's your view that sets the land shall be remain under (Inaudible) jurisdiction, so within its territory, the Secretary of the Interior is the master because United States is the master.","start":2259.614,"stop":2272.07,"duration":12.46}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2272.07,"stop":2273.577,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I put that question to you in no difference form?","start":2273.577,"stop":2276.043,"duration":2.47},{"text":"Supposing a new tribe of Indians moved in with the territory that you're talking about which were subject to the permissive authority given by the Secretary of Interior, would that be under the Statehood Act reser -- the protection under reservation clause?","start":2276.043,"stop":2295.422,"duration":19.38}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe not sir and here is the reason.","start":2295.422,"stop":2297.378,"duration":1.96},{"text":"There were nine trap sites which where set forth in the federal regulation as pertaining to Kake and there were four trap sites pertaining to Angoon when the Statehood Act was passed.","start":2297.378,"stop":2310.347,"duration":12.97},{"text":"Now, these with trap sites, you might say which were bought and paid for by the Indians because the United States put up the money and they -- they purchased traps and canneries.","start":2310.347,"stop":2322.182,"duration":11.83},{"text":"And there is, as the Supreme Court of Alaska says a moral priority to the owner to go in there.","start":2322.182,"stop":2327.947,"duration":5.77},{"text":"Now, I don't think the -- the Secretary can take that and give back to other Indians.","start":2327.947,"stop":2331.576,"duration":3.63},{"text":"I don't believe it's possible.","start":2331.576,"stop":2333.062,"duration":1.49},{"text":"He hasn't permitted Kake or Angoon to fish all of those trap sites.","start":2333.062,"stop":2337.812,"duration":4.75},{"text":"Out of the nine trap sites which he had authorized when he left some big fish for Kake, he's permitted only four to be fished.","start":2337.812,"stop":2347.476,"duration":9.66},{"text":"Out of the four for Angoon's, he has permitted only three to be fished, but I think that marks the limits on it and I don't think he can give the right of Kake and Angoon a way the other Indians anymore than can he could authorize taking Angoon to go to other Indian preserves and fish them.","start":2347.476,"stop":2362.863,"duration":15.39}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Could he create some more traps, some more trap rights that were given to a new Indian tribe that might move in there?","start":2362.863,"stop":2372.649,"duration":9.79}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"An Indian tribe, of course this is quite a ways away from my case.","start":2372.649,"stop":2378.167,"duration":5.52},{"text":"I -- I don't want to argue somebody else his rights, but if -- if you got to try up there that can show the continuous link of fishing, I suppose under the reservation of absolute jurisdiction and control over that right, the Secretary might convert to a trap.","start":2378.167,"stop":2393.415,"duration":15.25},{"text":"I would assume that so, it's merely in another way of fishing.","start":2393.415,"stop":2396.734,"duration":3.32},{"text":"It is a regulation of the method of the fishing and traps are far more satisfactory from a conservations standpoint then other method of fishing according to reputable testimony from the Department of Interior before Congress.","start":2396.734,"stop":2412.382,"duration":15.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the approximate size of this area, of this land in question?","start":2412.382,"stop":2418.868,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, I -- it's set forth with degrees of latitude and longitude in the regulations and I did not calculate it.","start":2418.868,"stop":2429.346,"duration":10.48},{"text":"I regret that I can't give the -- I don't know that I could calculate it.","start":2429.346,"stop":2433.254,"duration":3.91},{"text":"I didn't have it calculated.","start":2433.254,"stop":2434.666,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it a great area?","start":2434.666,"stop":2436.663,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe not sir.","start":2436.663,"stop":2437.616,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2437.616,"stop":2438.453,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"These are set forth lying between so many degrees, minutes and seconds and there isn't much difference in the seconds and I don't know what to seconds of longitude are in that area.","start":2438.453,"stop":2450.954,"duration":12.5}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The Supreme Court of Alaska seems to as far what it says is concerned, seems to react against the use of the trap, I'm reading on page 29 (a) of the jurisdictional statement, in the number two case, which says, “Under the power, it has not been unusual for a single trap to catch as many as 600,000 fish in a single season as compared to a season's catch of gillnet or purse seine fisherman to the 10,000.","start":2450.954,"stop":2491.715,"duration":40.76},{"text":"It -- the prejudice, it seems in this opinion, be not -- the traps were the budge colonialism but the traps were the way for massive extermination of fish.","start":2491.715,"stop":2502.989,"duration":11.27}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's perfectly true that this is rationalized by the Supreme Court of Alaska.","start":2502.989,"stop":2510.522,"duration":7.53},{"text":"They did not send us back to reopen this.","start":2510.522,"stop":2514.015,"duration":3.49},{"text":"I would have been prepared to put competent fish biologists on to prove that the problem is how many fish are taken and how well they are handled and not when you take them hook and line or by some dynamite or some other destructive means.","start":2514.015,"stop":2531.042,"duration":17.03},{"text":"The traps now catch only an infinite testimonial part of the salmon catch in Alaska because they're so greatly restricted.","start":2531.042,"stop":2541.669,"duration":10.63},{"text":"There state brief puts in as its final appendix, a tabulation showing what's happened in the last two or three years in comparison with earlier years and shows us way done.","start":2541.669,"stop":2552.322,"duration":10.65},{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas, may I call your attention to the talk of the state court, at the bottom of page 5 (a) and running the 6 (a) of its opinion.","start":2552.322,"stop":2564.315,"duration":11.99},{"text":"The top of 6 (a), they give the argument.","start":2564.315,"stop":2566.961,"duration":2.65},{"text":"I don't' think they give it adequately but they give the argument of the proponents of fish traps.","start":2566.961,"stop":2575.163,"duration":8.2},{"text":"They -- they talk on both sides of it, but I don't think that it was meant to do more than claim of the state police power refers to the regulation of fishing which I think we would all agree.","start":2575.163,"stop":2592.036,"duration":16.87},{"text":"They haven't squarely put this on a conservation basis.","start":2592.036,"stop":2596.243,"duration":4.21},{"text":"They give him both sides sir.","start":2596.243,"stop":2597.45,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Cragun, may I hold you up for one more second to --","start":2597.45,"stop":2599.664,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":2599.664,"stop":2600.063,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- have you to tell me that what to relation of the catch of these three communities, traps catches is the total fish economy of Alaska?","start":2600.063,"stop":2612.896,"duration":12.83}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I can't do better than accept the state's -- it comes.","start":2612.896,"stop":2626.45,"duration":13.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I did (Voice Overlap)","start":2626.45,"stop":2629.189,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"I cannot find my brief, I somehow mislaid it.","start":2629.189,"stop":2633.164,"duration":3.98},{"text":"I did calculate it.","start":2633.164,"stop":2634.185,"duration":1.02},{"text":"This is not the one on which I had calculated but it runs to less than 2%.","start":2634.185,"stop":2639.045,"duration":4.86},{"text":"It's practically (Inaudible) even with an outstanding season such as they have this year.","start":2639.045,"stop":2645.785,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"2% of the total?","start":2645.785,"stop":2647.069,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the total in Alaska, yes.","start":2647.069,"stop":2649.571,"duration":2.5},{"text":"It's on page 63 Appendix D of the State's brief.","start":2649.571,"stop":2653.666,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":2653.666,"stop":2656.054,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand you today that the (Inaudible) catch had power to prohibit the (Inaudible)","start":2656.054,"stop":2669.507,"duration":13.45}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, does -- the state him to power to prohibit traps.","start":2669.507,"stop":2674.032,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2674.032,"stop":2675.447,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh yes, I think he does because he has the regulation and control of the Indian fishing.","start":2675.447,"stop":2683.325,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"They claim any -- claim any rights in constitutional right, anything like that above the Secretary's order?","start":2683.325,"stop":2690.691,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2690.691,"stop":2690.985,"duration":0.29},{"text":"I think that unfortunately under the decisions of this Court, they can't pin it on the constitution so ruled in the Tee-Hit-Ton case.","start":2690.985,"stop":2699.916,"duration":8.93},{"text":"They have an aboriginal right which is a true right and a legal right and one on which they can recover, but because of the political nature of that right, it requires further action of Congress before they can come in and assert it against the United Sates.","start":2699.916,"stop":2713.752,"duration":13.84}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"A matter of grace, though?","start":2713.752,"stop":2715.556,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a matter of grace.","start":2715.556,"stop":2716.639,"duration":1.08},{"text":"It's a legal right, but there without a remedy until the Congress gives it.","start":2716.639,"stop":2722.525,"duration":5.89},{"text":"Congress did give it to them in the Court of Claim case.","start":2722.525,"stop":2726.022,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I hope you'll have time enough left to say your piece about equal footing.","start":2726.022,"stop":2731.831,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I had hoped so.","start":2731.831,"stop":2733.119,"duration":1.29},{"text":"I have had a one -- well, I might as well take it even the expensively (Voice Overlap)","start":2733.119,"stop":2741.474,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you more important point Mr. Cragun?","start":2741.474,"stop":2743.349,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I haven't more important point.","start":2743.349,"stop":2745.059,"duration":1.71},{"text":"I don't suppose that neither did the Supreme Court of Alaska.","start":2745.059,"stop":2747.86,"duration":2.8},{"text":"Supreme Court of Alaska says that this statute is invalid, Section 4 reserving absolute jurisdiction and control of the United States is invalid because it violates the equal footing done.","start":2747.86,"stop":2760.539,"duration":12.68},{"text":"Now, equal footing is something that Congress accords but it has apparently by this Court been treated as on the level of a constitutional right of the State to be on an equal footing or the other states.","start":2760.539,"stop":2771.98,"duration":11.44},{"text":"But this Court has repeatedly sustained reservations of Indian rights and Indian fishing rights, both on and off the reservation where treaties provided for off reservation rights under similar reservations.","start":2771.98,"stop":2788.405,"duration":16.43},{"text":"Not all of them have been absolute jurisdiction and control although the limits referred to in the Sandoval case was absolute jurisdiction and control, the very words we have here.","start":2788.405,"stop":2800.729,"duration":12.32},{"text":"The Winans case I think is the -- probably the outstanding example of what I'm talking about.","start":2800.729,"stop":2810.073,"duration":9.34},{"text":"There, they met the equal footing doctrine squarely and they met Shively against Bowlby which is also relied upon by the State Supreme Court which held that Tideland that passed the State as part of its being admitted on an equal footing.","start":2810.073,"stop":2826.663,"duration":16.59},{"text":"The (Inaudible) Brothers case, Dick case, Ex Parte Webb and Sandoval, but I have mentioned two or three times are further examples of reservations and Statehood Acts like this, of rights to the Indians or a power over the Indians, some of them such as Ex Parte Webb is reserving a power over the Indians to prohibit the introduction of liquor, they had been repeatedly sustained by this Court and there is simply nothing to the equal footing point.","start":2826.663,"stop":2857.674,"duration":31.01},{"text":"Now, I think the other ground given that this conflicts with the State's police power.","start":2857.674,"stop":2864.119,"duration":6.45},{"text":"Federal statute must give way before the police power has been plainly ruled on by this Court.","start":2864.119,"stop":2869.302,"duration":5.18},{"text":"If the Federal Government has power, reservation of exclusive jurisdiction and control then under the Supremacy Clause that overrides the state statute and I take it therefore that there is no basis or saying that it's in valid.","start":2869.302,"stop":2887.675,"duration":18.37},{"text":"They made not a point.","start":2887.675,"stop":2888.482,"duration":0.81},{"text":"They say, “Well, it's any factor.”","start":2888.482,"stop":2890.699,"duration":2.22},{"text":"They say that there's a distinction between in the Statehood Act, between the rights of Indians at -- the property including fishing rights of Indians and fishing itself.","start":2890.699,"stop":2906.869,"duration":16.17},{"text":"Maybe the Federal Government has power to regulate fishing rights, but here what these people are doing is fishing and let Alaska have control over there.","start":2906.869,"stop":2915.872,"duration":9},{"text":"It's a somatic distinction which frankly I cannot follow and I believe that Congress did not commit a mere meaningless Act in what it did.","start":2915.872,"stop":2924.985,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you sit down, I'd like to ask you this question.","start":2924.985,"stop":2927.771,"duration":2.79},{"text":"There were no treaties between and these communities, were they?","start":2927.771,"stop":2932.447,"duration":4.68}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"None whatever, there never been treaties with Alaskan Indians.","start":2932.447,"stop":2936.193,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And therefore I would like to ask you, what is the transcending authority, constitutional authority of the United States in relation to have a regular Indians in Alaska (Inaudible)?","start":2936.193,"stop":2951.757,"duration":15.56}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"It has been set forth many times.","start":2951.757,"stop":2954.691,"duration":2.93},{"text":"The greatest length or list of the source of power was given in the Kagama case by this Court, K-A-G-A-M-A.","start":2954.691,"stop":2966.753,"duration":12.06},{"text":"It's also adverted to in the Sandoval case to which I have referred a number of times, but fundamental -- the main basis in the Commerce Clause because this Commerce not just between the States and with foreign nations but with the Indian tribes and here, you've got an important element of Commerce.","start":2966.753,"stop":2985.721,"duration":18.97},{"text":"That alone would support it as this Court has said but there are other sources of power to particularly the power in international affairs to deal with the continent people.","start":2985.721,"stop":3011.474,"duration":25.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis.","start":3011.474,"stop":3012.732,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3012.732,"stop":3015.971,"duration":3.24},{"text":"I appear here on behalf of the Federal Government in support of the position of the appellants that the State of Alaska has no power to impose its fish trap regulations upon these appellants, but rather that the continued absolute jurisdiction and control over these matters still resides within the control of Federal Government acting through the Secretary of the Interior.","start":3015.971,"stop":3040.997,"duration":25.03},{"text":"Perhaps before I begin my affirmative argument in support of the appellant's position, it might be helpful if I try to -- in my answer to a several of the particular questions which had been raised by members of the Court.","start":3040.997,"stop":3056.291,"duration":15.29},{"text":"First, with relation to Section 6 (e) which is -- and the Westland proviso, the Statehood Act itself provided that for -- that fisheries and wildlife resources should not be transferred to the State, but continue on the federal control where they've been since Alaska become a territory until the Secretary of the Interior was satisfied that Alaska has provided appropriate fishing and wildlife resource legislation in the broad national interest and then it provided for certification and in -- if he was so satisfied and then the -- the resources and the enforcement machinery will be turnover to Alaska.","start":3056.291,"stop":3095.5,"duration":39.21},{"text":"Now, the Secretary did make the certification on April 1959, shortly after Alaska became a state, Alaska became a state on January 3, 1959.","start":3095.5,"stop":3105.437,"duration":9.94},{"text":"But I think it's important Mr. Justice Brennan to point out that at the time the Secretary made that certification, two things were in existence.","start":3105.437,"stop":3112.782,"duration":7.35},{"text":"One, he'd already proposed to continue his fishing regulations with relation to these appellants.","start":3112.782,"stop":3118.406,"duration":5.62},{"text":"He had issued a proposed regulation permitting these appellants to continue and two, the Alaska statute which was then in effect, the Alaska statute prohibiting fish traps said nothing in this statute shall be construed to violate Section 4 of the Statehood Act which --","start":3118.406,"stop":3135.995,"duration":17.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That was -- that was the set of facts Mr. Davis, before me on the application (Voice Overlap)","start":3135.995,"stop":3140.11,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3140.11,"stop":3141.629,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the certification had not yet become effective as I recall?","start":3141.629,"stop":3144.696,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The certification did not become effective until January 1, 1960.","start":3144.696,"stop":3148.753,"duration":4.06},{"text":"But what I just want to point out is that the Secretary did not file the certification, assumed that the Alaska fish traps statutes applied to these appellant Indians because he himself had continued to regulate them and the statute, the Alaska statute which was then in effect contained a section which said, “Nothing in this statute shall contravene anything in Section 4 of the Statehood Act.”","start":3148.753,"stop":3170.248,"duration":21.49},{"text":"Now, we're precluded from arguing on the basis of the Alaska statute because the Alaska Supreme Court has since that the time construed it to apply to these appellants' fish traps.","start":3170.248,"stop":3179.475,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Now, as to what the power of the Secretary would be as to these Indians or other Indians in the future, I want to make it clear that in point of view of the Federal Government, he does not have power at large.","start":3179.475,"stop":3192.862,"duration":13.39},{"text":"Section 4 refers to fishing rights held at the time of Statehood, held at the time of Statehood.","start":3192.862,"stop":3200.293,"duration":7.43},{"text":"And as we construe Section 4, if I may intervene to go back just a minute, Section 6 (e) was in the Statehood Act.","start":3200.293,"stop":3210.829,"duration":10.54},{"text":"That's the transfer of jurisdiction over wildlife and fishing to the State, but Section 4 was also on the Statehood Act, the very same Act provided for reservation of Indian fishing rights and so that Section 4 read in pairing material with Section 6 (e) reserved fishing rights whatever that maybe.","start":3210.829,"stop":3230.097,"duration":19.27}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And whatever that maybe, as I read the legislative history was left for legislative -- future legislative and/or judicial determination, is that right?","start":3230.097,"stop":3239.958,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right Mr. Justice Douglas, with this exception that they did not want to make any change.","start":3239.958,"stop":3244.708,"duration":4.75},{"text":"They wanted to maintain the status quo.","start":3244.708,"stop":3246.961,"duration":2.25},{"text":"They very clearly did not want to grant any rights to Indians or take away weight.","start":3246.961,"stop":3251.646,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I've been able to find anything that describes with clarity with which you plead what these fishing rights were.","start":3251.646,"stop":3258.995,"duration":7.35}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I will try in a moment to reach that.","start":3258.995,"stop":3261.134,"duration":2.14},{"text":"I was just trying to -- to answer some of the specific questions and the burden of my argument --","start":3261.134,"stop":3265.229,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Keep coming back in legislative history to the phrase or such as a legislature or Congress or the courts show (Voice Overlap)","start":3265.229,"stop":3273.558,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3273.558,"stop":3274.181,"duration":0.62},{"text":"I will try to deal with that Mr. Justice Douglas but before I do, I just wanted to answer the -- the question as to what the power of the Secretary was in our view with relation to these Indians or other Indians.","start":3274.181,"stop":3285.473,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But then as I understand Mr. Davis, so far as the Metlakatla Indians are concerned their fishing trap rights or rather rights are limited to the reservations?","start":3285.473,"stop":3300.728,"duration":15.26}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":3300.728,"stop":3300.98,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"As to the -- the --","start":3300.98,"stop":3302.457,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Kake and Angoon.","start":3302.457,"stop":3303.242,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Kake, as to their ancient lands, whatever those ancient lands might be.","start":3303.242,"stop":3307.436,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"While, I think it's -- it's even more precise than that Mr. because the Sec -- at the time of Statehood, the Secretary had said that there were 21 fish traps sites as a whole for all three groups, 21.","start":3307.436,"stop":3319.316,"duration":11.88},{"text":"He only authorized 11 traps, but there were 21 sites as a whole, all within the same general area.","start":3319.316,"stop":3325.716,"duration":6.4},{"text":"In our view, he can extend to the 21 sites, that is he can increase the number of fish traps from 11 to 21, which were at that time in existence for these groups.","start":3325.716,"stop":3341.191,"duration":15.47},{"text":"He can decrease it.","start":3341.191,"stop":3342.447,"duration":1.26},{"text":"He cannot go beyond that --","start":3342.447,"stop":3347.383,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number.","start":3347.383,"stop":3348,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Number --","start":3348,"stop":3348.721,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And cannot go beyond those territorial limits.","start":3348.721,"stop":3351.591,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3351.591,"stop":3352.252,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3352.252,"stop":3352.474,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":3352.474,"stop":3353.265,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say he can go beyond the number within the territorial limits.","start":3353.265,"stop":3358.876,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's right.","start":3358.876,"stop":3359.58,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, now just go beyond that -- beyond the 21 fixed sites.","start":3359.58,"stop":3363.822,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3363.822,"stop":3364.065,"duration":0.24},{"text":"He cannot go beyond the 21.","start":3364.065,"stop":3365.6,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that there are 21 fixed sites.","start":3365.6,"stop":3368.227,"duration":2.63},{"text":"That's the point.","start":3368.227,"stop":3368.773,"duration":0.55},{"text":"He can't move --","start":3368.773,"stop":3369.746,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3369.746,"stop":3370.437,"duration":0.69},{"text":"Yes sir, yes.","start":3370.437,"stop":3371.088,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the 21, helter-skelter.","start":3371.088,"stop":3373.011,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- now, I should make it clear to the Court that this is the view of Department of Justice, the Department of the Interior thinks he can't go beyond the 11 which were in actual existence at the moment of Statehood.","start":3373.011,"stop":3383.537,"duration":10.53},{"text":"Well, he hasn't tried to go beyond the 11 and I don't think the Court has to decide that issue because --","start":3383.537,"stop":3389.922,"duration":6.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But whether it's 11 or 21, in any event, they are fixed site?","start":3389.922,"stop":3393.722,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":3393.722,"stop":3394.379,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which pinpoint territorially whether they (Voice Overlap)","start":3394.379,"stop":3396.464,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right and he cannot move them around.","start":3396.464,"stop":3398.409,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that include also the question I put to Mr. Cragun, a change in the method even at those fixed sites electronic as Justice Douglas (Inaudible) changed, that's not this case.","start":3398.409,"stop":3410.133,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a difficult question Mr. Justice.","start":3410.133,"stop":3413.531,"duration":3.4},{"text":"I would be inclined to think that he could not make a change and at the time of Statehood, they were fish traps and that was -- that was the fishing right they had, but -- but I don't wish to give a -- a definitive answer.","start":3413.531,"stop":3424.592,"duration":11.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) that question has not stirred here.","start":3424.592,"stop":3426.797,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right Mr. Justice.","start":3426.797,"stop":3431.092,"duration":4.3},{"text":"Now, the -- as Mr. Schifter pointed out yesterday, there's a very great difference between the opinion of the Supreme Court of Alaska and the position taken by the State in its brief which was filed a week ago.","start":3431.092,"stop":3445.308,"duration":14.22},{"text":"If I may, at the outset, I'd like to be with the opinion of the Supreme Court of Alaska, which the Attorney General of the State has not thought it necessary to support in his brief because I would like to make it clear to the Court that in our view, the propositions -- the legal propositions announced by the Supreme of Alaska are wrong, and -- and should be repudiated by this Court because they have a -- well radiation beyond this particular case with relation to the Indians of Alaska.","start":3445.308,"stop":3477.897,"duration":32.59},{"text":"I do not intend unless the Court should wish me to stand a great deal of time on -- on -- on these issues because the State does not seek to support them, but I would like to state our position on it.","start":3477.897,"stop":3487.278,"duration":9.38},{"text":"And the first position is the Supreme Court of Alaska said that the Indian power of Congress does not extend to Alaska.","start":3487.278,"stop":3494.279,"duration":7},{"text":"It may extend to the rest of the continental United States but it does not extend to Alaska.","start":3494.279,"stop":3498.841,"duration":4.56},{"text":"That is refuted by any -- by three or four decisions of this Court which the Alaska Pacific Fisheries case and (Inaudible) case and Hynes against Grimes Packing and decisions in the lower courts which have held that -- that the Indian power of Congress does extend to Alaska.","start":3498.841,"stop":3515.596,"duration":16.76},{"text":"It's -- it's refuted by the consistent legislative Congress from the time it began rarely to legislate for Alaska in 1884 and the Organic Act of 1884 in which made special provision for -- for Alaska Indians.","start":3515.596,"stop":3529.61,"duration":14.01},{"text":"It's refuted by the Metlakatla legislation by the extension of the Wheeler-Howard Act, the Indian Reorganization Act, one of the great charters of Indian progress in this country to Alaska.","start":3529.61,"stop":3540.505,"duration":10.89},{"text":"It's -- it's even refuted by the provisions of the 19 -- 1953 statue that Mr. Justice Frankfurter was asking about, extending criminal jurisdiction to Alaska but excluding fishing plan.","start":3540.505,"stop":3551.577,"duration":11.07},{"text":"So I think there's really nothing to that point.","start":3551.577,"stop":3553.937,"duration":2.36},{"text":"And the second point, the Supreme Court of Alaska makes or suggests is that equal footing prevents a reservation by the Federal Government as we think it tried to do in Section 4 of the Statehood Act, of rights with relation to Indians and Alaska and again the decisions of this Court as Mr. Cragun has indicated consistently hold otherwise.","start":3553.937,"stop":3575.269,"duration":21.33},{"text":"What the Court has held is that in a Statehood Act, the Federal Government can reserve rights which it would have the power to exercise under the regular granted provisions of the constitution.","start":3575.269,"stop":3587.367,"duration":12.1},{"text":"In Coyle against Oklahoma, the case which said Oklahoma couldn't -- could not be prevented from moving its capital from Guthrie to Oklahoma by prohibition in the Oklahoma City by prohibition in Statehood Act, the Court three times when out of its way to indicate that with respect to those matters, particularly Indian matters which the Federal Government have granted powers on the Commerce Clause, of course it could reserve powers.","start":3587.367,"stop":3613.802,"duration":26.43},{"text":"And -- and this was repeated in the Sandoval and other cases.","start":3613.802,"stop":3617.44,"duration":3.64},{"text":"And I think almost every Statehood Act since the 1880's or 1870's has contained a reservation with relation to Indians except Hawaii which has no Indians and they've contained a reservation with relation to Hawaiian natives in that statute.","start":3617.44,"stop":3633.654,"duration":16.21},{"text":"And so that's the second point of the Supreme Court of Alaska which I think it's just wrong if may say so with respect to the Court.","start":3633.654,"stop":3641.965,"duration":8.31},{"text":"Then the Supreme Court of Alaska seem to think that the reservation in Section 4 which reserves to the absolute jurisdiction and control of the Federal Government land and property held by for the Indians including fishing rights, reserve that -- that that failed because the -- there wasn't a meeting of their minds between the State of Alaska and Congress.","start":3641.965,"stop":3668.041,"duration":26.08},{"text":"Now, we spell at the answer to that in our -- in our brief and I think for the short answer that I may say is that the Alaska Statehood Act provided that the people of Alaska would have to take a vote on the entire statement under -- under disclaimer provision, the one we have here and if they adopted it, as they did, the Constitution of Alaska shall be deemed to be amended in pursuance thereto.","start":3668.041,"stop":3694.419,"duration":26.38},{"text":"So, I think there's nothing to that point.","start":3694.419,"stop":3697.69,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Then the last point made by the -- by the Supreme Court of Alaska in this respect is that the Omnibus Act Amendments, that's the Amendment which -- which said that the absolute jurisdiction and control of the United States didn't continue for federally owned lands generally and only for lands which were held by for the natives, but that was invalid because it was passed after Statehood.","start":3697.69,"stop":3722.696,"duration":25.01},{"text":"The State does not rest on that because I think it would not want that the grant of jurisdiction that it received under that Act over federal lands generally to be invalidated, but I think that legally speaking, the Supreme Court of Alaska was erroneous there to.","start":3722.696,"stop":3739.441,"duration":16.74},{"text":"Because first, it's very clear from the legislative history that Congress thought it was correcting an error.","start":3739.441,"stop":3744.566,"duration":5.13},{"text":"It says in the -- in the reports, we intended to limit this after jurisdiction and control only to native, to Indian lands and we inadvertently did more and of course there's a tremendous area of Alaska which -- in Alaska would be deprived of the police power if the words were taken literally, and that's why they amended it.","start":3744.566,"stop":3763.723,"duration":19.16},{"text":"I should say -- I think there were questions asked about public lands in Alaska.","start":3763.723,"stop":3769.138,"duration":5.41},{"text":"The Statehood Act does contain provisions for setting aside of defense area of Alaska in which the Federal Government would have exclusive provision -- exclusive authority completely but that's in a separate section with its own powers and authority.","start":3769.138,"stop":3784.056,"duration":14.92},{"text":"As to the other public lands and -- and this defense area was limited geographically to a certain section of Alaska, as to the others, Commerce has made it clear that the normal civil and clinical jurisdiction extends to the federal lands.","start":3784.056,"stop":3798.419,"duration":14.36},{"text":"Now, I think I would like to turn to what I consider in which I think the State considers now, the really basic issue in this case which is -- what is meant by the term fishing rights in Section 4?","start":3798.419,"stop":3812.032,"duration":13.61},{"text":"I wish to make it clear on behalf of the Federal Government that fishing rights that I espoused here, we do not think of vested or compensable as against the Federal Government.","start":3812.032,"stop":3823.14,"duration":11.11},{"text":"That is we don't think the Court has to decide this issue in this case at all.","start":3823.14,"stop":3827.474,"duration":4.33},{"text":"I just wish to make it clear so that there be no misapprehension as to position of the Federal Government.","start":3827.474,"stop":3832.465,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Your estoppel --","start":3832.465,"stop":3834.283,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, sometimes we found that -- that -- it must be make it clear counsel thinks that (Voice Overlap) pardon me?","start":3834.283,"stop":3839.742,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You have hardship.","start":3839.742,"stop":3840.736,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon me?","start":3840.736,"stop":3841.157,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You expect hardship.","start":3841.157,"stop":3842.159,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3842.159,"stop":3842.935,"duration":0.78},{"text":"I just want to make it clear that -- that we think that these are fishing rights which are protected us against the State of Alaska and are protected in which the Secretary of the Interior can control and regulate.","start":3842.935,"stop":3854.224,"duration":11.29},{"text":"They're contestable in the sense that if the Secretary should refuse to continue them or Congress should say that Secretary stop fishing traps in Alaska or if this Court should hold against us and say that Alaska can regulate that they would be no suit in the Court of Claim saying that, “By Section 4 we gave up these rights.”","start":3854.224,"stop":3872.993,"duration":18.77},{"text":"But with that disclaimer which I think the Court may not reach at all in this case.","start":3872.993,"stop":3880.203,"duration":7.21},{"text":"We do think that -- that the fishing rights which were protected, which are protected by Section 4 are involved in this particular case.","start":3880.203,"stop":3889.362,"duration":9.16},{"text":"What is our view of what a fishing right within the meaning of Section 4?","start":3889.362,"stop":3893.537,"duration":4.17},{"text":"Our feeling is that if say a permission, a license, a privilege, a right on actual fishing by or in behalf of Indians as Indians under the aegis of the Federal Government.","start":3893.537,"stop":3908.425,"duration":14.89},{"text":"Now, those are general words and I will try to fill them out with relation to the particular groups here.","start":3908.425,"stop":3915.835,"duration":7.41},{"text":"As Mr. Schifter has pointed out, from 1891, the Metlakatla's have been subject to the supervision and jurisdiction of the Secretary of the Interior.","start":3915.835,"stop":3925.264,"duration":9.43},{"text":"Both Congress and the President have made very clear that they have fishing rights in -- in their reserve.","start":3925.264,"stop":3931.459,"duration":6.19},{"text":"They are spelled out in the President's executive order.","start":3931.459,"stop":3936.158,"duration":4.7},{"text":"It's made very clear in the decision of this Court in the Alaska Pacific Fisheries case.","start":3936.158,"stop":3940.895,"duration":4.74},{"text":"It's assumed and confirmed by Congress in the various statutes.","start":3940.895,"stop":3946.483,"duration":5.59},{"text":"So these fishing rights come under a federal statute.","start":3946.483,"stop":3951.099,"duration":4.62},{"text":"They come under complex of federal statutes with relation to Metlakatla.","start":3951.099,"stop":3955.646,"duration":4.55},{"text":"They are not vested we think and the Metlakatla's do not claim they're vested, but they are fishing rights under a federal statute, which were in existence at the time of Statehood.","start":3955.646,"stop":3966.729,"duration":11.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand why you're saying not vested.","start":3966.729,"stop":3970.195,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"What I mean by not vested is that if the Congress repealed the statutes, they could not sue the United States.","start":3970.195,"stop":3975.67,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) vested against Alaska?","start":3975.67,"stop":3976.901,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"They are not vested as against United States.","start":3976.901,"stop":3978.831,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":3978.831,"stop":3979.847,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Congress might be able to change it but presently, they do have some fixed vessel rights, wouldn't they?","start":3979.847,"stop":3986.598,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"As against Alaska, as against private parties not as against the United States.","start":3986.598,"stop":3991.098,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Solicitor, vested on not against the United States, it's part of the larger problem of Indian rights against him (Voice Overlap)","start":3991.098,"stop":3996.401,"duration":5.3}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that's right.","start":3996.401,"stop":3997.247,"duration":0.85},{"text":"That's right, that's right.","start":3997.247,"stop":3998.246,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true of Metlakatla.","start":3998.246,"stop":3999.848,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":3999.848,"stop":4000.337,"duration":0.49},{"text":"Now, to go on to the Kake and Angoon, which are in a little different situation but we think basically not dissimilar Mr. Justice Whittaker because the situation in those cases is this.","start":4000.337,"stop":4013.801,"duration":13.46},{"text":"Both of those Indian communities which existed as any to communities for a long time were charted under the Wheeler-Howard Act, the Indian Reorganization Act.","start":4013.801,"stop":4024.733,"duration":10.93},{"text":"And that we think is a terribly significant factor because the Wheeler-Howard Act provided, and I'd like -- if I could to give the tone of the Act just to read to the Court its -- its title because it's very important.","start":4024.733,"stop":4039.206,"duration":14.47},{"text":"The Wheeler-Howard Act was an Act to conserve and develop Indian lands and resources, to extend to Indians the right to form business in other organizations, to establish a credit system for Indians, to grant Indian certain rights of Home Rule provide for vocational education for Indians and this was extended to Alaska.","start":4039.206,"stop":4060.475,"duration":21.27},{"text":"The purpose of the Act was to encourage these Indian communities to develop businesses so they could become self-sufficient and self-sustaining and have a viable community.","start":4060.475,"stop":4069.051,"duration":8.58},{"text":"That was very purpose.","start":4069.051,"stop":4070.764,"duration":1.71},{"text":"Under it -- under it the Secretary of the Interior loaned money to Kake and Angoon.","start":4070.764,"stop":4076.959,"duration":6.19},{"text":"He purchased on their behalf the Indian canaries which they operated.","start":4076.959,"stop":4081.191,"duration":4.23},{"text":"Those Indian canaries in the case of Kake and Angoon are held by the United States in trust for the Indian groups.","start":4081.191,"stop":4087.519,"duration":6.33},{"text":"He supervises their finances.","start":4087.519,"stop":4091.438,"duration":3.92},{"text":"It's all part of the -- of the purpose of the Wheeler-Howard Act to encourage these Indian communities to become viable communities.","start":4091.438,"stop":4100.479,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that done to the Metlakatla also?","start":4100.479,"stop":4102.756,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4102.756,"stop":4103.425,"duration":0.67},{"text":"But I mean the Kake and Angoon do not have the special statutes referring to them particularly by name which exist in Metlakatla.","start":4103.425,"stop":4112.528,"duration":9.1},{"text":"Metlakatla has statutes which refer to them by name.","start":4112.528,"stop":4115.621,"duration":3.09},{"text":"Kake and Angoon do not have statutes.","start":4115.621,"stop":4117.778,"duration":2.16},{"text":"I'm trying to point out that though Kake and Angoon do not have statutes which refer to them by name, they are basically in the same position that as general statutes which Congress passed and which Congress directed the Secretary of the Interior to use for Indian tribes in Alaska, he used for these two groups.","start":4117.778,"stop":4136.749,"duration":18.97}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"He could have --","start":4136.749,"stop":4138.368,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) right hand upon the fact that it was an Indian community or ban this specific grant to produce in proclamation?","start":4138.368,"stop":4147.425,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it depends upon the fact that they were exercising under federal statutes and under executive orders a fishing right at the time of Statehood.","start":4147.425,"stop":4158.799,"duration":11.37},{"text":"And I think that Kake and Angoon were exercising a fishing right under the Wheeler-Howard Act and under the -- the designation by the Secretary of the Interior that they could use fish traps.","start":4158.799,"stop":4169.823,"duration":11.02},{"text":"He meant --","start":4169.823,"stop":4171.082,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The point of your argument is you're trying to fix that established what interest they enjoyed as of the date of Statehood.","start":4171.082,"stop":4179.648,"duration":8.57}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And further Mr. Justice Frankfurter, I'm trying to share that this was pursuant to statute of Congress and not something at large in the air.","start":4179.648,"stop":4187.053,"duration":7.4},{"text":"That was a pursuant to statute of Congress and that a fishing --","start":4187.053,"stop":4189.383,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But at large, you might not be able catch it. [Laughter]","start":4189.383,"stop":4192.759,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"And that if where pursuant to statute or executive order or long used and occupation recognized by Congress, that's the kind of fishing right which Congress intended to protect under Section 4.","start":4192.759,"stop":4206.334,"duration":13.57}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"The Secretary then can abolish all these traps for next season if he wanted to do.","start":4206.334,"stop":4210.195,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"In the view of the Department of Justice, I have to make it clear that the Interior Department thinks that he is stuck with the 11 traps and that he cannot himself abolish them.","start":4210.195,"stop":4218.447,"duration":8.25},{"text":"But in the view of Department of Justice, he can abolish that he has the right in our view.","start":4218.447,"stop":4225.41,"duration":6.96},{"text":"The Interior Department as indicated in our brief thinks that he has -- he cannot neither nor decrease the 11 traps which were in existence at the moment of Statehood.","start":4225.41,"stop":4234.716,"duration":9.31}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the -- the view of the Interior department?","start":4234.716,"stop":4236.966,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the view of the Interior department.","start":4236.966,"stop":4238.351,"duration":1.38},{"text":"We do not take that view.","start":4238.351,"stop":4240.959,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether he could not (Inaudible) premises right with reference to have adopted (Inaudible)","start":4240.959,"stop":4247.54,"duration":6.58}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh yes, there's no doubt.","start":4247.54,"stop":4248.96,"duration":1.42},{"text":"And interior has no doubt that Congress could.","start":4248.96,"stop":4251.421,"duration":2.46},{"text":"I mean they don't have any examine about that.","start":4251.421,"stop":4256.457,"duration":5.04},{"text":"Now, I will confess that there isn't very much in the legislative history which bears directly of the meaning of the term fishing rights that is specifically.","start":4256.457,"stop":4267.942,"duration":11.48},{"text":"There is this background that Congress was very well aware of how important fishing rights was to these and other Indians in Alaska, that Congress was very much aware of that.","start":4267.942,"stop":4277.748,"duration":9.81},{"text":"Congress was also aware of the -- of the great antipodally of the people of Alaska to fish traps generally.","start":4277.748,"stop":4284.97,"duration":7.22},{"text":"It was aware of and even though it was of that, it did pass Section 4.","start":4284.97,"stop":4289.807,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course there are some -- the fishing resources as I gather in Alaska had been so seriously depleted that some had even able talked about stopping all fishing.","start":4289.807,"stop":4299.078,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that is true.","start":4299.078,"stop":4300.218,"duration":1.14},{"text":"But there is -- there is--","start":4300.218,"stop":4301.05,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"For year or two.","start":4301.05,"stop":4301.945,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4301.945,"stop":4302.578,"duration":0.63},{"text":"As you know Mr. Justice, though the people of Alaska, as indicated by Senator Gruening in -- on the floor Congress and (Inaudible) think that fish traps are anti-conservation devices, the Interior department fish and wildlife people do not think so.","start":4302.578,"stop":4318.233,"duration":15.65},{"text":"They think that a fish trap appropriately regulated can be just as a --","start":4318.233,"stop":4324.109,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose that's whether you applied fisherman or – [Laughter]","start":4324.109,"stop":4328.935,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Anyway, in this particular case, there was no evidence on this issue -- on this issue.","start":4328.935,"stop":4332.823,"duration":3.89},{"text":"And I -- and Congress was fully aware of the -- of the conservation claims of people of Alaska.","start":4332.823,"stop":4337.944,"duration":5.12},{"text":"They were, there's -- I think two or three surveys of this and Congress never decided the issue that is it never found that fish traps were --","start":4337.944,"stop":4346.181,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think you can never catch one of those salmons of that size on the fly?","start":4346.181,"stop":4350.665,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not that kind of sportsman Mr. Justice Brennan. [Laughter]","start":4350.665,"stop":4353.427,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis -- Mr. Davis, in fishing rights broadly speaking, the opportunity to catch fish, I'm not offering this for technical.","start":4353.427,"stop":4363.931,"duration":10.5},{"text":"Let's say an indication then whether traps other deemed at the Interior's instruments (Inaudible) for instance, having conservation instrument are means for enabling (Inaudible) fish would -- would be raised on this -- on the basis of ultra vires of the Secretary would implement that authority that he has.","start":4363.931,"stop":4391.097,"duration":27.17}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right!","start":4391.097,"stop":4392.044,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that could be done either if the Court take judicial notice that traps are destructive implements all by proof?","start":4392.044,"stop":4401.116,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4401.116,"stop":4402.057,"duration":0.94},{"text":"And I think the Court cannot take judicial notice of it and there has been no proof of that and this was a matter that Congress considered, but (Voice Overlap)","start":4402.057,"stop":4413.761,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) You are syaing Congress considered this?","start":4413.761,"stop":4416.325,"duration":2.56}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"In a sense no, that Congress has been aware of the claim of the people of Alaska that fish traps are anti-conservation devices, and knowing that claim nevertheless passed this statute.","start":4416.325,"stop":4427.368,"duration":11.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Broad statue -- unlimiting statute.","start":4427.368,"stop":4429.346,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right sir.","start":4429.346,"stop":4430.367,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Leaving his conduct subject to attack in a way which authorized conduct by executive (Voice Overlap)","start":4430.367,"stop":4435.519,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4435.519,"stop":4436.374,"duration":0.85},{"text":"And I would think that Mr. Justice to go one step further that even if the Secretary had no power to allow fish traps one reason or another, that would not give authority to the State of Alaska to enforced its criminal statutes.","start":4436.374,"stop":4448.275,"duration":11.9},{"text":"You would have to sue the Secretary in the usual way and have to set aside his regulations.","start":4448.275,"stop":4453.29,"duration":5.02},{"text":"The State of Alaska would not have power to enforce its criminal statutes and that's what this case is about where --","start":4453.29,"stop":4458.753,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you that -- am I going to refer from that, that although there is no regulation by the Secretary of the Interior, Alaska would be without power evoked by under its police power to be with the proper -- with a problem like this?","start":4458.753,"stop":4475.42,"duration":16.67}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I would say that.","start":4475.42,"stop":4476.34,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You have to say that.","start":4476.34,"stop":4477.146,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that.","start":4477.146,"stop":4478.362,"duration":1.22},{"text":"I would say that -- the Secretary did have -- of course had a regulation from the very beginning.","start":4478.362,"stop":4483.789,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But in the absence of it and his appeal is free until the -- either Congress or Secretary acts.","start":4483.789,"stop":4489.456,"duration":5.67}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that.","start":4489.456,"stop":4490.194,"duration":0.74},{"text":"And I would point out Mr. Chief Justice Frankfurter (Voice Overlap)","start":4490.194,"stop":4491.817,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or this Court.","start":4491.817,"stop":4492.996,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Or this Court, always this Court. [Laughter]","start":4492.996,"stop":4498.447,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, does that mean this too that if the Secretary now may change his mind and not authorize use of any these traps, but Indians went ahead nevertheless and used it and any sanctions would have to be imposed under some federal law could not in any event permit Alaska to impose its criminal law.","start":4498.447,"stop":4517.361,"duration":18.91}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I'm not sure of that Mr. Justice for this reason that in his present regulations the Secretary in many other respects adapts the Alaska regulations that isn't relation to under things.","start":4517.361,"stop":4527.695,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But it has the provisions of the White Act too, aren't they?","start":4527.695,"stop":4529.484,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's right.","start":4529.484,"stop":4530.14,"duration":0.66},{"text":"I think the White Act provisions would apply and that that federal sections would -- would also apply.","start":4530.14,"stop":4535.188,"duration":5.05},{"text":"I'm not certain with the Secretary by adoption of the Alaska game laws or fish laws couldn't also make those applicable.","start":4535.188,"stop":4544.576,"duration":9.39},{"text":"In the -- as I mentioned before, there is nothing that I can point you, nothing very substantial that can I can point to, defining what the term fishing rights is in Section 4, but there are some indications, in addition to the general history of the background of this case.","start":4544.576,"stop":4562.615,"duration":18.04},{"text":"And one of the important things that I would like to stress is that Congress was aware of the importance of fishing to these Indian communities and others in Alaska. That was a very important factor that Congress was aware of generally.","start":4562.615,"stop":4575.062,"duration":12.45},{"text":"I think it was aware perhaps not specifically of -- of all the fishing by these Indian groups, certainly they aware of the Metlakatla of what they've been doing.","start":4575.062,"stop":4587.834,"duration":12.77},{"text":"They -- I think Congress was aware the fact that in the Felix Cohen's handbook in 1940 and his handbook on Indian law published by the Interior Department, under this chapter on Alaska natives, Alaska Indians under the rubric fishing and hunting rights, he discusses this along with others that is -- I think the Attorney General will indic -- will talk, say that the statute is limited to certain specific ceiling rights which Congress gave to the Indians that very -- and natives at various times.","start":4587.834,"stop":4619.083,"duration":31.25},{"text":"But what I want to point out is that in 1940, Felix Cohen in the authoritative handbook talking about fishing and hunting rights in Alaska for Alaska Indians, refer to these fish trap types of -- of commissions as part of the -- of the fishing rights of the Indians in Alaska as well as the others.","start":4619.083,"stop":4636.327,"duration":17.24},{"text":"Now, Governor Heintzleman of Alaska who was the Governor in 1954 at a hearing and this is not spelled out in our brief and that's why I take time to mention it, Governor Heintzleman in Alaska -- of Alaska talked about fishing rights before congressional committee as rights which were exercised for a long time under used on occupation by the Indians.","start":4636.327,"stop":4659.528,"duration":23.2},{"text":"He used the term fishing rights and it was quite clear from the context that he wasn't talking about a kind of right that you have to -- have a deed for or -- because he said there were no written papers indicating what fishing had been done by these Indians that you could find it out by -- by -- by evidence and proof.","start":4659.528,"stop":4682.951,"duration":23.42},{"text":"Now, all these we think really add up to the fact that when Congress used the word fishing rights, it used in the sense of the fishing which was done by Indians as Indians.","start":4682.951,"stop":4694.58,"duration":11.63},{"text":"Now of course, we don't claim that every Indian in Alaska is controlled by the Federal Government because most of the Indians in Alaska who do fishing are not under aegis of the Federal Governments.","start":4694.58,"stop":4706.718,"duration":12.14},{"text":"One of my colleagues pointed out to me if an Indian, who happens to be a drugstore (Inaudible) Alaska goes out fishing on Sunday, he of course is not under the control of the -- of the -- of the Interior Department.","start":4706.718,"stop":4718.085,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Or if an Indian happens to be a member of a fishing crew in some other part of Alaska but he is not fishing as Indian.","start":4718.085,"stop":4725.485,"duration":7.4},{"text":"An Indian who happens to be fishing in Alaska and the -- the Indians that we are concerned with and there, the only ones concerned with here are the Indians who has special treatment, special rights, special history under the Secretary of the Interior and under the legislation which covers as enacted for the Metlakatla, specifically for Kake and Angoon under the Wheeler-Howard Act as it was applied to Alaska couple of years later.","start":4725.485,"stop":4754.255,"duration":28.77}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"To exercise Indian fishing rights, you have to fish with the trap, I gather.","start":4754.255,"stop":4757.871,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"No, they are -- no, there are other Indian fishing rights and perhaps I should make that clear Mr. Justice Douglas.","start":4757.871,"stop":4763.427,"duration":5.56},{"text":"There are other fishing rights which are not involved in this case, which involved special use of special equipment on the Yukon and Kuskokwim rivers.","start":4763.427,"stop":4772.114,"duration":8.69},{"text":"They were seal fishing in the -- of the Pribilof and there -- in the Coquille reservation, they have a right to use bigger kind of gear, not a fish trap but (Voice Overlap)","start":4772.114,"stop":4780.911,"duration":8.8}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And any of them use dynamite or explosives to kill fish?","start":4780.911,"stop":4787.777,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think not.","start":4787.777,"stop":4789.643,"duration":1.87},{"text":"I mean, I think as I've indicated to Mr. Justice Frankfurter without taking a definitive position on it that the Secretary is limited to the kind of fishing that these people did.","start":4789.643,"stop":4799.914,"duration":10.27}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Some people say that's -- that's the way of getting rid of the fish?","start":4799.914,"stop":4802.247,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the Court could take judicial notice that was an anti-conservation.","start":4802.247,"stop":4806.597,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis.","start":4806.597,"stop":4808.029,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Go ahead, go ahead.","start":4808.029,"stop":4809.283,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"First time, I just asked two questions, has the Secretary of the Interior yet promulgated the authorization for --","start":4809.283,"stop":4818.324,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"The coming season.","start":4818.324,"stop":4819.004,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the coming season?","start":4819.004,"stop":4819.915,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"In 1960 Mr. Justice Brennan, he made a continuing regulations.","start":4819.915,"stop":4823.557,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":4823.557,"stop":4824.039,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Not -- he doesn't do it year-by-year anymore.","start":4824.039,"stop":4826.641,"duration":2.6},{"text":"He said that from here on out, they can fish at these 11 traps unless I, otherwise order, so that continues in effect.","start":4826.641,"stop":4833.519,"duration":6.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now my second question is, there's presently outstanding stay against the enforcement of the Alaskan statutes.","start":4833.519,"stop":4839.715,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4839.715,"stop":4840.43,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If the view with the appellants here prevails, what's your view of the remedies, should that stay made permanent or is a new declaration sufficient?","start":4840.43,"stop":4851.658,"duration":11.23}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, with due deference Mr. Justice, I think it would depend upon the representation of the Attorney General of Alaska.","start":4851.658,"stop":4859.162,"duration":7.5},{"text":"If he -- if Alaska will -- will abide by the decision of this Court as I'm sure it will, I would think that a declaratory judgment would be sufficient.","start":4859.162,"stop":4867.818,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- the request for release, I haven't check it again, but am I not right initially before the territorial court it was for injunctive relief?","start":4867.818,"stop":4876.968,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4876.968,"stop":4877.367,"duration":0.4},{"text":"But one -- at least, I checked one of the complaints.","start":4877.367,"stop":4879.491,"duration":2.12},{"text":"I did not have the time to check the others.","start":4879.491,"stop":4881.109,"duration":1.62},{"text":"One of complaints also asked for declaratory relief, maybe they do.","start":4881.109,"stop":4885.518,"duration":4.41},{"text":"In any case, I think that the Court could (Inaudible) an injunction against the Governor of the State if was it satisfied --","start":4885.518,"stop":4890.621,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we have affirmatively dissolved the outstanding stay.","start":4890.621,"stop":4893.428,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4893.428,"stop":4894.025,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But its customary not to grant injunction but take for granted which what you've said (Inaudible) or any others.","start":4894.025,"stop":4902.163,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's true.","start":4902.163,"stop":4902.988,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the difference here though and that's the reason I raised the question is that they have an outstanding stay against the Governor and the other officials of Alaska.","start":4902.988,"stop":4910.563,"duration":7.57},{"text":"We have affirmatively dissolved the outstanding stay.","start":4910.563,"stop":4912.52,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that if the Court should decide that they were the appellants' issue or declaratory judgment or order the lower court, I presumed that the State of Alaska would abide by that and the stay could be dissolved.","start":4912.52,"stop":4923.36,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Davis, I have one question.","start":4923.36,"stop":4925.448,"duration":2.09},{"text":"I understood you say to say to Mr. Justice Frankfurter that -- that even if it was decided not to have these traps that under circumstances would the State have any criminal jurisdiction over these fishing rights.","start":4925.448,"stop":4940.432,"duration":14.98},{"text":"Now, did you make any distinction between is because of their different situations between the Kake group and the other one?","start":4940.432,"stop":4951.331,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in a later answer to a similar question asked by another Justice, I qualified my answer to Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":4951.331,"stop":4959.07,"duration":7.74},{"text":"I said that I thought probably the Secretary, as he's done with respect to other rights, could provide that fishing rights, if he wished to abolish fish traps, he could say, “They shall be govern by the Alaska regulations.”","start":4959.07,"stop":4971.197,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh yes.","start":4971.197,"stop":4971.64,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"He has done in the (Voice Overlap)","start":4971.64,"stop":4972.867,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but in the absence of -- in the absence of some set regulations by the -- the Secretary, Alaska would have no jurisdiction, you say?","start":4972.867,"stop":4982.406,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think Alaska would have no jurisdiction but it would be a violation of the Federal White Act which provides for fishing by anybody in -- in contravention of the authority of the Secretary and if the Secretary withdrew the permission to fish -- to use these fish traps, it would be a violation of the White Act which has very severe penalties, I think severer than the State of Alaska.","start":4982.406,"stop":5003.475,"duration":21.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Just one other question.","start":5003.475,"stop":5005.722,"duration":2.25},{"text":"Did I understand counsel correctly that these fish traps amount to only about 2%?","start":5005.722,"stop":5012.989,"duration":7.27}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that is right.","start":5012.989,"stop":5014.613,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask one question before you sit down on your broad judicial (Inaudible).","start":5014.613,"stop":5020.745,"duration":6.13},{"text":"Assuming that there'd been no Wheeler-Howard Act, no action by the Interior with respect to Kakes and Angoons, would you still say -- would you still argue that their rights are protected on restriction for the State of Alaska?","start":5020.745,"stop":5040.371,"duration":19.63}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's a much harder question, Mr. Justice -- yes.","start":5040.371,"stop":5043.164,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the question I want to put to you?","start":5043.164,"stop":5044.641,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes I mean to answer, I mean to answer but I just want to indicate that in my view, it's a much harder question than the -- than the question you had me --","start":5044.641,"stop":5053.676,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"It becomes is harder in Alaska, because of what?","start":5053.676,"stop":5057.294,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Because of the fact that Congress has authorized the Secretary of the Interior to take action with respect to Kake and Angoon.","start":5057.294,"stop":5066.023,"duration":8.73},{"text":"That is in the Wheeler-Howard Act, Congress authorized him to foster a fishing -- an economy.","start":5066.023,"stop":5072.119,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Economy, no --","start":5072.119,"stop":5073.6,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"There's nothing --","start":5073.6,"stop":5074.445,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Nothing else.","start":5074.445,"stop":5074.541,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Oscar H. Davis","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but they didn't limit and he -- and they knew when -- certainly when they extended the Act to Alaska as they did in, and I think in 1936, that fishing was the major occupation which the Indians of Alaska would be able to get into, that was a major one.","start":5074.541,"stop":5089.18,"duration":14.64},{"text":"And so, the point I was trying to make Mr. Justice is that Congress did authorize him to take this action, providing canaries and to give money and so therefore that this is not something at large or something which even the Indians had been doing on their own.","start":5089.18,"stop":5104.719,"duration":15.54},{"text":"It's something authorized by Congress through its delegate, the Secretary.","start":5104.719,"stop":5108.552,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Now, to get back to your other question, if they had been no such that if these Indians had been just fishing with fish traps because the Secretary had allowed them along with all the others to fish with fish traps.","start":5108.552,"stop":5124.295,"duration":15.74},{"text":"I think that question would be whether they could long continued use an occupation of these particular sites, and if they could then I think that -- it was a fishing.","start":5124.295,"stop":5138.3,"duration":14.01},{"text":"I'm not certain that they could, but I mean if they could that I think would be fishing wholly apart from the authorization given by Congress through the Wheeler-Howard Act and the mechanism that it's -- thank you.","start":5138.3,"stop":5157.1,"duration":18.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Attorney General Moody.","start":5157.1,"stop":5158.144,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":5158.144,"stop":5162.609,"duration":4.47},{"text":"I move the -- that Mr. Avrum M. Gross of Alaska Bar be admitted pro hac vice.","start":5162.609,"stop":5168.756,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Motion will be granted, Mr. Gross?","start":5168.756,"stop":5171.924,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":5171.924,"stop":5176.99,"duration":5.07},{"text":"Mr. Justice Douglas pointed out early in the appellant's argument that the real question here is the interpretation of Section 4 of the Statehood Act and that Section 4 deprives Alaska of authority to regulate any Indian fishing rights.","start":5176.99,"stop":5194.005,"duration":17.02},{"text":"The real issue for this Court today is whether these appellants have fishing rights.","start":5194.005,"stop":5200.503,"duration":6.5},{"text":"Now, I don't believe this Court can decide that question without understanding what the regulatory scheme in Alaska was prior to the Statehood Act because all parties to this litigation are agreed that no rights were created in the Statehood Act, only rights were preserved.","start":5200.503,"stop":5219.557,"duration":19.05},{"text":"So the question is, what rights that Indians have prior to Statehood?","start":5219.557,"stop":5225.794,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Prior to 1924, regulation of the Alaska commercial fisheries was nearly non-existent although the power did exist in the Federal Government, but in 1924, Congress adopted the White Act.","start":5225.794,"stop":5239.474,"duration":13.68},{"text":"Now, the White Act perhaps remains a model for most state conservation programs today.","start":5239.474,"stop":5245.034,"duration":5.56},{"text":"Under that Act, the Secretary of the -- or Secretary of Commerce was subsequently transferred to the Secretary of the Interior was authorized to do several things.","start":5245.034,"stop":5255.041,"duration":10.01},{"text":"First of all, he was authorized to set up areas in Alaskan waters over any area in Alaska, over which the United States had jurisdiction through (Inaudible).","start":5255.041,"stop":5265.358,"duration":10.32},{"text":"It sets these areas of any waters of Alaska.","start":5265.358,"stop":5269.554,"duration":4.2},{"text":"Now, once he set up these areas, he could regulate the fishing within them.","start":5269.554,"stop":5274.172,"duration":4.62},{"text":"By that I mean that he could prescribe methods, means, times of fishing, seasons of fishing.","start":5274.172,"stop":5282.085,"duration":7.91},{"text":"Now, under the White Act, traps were allowed in Alaska, but there's been confusion raised here and I want to clear it up as quickly as possible.","start":5282.085,"stop":5292.171,"duration":10.09},{"text":"The appellants say that the Secretary of the Interior authorized them to use fish traps.","start":5292.171,"stop":5298.53,"duration":6.36},{"text":"Now that is simply not true.","start":5298.53,"stop":5301.05,"duration":2.52},{"text":"The Secretary of the Interior passed regulations which allowed anyone to use fish traps in a particular area, just as a particular any other type of equipment was authorized, nets, hook and line, anything.","start":5301.05,"stop":5315.045,"duration":13.99},{"text":"Traps were one of the types of equipment which were authorized to be used in a particular area of water.","start":5315.045,"stop":5320.845,"duration":5.8},{"text":"No particular community or person was ever authorized to use traps in Alaska.","start":5320.845,"stop":5327.083,"duration":6.24},{"text":"I think that's crucial because -- because all through this litigation, I think the impression has been given that the Secretary specifically designated this community to use traps, he did not.","start":5327.083,"stop":5339.112,"duration":12.03},{"text":"Areas were permitted and these individuals used traps in the area.","start":5339.112,"stop":5343.941,"duration":4.83},{"text":"Now, in fact --","start":5343.941,"stop":5345.019,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And anyone else could do.","start":5345.019,"stop":5346.834,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly correct Mr. Chief Justice.","start":5346.834,"stop":5348.919,"duration":2.09},{"text":"In fact, the records show that the very traps which were used by Kake and Angoon in this litigation were actually used by the P.E. Harris Company prior to 1948 and 1950 in the exact place where they are now being fished today, so anyone could use them.","start":5348.919,"stop":5370.538,"duration":21.62},{"text":"Now, when we talk about a native fishery in Alaska, it's actually a misnomer.","start":5370.538,"stop":5376.725,"duration":6.19},{"text":"In the commercial fisheries, there was no native fishery.","start":5376.725,"stop":5380.579,"duration":3.85},{"text":"The White Act made no distinctions between Alaskans, White Alaskans and Native Alaskans.","start":5380.579,"stop":5387.166,"duration":6.59},{"text":"This is quite reasonable if the Court will -- will think fishing is perhaps the only industry of Alaska.","start":5387.166,"stop":5392.519,"duration":5.35},{"text":"It certainly was back to turn of the century except for gold which is now extremely (Inaudible), but it was -- would have been impossible for people to come to the territory if they could not have fished on at least an equal basis with the natives that were there.","start":5392.519,"stop":5406.831,"duration":14.31},{"text":"Now in this litigation, the natives aren't only claiming the right to fish on an equal basis with White citizens in Alaska, they're claiming it on a privilege basis.","start":5406.831,"stop":5417.449,"duration":10.62},{"text":"But the White Act specifically said that no exclusive right of fishery shall be given to any group in Alaska.","start":5417.449,"stop":5425.537,"duration":8.09},{"text":"And this Court held in Hynes against Grimes that that specific clause applied to natives as well as anybody else that no rights could be given to natives under the White Act, absolutely none.","start":5425.537,"stop":5438.68,"duration":13.14}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you please sir?","start":5438.68,"stop":5441.239,"duration":2.56},{"text":"Did that provision of the White Act have any effect to cancel the earlier 1916 grant of exclusive fishing rights in these thousand foot -- 300,000 feet kilometer (Inaudible) and Metlakatla?","start":5441.239,"stop":5459.498,"duration":18.26}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I -- I will answer question but the fully discussion of this will be undertaken by Mr. Attorney General Moody.","start":5459.498,"stop":5466.16,"duration":6.66},{"text":"I wish to restrict myself mainly to Kake and Angoon, but I --","start":5466.16,"stop":5470.121,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"White Act was passed in 1924.","start":5470.121,"stop":5471.919,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":5471.919,"stop":5472.651,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"This grant to the Metlakatla since 1916?","start":5472.651,"stop":5475.252,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":5475.252,"stop":5476.513,"duration":1.26},{"text":"And I believe that the 1924 statement in the White Act which says that no citizen shall be denied the right to fish in Alaska, in any area where fishing is permitted by the Secretary of the Interior which is the last sentence of Section 1, may have will abolish the Metlakatla water reservation.","start":5476.513,"stop":5496.477,"duration":19.96},{"text":"I do not believe that it is necessary for the Court to hold that, to uphold Alaska's right to regulate the Metlakatla Reservation.","start":5496.477,"stop":5502.926,"duration":6.45},{"text":"But I -- and I do raise the point that Congress may well have meant to exclude the Metlakatla Reservation which had -- it had specifically set up, but you do raise the point which may well be valid and it may well indeed have abolished the water reservation, the specific declaration of equal rights to all fishermen in all waters of Alaska.","start":5502.926,"stop":5522.798,"duration":19.87}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there anything in the legislative history that shows what Congress intended in that regard?","start":5522.798,"stop":5528.673,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"This is debated between Justice Rutledge in Hynes against Grimes Packing Company, seem to view that the legislative -- the legislative history of the White Act did imply that Congress meant to exclude the White Act from applications to validly created Indian reservations.","start":5528.673,"stop":5547.161,"duration":18.49},{"text":"Now, the Court, the majority of the Court at that time disagreed.","start":5547.161,"stop":5554.061,"duration":6.9},{"text":"It did say and I think the Hynes case is extremely important here, because -- and perhaps I can answer your question best by reviewing the two holdings of the cases that have been pointed out here.","start":5554.061,"stop":5565.426,"duration":11.37},{"text":"Hynes said first of all that the Secretary for the President could reserve areas in Alaska for exclusive rights of fishing under the Wheeler-Howard Act, which was a later passed act than the White Act.","start":5565.426,"stop":5581.297,"duration":15.87},{"text":"It also said that the White Act could not be used to protect those areas and it also held that the White Act could apply to those areas.","start":5581.297,"stop":5590.184,"duration":8.89},{"text":"Now, a number of things I think are important.","start":5590.184,"stop":5592.281,"duration":2.1},{"text":"First of all, assuming that the area thereby set aside in the Hynes case became and exclusive right, it only became exclusive as to area.","start":5592.281,"stop":5604.411,"duration":12.13},{"text":"The Secretary was given full authority to regulate the means of fishing within the area.","start":5604.411,"stop":5611.997,"duration":7.59},{"text":"Now, so you have this distinction, the areas retained but the regulation is not.","start":5611.997,"stop":5618.171,"duration":6.17},{"text":"Now in Metlaktla, Metlakatla was established before the White Act was passed.","start":5618.171,"stop":5624.636,"duration":6.47},{"text":"Now, it may -- here, you get little interplay of two reservations created and an act between them.","start":5624.636,"stop":5632.934,"duration":8.3},{"text":"The Act may well have cut off the first and yet, it's superseded by the second, but in any case the regulation -- the regu -- the regulatory authority of the White Act extends to those reservations, the regulation of the fishing within the reservations.","start":5632.934,"stop":5648.512,"duration":15.58},{"text":"This, the Hynes case did hold that the area could be set aside, but the means of fishing within it was subject to general regulatory authority.","start":5648.512,"stop":5658.536,"duration":10.02},{"text":"There was never any right to be free of general regulatory authority in any reservation in Alaska.","start":5658.536,"stop":5666.615,"duration":8.08},{"text":"Now, this then was the status of fishing prior to the Statehood Act and the Statehood Act reserved for state control, all Indian fishing rights.","start":5666.615,"stop":5679.26,"duration":12.65},{"text":"Now first of all, I want to make absolutely clear the position of the Statehood.","start":5679.26,"stop":5683.845,"duration":4.59},{"text":"We will concede for argument that if Congress had wished to, it could have reserved the control of all Indian fishing to the Federal Government.","start":5683.845,"stop":5693.111,"duration":9.27},{"text":"The effect might well had been disastrous in Alaska, but it might well have done so, but Congress didn't.","start":5693.111,"stop":5700.595,"duration":7.48},{"text":"Congress only reserved Indian fishing rights.","start":5700.595,"stop":5704.337,"duration":3.74},{"text":"Those are the words of the statute.","start":5704.337,"stop":5706.143,"duration":1.81},{"text":"It could have used the fishing but it did not.","start":5706.143,"stop":5709.757,"duration":3.61},{"text":"So then the question becomes, looking back into Alaskan history by the -- by the test laid down by this Court as to what constitutes Indian rights, whether Indians really had rights in Alaska.","start":5709.757,"stop":5722.717,"duration":12.96},{"text":"Well, this Court has already heard from the appellants in this case, and I refer now to Kake and Angoon that there is no treaty between the Indians of Kake and Angoon and the Federal Government.","start":5722.717,"stop":5734.85,"duration":12.13},{"text":"It has also heard taken Angoon State that there is no reservation in Kake.","start":5734.85,"stop":5739.243,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask -- do I understand the concession goes this far, if in fact rights include the use of traps, Alaska now raises no constitutional --","start":5739.243,"stop":5752.237,"duration":12.99}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":5752.237,"stop":5752.544,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- section of the power of Congress who reserved the right to regulate the use of fish trap, is that it?","start":5752.544,"stop":5758.026,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":5758.026,"stop":5759.098,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That really we do in both cases that before us now based on the State's concession, only the question of what is meant -- the Congress means by rights.","start":5759.098,"stop":5768.939,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is absolutely correct.","start":5768.939,"stop":5771.032,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And if they did have right, that implicates a fishing right.","start":5771.032,"stop":5775.158,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"If they do have Indian fishing rights as defined by this Court then the State of Alaska would not have the power to regulate.","start":5775.158,"stop":5783.385,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you one more thing?","start":5783.385,"stop":5784.678,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir!","start":5784.678,"stop":5785.112,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"It would mean Indian fishing rights as to -- within the terms on Section 4?","start":5785.112,"stop":5791.299,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly right.","start":5791.299,"stop":5793.481,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, not the source of the policy.","start":5793.481,"stop":5795.598,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Section -- but what I -- what I wish to make clear Mr. Justice Whittaker is that rights have a -- have a defined meaning in Alaska and have defined meaning under -- under the terms, under the decisions of this Court and the term was not used in advisably.","start":5795.598,"stop":5810.88,"duration":15.28},{"text":"So I mean it's not a new concept of right. Now, there are no treaties and there are no reservations for the Kake and Angoon Indians.","start":5810.88,"stop":5821.148,"duration":10.27},{"text":"Now, this Court has recognized that -- that there are two basic kinds of Indian title recognized and unrecognized Indian title.","start":5821.148,"stop":5829.093,"duration":7.94},{"text":"As there are no reservations and no treaties, and no statute creating rights for Kake and Angoon specifically, we don't have recognized rights and Kake and Angoon freely admit this.","start":5829.093,"stop":5840.455,"duration":11.36},{"text":"So the question is where they have unrecognized rights and those would be of course rights protected against third parties, in this case the State of Alaska being the third party.","start":5840.455,"stop":5850.339,"duration":9.88},{"text":"Now recognized, unrecognized rights could be broken down in two categories again.","start":5850.339,"stop":5855.324,"duration":4.98},{"text":"Those rights which are preserved or aboriginal rights, historical Indian title it's called or those rights which are created by statute, a temporary right which does not create compensation, a right to compensation upon termination, but which is nonetheless a right against third parties.","start":5855.324,"stop":5872.338,"duration":17.01},{"text":"Now, we are here on a motion to dismiss.","start":5872.338,"stop":5877.579,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Now, aboriginal title is normally a question of fact, but we contend to this Court that as a matter of law, these Indians has no aboriginal title and cannot have aboriginal title.","start":5877.579,"stop":5891.105,"duration":13.53},{"text":"Now, in buttressing this claim, I wish to point out to the Court the last two sentences of Section 1 of the White Act.","start":5891.105,"stop":5900.716,"duration":9.61},{"text":"You will find that printed in full in our brief in the appendix on page 53 and 54 sentences that we are particularly interested in.","start":5900.716,"stop":5915.134,"duration":14.42},{"text":"Now, first of all, the Secretary was empowered to regulate fisheries all through Alaska and it said that when the Secretary did regulate fisheries, his regulations could not be made exclusive.","start":5915.134,"stop":5929.772,"duration":14.64},{"text":"They must apply to all equally.","start":5929.772,"stop":5932.896,"duration":3.12},{"text":"Now, this Court recognized in Hynes that it could not be exclusive as to natives too.","start":5932.896,"stop":5937.806,"duration":4.91},{"text":"It is specifically applied to native as well as others.","start":5937.806,"stop":5942.224,"duration":4.42},{"text":"So in short, this part, this sentence is exclusive -- no exclusive right forbade the Secretary of the Interior through his regulations to protect any aboriginal rights which existed.","start":5942.224,"stop":5955.666,"duration":13.44},{"text":"He had through his regulations, to open up any area in Alaska, if it was opened up to natives, it had to be opened up to Whites as well.","start":5955.666,"stop":5963.646,"duration":7.98},{"text":"So he could not protect aboriginal claim, any exclusive right of possession of natives.","start":5963.646,"stop":5968.882,"duration":5.24},{"text":"He could not protect it with that, but the next sentence, the next sentence of the White Act is most crucial.","start":5968.882,"stop":5977.31,"duration":8.43},{"text":"There it says that no citizens shall be denied the right to fish in any area of water in Alaska where -- where fishing is permitted.","start":5977.31,"stop":5986.286,"duration":8.98},{"text":"Now, here is the clearest and most unequivocal statement that could made that no person shall have an exclusive right in waters of Alaska, that whether he be native or White or corporation or individual.","start":5986.286,"stop":5999.213,"duration":12.93},{"text":"He has no exclusive right.","start":5999.213,"stop":6000.998,"duration":1.78},{"text":"If he had one, it is now gone.","start":6000.998,"stop":6003.971,"duration":2.97},{"text":"Everyone can fish there and everyone did fish there.","start":6003.971,"stop":6009.419,"duration":5.45},{"text":"I wish -- I can't make this too strong for the Court.","start":6009.419,"stop":6013.851,"duration":4.43},{"text":"These very natives, Kake and Angoon purchased their sites, purchased their cannery from a private company which was fishing in the very area they now -- now claim.","start":6013.851,"stop":6023.729,"duration":9.88},{"text":"All through Alaska, canneries are set up on the biggest Salmon streams quite obviously and these are very areas where these native tribes or native people fished in past years.","start":6023.729,"stop":6035.048,"duration":11.32},{"text":"Again quite obviously, people clustered where the fish were.","start":6035.048,"stop":6042.246,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Now, in regard to whether aboriginal rights exists such as Kake and Angoon claim, I should like to make reference to the Solicitor General's opinion which Kake and Angoon cite in their brief as holding, that no -- that aboriginal fishing rights do exist in Alaska.","start":6042.246,"stop":6064.967,"duration":22.72},{"text":"I should like to take -- to take this into consideration in conjunction with the claim in the Metlakatla brief which we agree, with which we agree that this Solicitor's opinion should be given some weight in this case.","start":6064.967,"stop":6077.261,"duration":12.29},{"text":"We recognized this, his interpretation of what the White Act meant for instance.","start":6077.261,"stop":6083.094,"duration":5.83},{"text":"Well, first of all, the Solicitor's opinion held that aboriginal fishing rights do exist in Alaska in spite of the White Act, but certain things are curious.","start":6083.094,"stop":6095.676,"duration":12.58},{"text":"First of all, from 1924 to 1942, no action was ever taken by the Solicitor to enforce these aboriginal rights.","start":6095.676,"stop":6105.016,"duration":9.34},{"text":"In 1942, he gave his opinion.","start":6105.016,"stop":6107.637,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The 1942 to 1959 again, exactly nothing was ever done to claim aboriginal rights except one thing, a bill was introduced by the Solicitor in Congress which would have protected what the solicitor considered aboriginal -- Department of Interior considered aboriginal rights and that bill was rejected, and you will find that in the Kake and Angoon brief.","start":6107.637,"stop":6131.716,"duration":24.08},{"text":"But most important is the opinion of the Solicitor on why he thought there were aboriginal rights in Alaska.","start":6131.716,"stop":6140.051,"duration":8.34},{"text":"He considered the last sentence of the White Act, the one I have already discussed with this Court regarding the exclusive that -- that every citizen must be allowed to fish in an area where any fishing is permitted and he said, “It's true.","start":6140.051,"stop":6157.694,"duration":17.64},{"text":"This sentence certainly does look like it extinguishes aboriginal rights.”","start":6157.694,"stop":6162.852,"duration":5.16},{"text":"But he said and the Court must remember that this was 1942 and prior to this Court's decision in the Tee-Hit-Ton case, “but” the solicitor said, “That taking by Congress of aboriginal title is forbidden under the Fifth Amendment, and therefore we cannot read this Act as unconstitutional interpretation.”","start":6162.852,"stop":6184.82,"duration":21.97},{"text":"Therefore, the Solicitor avoided that interpretation.","start":6184.82,"stop":6188.35,"duration":3.53},{"text":"This Court of course subsequently in 1954 I believe it was in the Tee-Hit-Ton case held specifically the opposite, that it was not indeed unconstitutional for Congress to terminate aboriginal title in anyway saw fit, without any liability arising whatsoever unless Congress saw fit to give that liability.","start":6188.35,"stop":6209.558,"duration":21.21},{"text":"So I merely point this out to show two things.","start":6209.558,"stop":6212.283,"duration":2.73},{"text":"First, the opinion of the Department of the Interior as expressed through its actions in Alaska has consistently been that no aboriginal title exists and second that even in his written opinion, the Solicitor recognized that there was no aboriginal title in Alaska and would have held so except for the fact that he believed this interpretation would have been unconstitutional, and that assumption has been proven incorrect by this Court.","start":6212.283,"stop":6240.832,"duration":28.55},{"text":"Now so much for aboriginal title, there also remains the question as to whether any other kinds of rights were created for these Indians unrecognized rights, but rights nonetheless.","start":6240.832,"stop":6251.547,"duration":10.71}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"You are talking in all this here, limiting yourself to the case, Angoon?","start":6251.547,"stop":6256.066,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes I am, Mr. Justice Harlan.","start":6256.066,"stop":6260.539,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that because the Attorney General is to argue the other case.","start":6260.539,"stop":6264.213,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct Mr. Chief Justice, but if any of the Justices wished to question me on any relation between the two, of course I'm prepared to answer on them.","start":6264.213,"stop":6272.537,"duration":8.32},{"text":"Now, so much for aboriginal title, but we still recognize that Congress could create through statutes right -- rights in these natives and if they did so, even though those rights were unrecognized, they were preserved by the Statehood Act.","start":6272.537,"stop":6286.669,"duration":14.13},{"text":"We fully concede this point.","start":6286.669,"stop":6288.653,"duration":1.98},{"text":"The question is, was the right to use traps, was it a right?","start":6288.653,"stop":6294.576,"duration":5.92},{"text":"Now, the only act under which fishing in Alaska was conducted was the White Act.","start":6294.576,"stop":6299.551,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"When you right in that sense, if I may -- you're just -- you're treating with a right as a special individual property right, are you?","start":6299.551,"stop":6312.921,"duration":13.37}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when I say property, special individual property right, I do not mean by this that it must be recognized as against the Government and therefore compensable upon on taking.","start":6312.921,"stop":6323.337,"duration":10.42},{"text":"When I say a right or a property right, I simply mean a claim against any one, meaning a third party, an individual or the state or the Federal Government, anyone.","start":6323.337,"stop":6333.651,"duration":10.31}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean something different than the right of every citizen as a citizen?","start":6333.651,"stop":6338.199,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is a public right of fishery Mr. Justice Whittaker and -- and this act specifically speaks of native rights and this is not -- this is a very different thing in the public right of fishery I believe.","start":6338.199,"stop":6352.177,"duration":13.98}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"The act if I recall it says that (Inaudible) absolute jurisdiction as control.","start":6352.177,"stop":6359.598,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":6359.598,"stop":6360.319,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"All of them.","start":6360.319,"stop":6362.13,"duration":1.81},{"text":"All lands and property, (Inaudible) including fishing right, all lands and other possible inferences including fishing rights held by native or by the United States for them.","start":6362.13,"stop":6376.314,"duration":14.18}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":6376.314,"stop":6376.836,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, fishing rights in that kind of (Inaudible) have some relationship to lands or other property, doesn't it?","start":6376.836,"stop":6384.592,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe that is correct.","start":6384.592,"stop":6386.089,"duration":1.5},{"text":"I believe that is -- that is very correct, but I am -- I am now trying to adjust -- this goes a trifle further than our argument.","start":6386.089,"stop":6393.838,"duration":7.75},{"text":"This gives an even more restricted view I think and I am trying to recognize that any kind of fishing right, even unconnected to property was not preserved to these natives, but the fishing right by the way that you are speaking of, I point this out Mr. Justice Whittaker, a fishing right connected to property.","start":6393.838,"stop":6413.769,"duration":19.93},{"text":"This is the very issue which was just taken off in the Court of Claims in which these very Indians have sued and -- and received a judgment that there is a liability against the Government for a taking of fishing rights connected to land.","start":6413.769,"stop":6431.57,"duration":17.8},{"text":"They did so.","start":6431.57,"stop":6433.727,"duration":2.16},{"text":"This – they got the claim for the entire portion of Southeastern Alaska which they now claim.","start":6433.727,"stop":6439.962,"duration":6.24},{"text":"The traps which are in this case are in that area, these very Indians have just received a claim for compensation for this that the lands were taken and the Court of Claims based this decision --","start":6439.962,"stop":6451.953,"duration":11.99}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Taken by what?","start":6451.953,"stop":6453.097,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's just I was getting to Justice Black, the Court of Claims held that the active taking in this case, they did not go up to the White Act.","start":6453.097,"stop":6459.859,"duration":6.76},{"text":"They took historical acts and got as far as I think it was 190 -- it's in -- before 1920 I believe in which Congress reserved from the public domain the Tongass Natural Forest in Southeastern Alaska which comprises all the land which is involved here and even more and the Court of Claims felt that this Reservation was inconsistent with the Indians' exclusive right of possession and they further pointed out that the Indians had lost their fishing rights connected to the land, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":6459.859,"stop":6494.795,"duration":34.94},{"text":"In fact the compensation in that case according to the Court of Claims will be granted as of the date the land was taken because the Court assumed in that case as I think you do now that these fishing rights were nothing more than easements connected to the land.","start":6494.795,"stop":6510.946,"duration":16.15}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"On pertinence.","start":6510.946,"stop":6511.921,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":6511.921,"stop":6512.689,"duration":0.77},{"text":"And the date that the land was taken, these fishing rights were taken.","start":6512.689,"stop":6515.885,"duration":3.2},{"text":"This is the Court of Claims viewpoint.","start":6515.885,"stop":6518.135,"duration":2.25},{"text":"And I believe that perhaps that one of the reasons the Court of Claims didn't reach, didn't go to White Act to destroy these fishing rights which I think the White Act clearly did, was because by 1924, the value of these fisheries are astronomical and -- and it's going to be astronomical enough at the date of taking of the Tongass Natural Forest.","start":6518.135,"stop":6538.108,"duration":19.97},{"text":"But I think the Court of Claims was quite satisfied and happy with terminating these rights at the earliest date possible, if there were alternative basis and I think they saw it -- they do not mention the White Act but they do not need to because they have terminated the rights before the White Act has ever even passed.","start":6538.108,"stop":6555.875,"duration":17.77},{"text":"Now --","start":6555.875,"stop":6556.205,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That acts, I assume you're coming to it, do I get your argument in effect in this that under the White Act provision no exclusive for several right of fishery shall be granted etcetera, effectively destroyed, whatever it was either of this may have had and that all the Section 4 did was the -- including Indian fishing rights was to save a lawsuit and to confirm your view that they had nothing.","start":6556.205,"stop":6583.035,"duration":26.83}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"No -- no that is not my distinction, Mr. Justice.","start":6583.035,"stop":6584.346,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, and then what I do hope you're going to get to that is what was it that including Indian fishing rights (Voice Overlap) reserved?","start":6584.346,"stop":6592.068,"duration":7.72}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd be happy to tell the Court.","start":6592.068,"stop":6594.519,"duration":2.45},{"text":"First of all Mr. Justice Brennan, I want a one thing clear, we do not argue here that Metlaktla was abolished by the White Act.","start":6594.519,"stop":6602.71,"duration":8.19},{"text":"It may have been, and I grant this, but we do not view that it is necessary to our case.","start":6602.71,"stop":6607.163,"duration":4.45},{"text":"One thing is quite clear, Karluk in the Hynes case for instance was not abolished for simple reason it was created after the White Act, that much we know, but let me list for the Court some fishing rights that there are in Alaskan perhaps it can understand the difference then between what we are talking about here and what legitimate fishing rights are.","start":6607.163,"stop":6625.929,"duration":18.77},{"text":"There are statutes in Alaska out of the federal statutes -- excuse me which are cited in our brief, which forbid any citizen of Alaska as well as any where else to take Fur Seals.","start":6625.929,"stop":6637.303,"duration":11.37},{"text":"This is a seal fishery by the way and that's the proper terminology.","start":6637.303,"stop":6640.85,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Fur Seals.","start":6640.85,"stop":6641.661,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Fur Seals, that's correct, but the natives, living along the coast of Alaska are permitted this right for subsistence.","start":6641.661,"stop":6649.596,"duration":7.93},{"text":"They are -- they are the only ones allowed to take the seals.","start":6649.596,"stop":6653.186,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this by express statutory provision (Voice Overlap)","start":6653.186,"stop":6655.128,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"By an expressed statutory provision (Voice Overlap)","start":6655.128,"stop":6656.83,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the date Mr. Gross?","start":6656.83,"stop":6658.735,"duration":1.9},{"text":"What's the date of the legislation?","start":6658.735,"stop":6660.412,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"1944 I believe Justice Frankfurter.","start":6660.412,"stop":6663.856,"duration":3.44},{"text":"It's cited in our brief.","start":6663.856,"stop":6666.348,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And to that extent, that was an amendment of the White Act?","start":6666.348,"stop":6670.217,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I do not think if you consider Seals a commercial fishery, since White Act was directed for the regulation of the commercial fishery and seals have never been considered in that same manner.","start":6670.217,"stop":6685.017,"duration":14.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you get into trouble, don't you?","start":6685.017,"stop":6687.244,"duration":2.23},{"text":"I think (Inaudible) construe, alright, go on so let's see the rest of it.","start":6687.244,"stop":6690.872,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think so because where Seals fishery, the White Act was directed at the Salmon fishery in Alaska, if you look at the commercial --","start":6690.872,"stop":6699.46,"duration":8.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did it say the Salmon fishery?","start":6699.46,"stop":6700.613,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"No it said the commercial fisheries of Alaska but Seals are not a commercial fishery of Alaska because they were banned.","start":6700.613,"stop":6706.667,"duration":6.05},{"text":"They were -- the treaty which stopped all fishing from Seals antedated the White Act.","start":6706.667,"stop":6710.268,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You tell me that's outside the White Act for different reason?","start":6710.268,"stop":6713.585,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":6713.585,"stop":6714.177,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":6714.177,"stop":6714.549,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":6714.549,"stop":6716.485,"duration":1.94},{"text":"Now, also we have the Karluk Reservation set up and which in Hynes -- in Hynes against Grimes Packing Company was upheld, an exclusive right of fishery, an area of water in which no other Alaskan can fish but natives, this is all.","start":6716.485,"stop":6734.934,"duration":18.45},{"text":"Now this --","start":6734.934,"stop":6735.91,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a commercial -- is that a commercial fishery?","start":6735.91,"stop":6736.869,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it was.","start":6736.869,"stop":6738.675,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And a monopoly was granted?","start":6738.675,"stop":6739.971,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"A monopoly was granted to the natives as to the area of fishery; that is right.","start":6739.971,"stop":6744.072,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And how is that contesting with the White Act?","start":6744.072,"stop":6747.155,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"The Act under which the Karluk Reserve was set up was passed in 1936, 12 years after the White Act.","start":6747.155,"stop":6755.651,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that – there was an implied amendment to that?","start":6755.651,"stop":6757.799,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there was.","start":6757.799,"stop":6759.792,"duration":1.99},{"text":"Well it --","start":6759.792,"stop":6760.355,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And I assume you would avoid getting in to that conclusion in this case?","start":6760.355,"stop":6765.306,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"In what -- in what case?","start":6765.306,"stop":6766.907,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In this very case, Section 4 that we have got a White Act problem?","start":6766.907,"stop":6773.05,"duration":6.14}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Section 4 in effect Mr. Justice Frankfurter literally repeals the White Act as applied to Alaska for the simple reason that there --","start":6773.05,"stop":6781.446,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it -- but it -- but it withheld that repeal in order to keep within federal authority, protection of the Indians.","start":6781.446,"stop":6790.417,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Protection of the Indian fishing rights.","start":6790.417,"stop":6792.009,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":6792.009,"stop":6792.827,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":6792.827,"stop":6793.754,"duration":0.93},{"text":"And if they were fishing rights, the White Act is still operative as to those fishing rights.","start":6793.754,"stop":6797.743,"duration":3.99},{"text":"That is correct, but --","start":6797.743,"stop":6801.712,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":6801.712,"stop":6806.454,"duration":4.74}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 14, 1961 (Part 2)","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren7/oral_argument_audio/23598","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gross, you may continue your argument.","start":0,"stop":3.158,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3.158,"stop":6.047,"duration":2.89},{"text":"At recess, I was trying to indicate to this Court the nature of some genuine native rights in Alaska, which were truly rights and to compare them with the rights in quotes which are claimed in this case.","start":6.047,"stop":19.448,"duration":13.4},{"text":"Now first, I pointed out that the seal fishery was specially set up by statute and natives had a -- an exclusive right to take seals for subsistent.","start":19.448,"stop":29.98,"duration":10.53},{"text":"No other person was allowed this right.","start":29.98,"stop":32.68,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Now secondly, there is the Karluk Reservation which this Court sustained in Hynes against Grimes Packing Company.","start":32.68,"stop":40.904,"duration":8.22},{"text":"Now, it sustained it as to which exclusiveness that no other Alaskan or anyone else could fish within the confines of the Karluk Reservation.","start":40.904,"stop":50.399,"duration":9.49},{"text":"Now thirdly, the White Act only pertained to commercial fishing.","start":50.399,"stop":56.675,"duration":6.28},{"text":"Now, it did not affect subsistence fishing.","start":56.675,"stop":59.625,"duration":2.95},{"text":"Now, along the Yukon and Kuskokwim Rivers in Alaska, they have always -- the natives of that area have always fished for King Salmon on the subsistence basis and in doing so, they have used small hand traps and fish wheels and if the Court will note Chapter 17 as amended of the Alaska session laws, which is the statute in issue in this case, you will see that it excludes hand-driven fish traps and fish wheels, which is the means of subsistence fishing along those rivers in Alaska.","start":59.625,"stop":89.91,"duration":30.28}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What's a fish wheel?","start":89.91,"stop":91.038,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"A fish wheel, Mr. Justice Stewart, is a -- is a wheel which is turned by the current, much as a windmill would be turned by the wind and salmon are not very intelligent.","start":91.038,"stop":102.056,"duration":11.02},{"text":"They come into the wheel and the wheel just literally picks them right up, carries them around and dumps them into a trawl.","start":102.056,"stop":107.374,"duration":5.32},{"text":"They slide down the trawl into a box where they're kept until the native takes them out.","start":107.374,"stop":112.671,"duration":5.3},{"text":"It's an aboriginal means of fishing.","start":112.671,"stop":114.925,"duration":2.25},{"text":"It's hundreds of years old, or as, I might point out that the fish traps in this case are extremely recent developments.","start":114.925,"stop":121.467,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How large are they, Mr. Gross?","start":121.467,"stop":123.538,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Fish wheels or fish traps, Your Honor?","start":123.538,"stop":125.066,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The fish wheels.","start":125.066,"stop":126.087,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, fish wheels, maybe -- oh, they may extend for 10 or 15 feet above the water.","start":126.087,"stop":134.092,"duration":8.01},{"text":"It's difficult to say because there are pipes leading various ways.","start":134.092,"stop":137.406,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but they are rather larger, aren't they?","start":137.406,"stop":139.741,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in comparison with the fish trap?","start":139.741,"stop":141.033,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, no, no.","start":141.033,"stop":141.819,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"No, and their -- their -- the effect on the salmon runs is almost negligible --","start":141.819,"stop":145.972,"duration":4.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":145.972,"stop":146.172,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but they take very few.","start":146.172,"stop":147.435,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":147.435,"stop":148.811,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, I want to stress to the Court where these rights I have -- there only three or four rights that I've told this Court about, but, I don't want to minimize their importance.","start":148.811,"stop":157.665,"duration":8.85},{"text":"These are tremendously important fishing rights.","start":157.665,"stop":160.102,"duration":2.44},{"text":"Let me show why.","start":160.102,"stop":161.673,"duration":1.57},{"text":"The Karluk River reservation gives the natives of Karluk an exclusive right to fish the area around the Karluk River.","start":161.673,"stop":170.122,"duration":8.45},{"text":"Now, this Court will recall in Hynes and Grimes Packing Company, it recognized that the Karluk River fishery was perhaps the most important fishery in that area of Alaska.","start":170.122,"stop":179.411,"duration":9.29},{"text":"It's an enormous fishery.","start":179.411,"stop":181.187,"duration":1.78},{"text":"They -- they take millions of red salmon that come up the Karluk River each year.","start":181.187,"stop":186.234,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Now -- and don't -- this right cannot be minimized.","start":186.234,"stop":188.648,"duration":2.41},{"text":"It's very important.","start":188.648,"stop":190.861,"duration":2.21},{"text":"As far as subsistence or the Kuskokwim is concerned, this may not be terribly important to the fish runs, but it's terribly important to the natives on the Kuskokwim.","start":190.861,"stop":198.239,"duration":7.38},{"text":"This is their way of life.","start":198.239,"stop":199.661,"duration":1.42},{"text":"They eat this fish.","start":199.661,"stop":201.049,"duration":1.39},{"text":"These are subsistence.","start":201.049,"stop":202.262,"duration":1.21},{"text":"They're not using them to make money with.","start":202.262,"stop":203.69,"duration":1.43},{"text":"They -- they're using to feed their wives and children and to them, it's an important right.","start":203.69,"stop":207.403,"duration":3.71},{"text":"There's no question about that and these are aboriginal natives.","start":207.403,"stop":210.382,"duration":2.98},{"text":"These are people that have not developed in the interior of Alaska.","start":210.382,"stop":214,"duration":3.62},{"text":"These are the backward tribes.","start":214,"stop":215.976,"duration":1.98},{"text":"We are not talking about that kind of a tribe in this case, right.","start":215.976,"stop":219.203,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"They take millions of them just for subsistence?","start":219.203,"stop":222.805,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Not literally millions, Your Honor.","start":222.805,"stop":224.383,"duration":1.58},{"text":"I would guess the -- the number is closer.","start":224.383,"stop":226.798,"duration":2.41},{"text":"I'm not into --","start":226.798,"stop":227.16,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I -- I understood you to say millions, literally millions.","start":227.16,"stop":230.123,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's on the Karluk River commercial fishery, Your Honor.","start":230.123,"stop":232.598,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh -- oh, I see.","start":232.598,"stop":233.771,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- that was upheld in Hynes against Grimes.","start":233.771,"stop":236.099,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":236.099,"stop":236.542,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in these cases, in every one of these cases, we have a statute or a practice which has distinguished natives from the rest of the population.","start":236.542,"stop":244.527,"duration":7.98},{"text":"In fact, I might use the Solicitor General's words.","start":244.527,"stop":247.139,"duration":2.61},{"text":"These Indians are fishing as Indians, not as citizens.","start":247.139,"stop":251.085,"duration":3.95},{"text":"They are fishing as Indians.","start":251.085,"stop":252.363,"duration":1.28},{"text":"This is something connected to their specific status as Indian, but under the White Act, under the White Act now which is talking about the commercial fisheries in Alaska, under that Act, Indians fished as equals with everyone.","start":252.363,"stop":266.503,"duration":14.14},{"text":"They're not only were treated equally, they were treated in common.","start":266.503,"stop":270.555,"duration":4.05},{"text":"There was no distinction made in any regulation between Indians and non-Indians.","start":270.555,"stop":274.979,"duration":4.42},{"text":"They were just speaking of citizens and Indians were citizens.","start":274.979,"stop":278.992,"duration":4.01},{"text":"Everyone was treated exactly the same.","start":278.992,"stop":282.398,"duration":3.41},{"text":"Now, the question then comes up, and this is specific, whether the use of a fish trap under the White Act created any kind of a right whatsoever.","start":282.398,"stop":292.672,"duration":10.27},{"text":"Now, for one thing we're talking about common treatment.","start":292.672,"stop":295.327,"duration":2.65},{"text":"Everyone is using -- everyone has the same power to use a fish trap because the regulation permits it in a certain area.","start":295.327,"stop":302.845,"duration":7.52},{"text":"Anyone can move into that area and set up a fish trap.","start":302.845,"stop":306.274,"duration":3.43},{"text":"So, once this is done, did it create a right?","start":306.274,"stop":309.162,"duration":2.89},{"text":"And this Court doesn't have to be in the dark on this question because there are federal cases in Alaska.","start":309.162,"stop":313.97,"duration":4.81},{"text":"They hold series of federal cases, which you will find cited at page 21 of our brief, which spec --","start":313.97,"stop":319.476,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":319.476,"stop":326.723,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly correct.","start":326.723,"stop":328.29,"duration":1.57},{"text":"As the Solicitor General would say, “We are speaking of their Indian right as Indians”.","start":328.29,"stop":334.263,"duration":5.97},{"text":"This is a very different thing than the general public right of fishery which is normally spoken of in abstract terms.","start":334.263,"stop":340.96,"duration":6.7},{"text":"We are speaking of an individual or a community for that matter, right against any other party or against the Government itself.","start":340.96,"stop":348.458,"duration":7.5},{"text":"And -- and the cases in Alaska cited at page 21 of our brief, federal cases in Alaska have an equivocally held that the use of a trap under the White Act created rights against no one, absolutely no one.","start":348.458,"stop":362.184,"duration":13.73},{"text":"It could be appropriated by third parties.","start":362.184,"stop":364.141,"duration":1.96},{"text":"Third parties could come in and set-up a trap right next door.","start":364.141,"stop":367.504,"duration":3.36},{"text":"It could be -- it couldn't be enforced against the Government.","start":367.504,"stop":369.911,"duration":2.41},{"text":"The Government could stop to use of traps in the area in the moment and did often times.","start":369.911,"stop":375.177,"duration":5.27},{"text":"Now, with these decisions --","start":375.177,"stop":377.153,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":377.153,"stop":380.141,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly, exactly.","start":380.141,"stop":381.96,"duration":1.82},{"text":"The -- these traps were regulated not by individuals but by areas and the -- just like -- it would speci -- you will see in our -- our brief -- by the way Mr. Justice Whittaker, on page 19 and 20, a typical regulation under which traps were allowed.","start":381.96,"stop":397.671,"duration":15.71},{"text":"Now, I picked this regulation because it is the regulation under which the Kake and Angoon traps were fished and you'll see that it opens areas to trap fishing and defines them by degrees of longitude -- latitude.","start":397.671,"stop":410.014,"duration":12.34},{"text":"Now, in this area, anyone could use a fish trap, absolutely anyone.","start":410.014,"stop":413.772,"duration":3.76},{"text":"Just like -- the only -- the only limitation was areas -- physical limitations.","start":413.772,"stop":419.614,"duration":5.84},{"text":"Two nets can't fish in the same water at the same time.","start":419.614,"stop":421.913,"duration":2.3},{"text":"There is just isn't enough room and the same thing goes for traps.","start":421.913,"stop":425.387,"duration":3.47},{"text":"There has to be a -- a distance between traps.","start":425.387,"stop":427.295,"duration":1.91},{"text":"There always was a distance between traps in Alaska, but it could be anyone, anyone could fish the traps.","start":427.295,"stop":434.114,"duration":6.82},{"text":"It's just a particular form of fishing gear like anything else as a particular form of fishing gear.","start":434.114,"stop":439.24,"duration":5.13},{"text":"Now, along with the fact that the White Act treated these natives, that we're talking about here as completely equal citizens in every regard and gave them no native rights in the commercial fishery, I wish to point out to this Court that this was entirely consistent with the entire congressional policy all through Alaska.","start":439.24,"stop":460.693,"duration":21.45},{"text":"Natives were not segregated from the rest to the population.","start":460.693,"stop":463.703,"duration":3.01},{"text":"We had no treaties in the Alaska, none whatsoever.","start":463.703,"stop":466.986,"duration":3.28},{"text":"We had, except for the Metlakatla in Karluk, no reservations in Alaska whatsoever and these are limited reservations as -- as this Court will see from -- from observing the statutes under which they were established.","start":466.986,"stop":477.822,"duration":10.84},{"text":"Now, Indians in Alaska have always paid all taxes in Alaska, always.","start":477.822,"stop":482.622,"duration":4.8},{"text":"They've no distinction between them and other citizen.","start":482.622,"stop":485.524,"duration":2.9},{"text":"They've always been tried by territorial which were, in those cases, federal courts, along under territorial law.","start":485.524,"stop":492.966,"duration":7.44},{"text":"They never had a tribal law under which these Indians were -- were tried, always the same -- tried in the same manner.","start":492.966,"stop":499.812,"duration":6.85},{"text":"They have always been completely full citizens.","start":499.812,"stop":502.659,"duration":2.85},{"text":"There has been no distinction made between them and the rest to the citizens in Alaska and I pointed out in the brief, but I want reiterate to this Court how completely amalgamated the natives are in Alaska.","start":502.659,"stop":514.577,"duration":11.92},{"text":"Now, for instance, natives vote.","start":514.577,"stop":516.644,"duration":2.07},{"text":"Now, you've heard -- you've heard the estimate here of how many natives there are in the -- in the State.","start":516.644,"stop":521.486,"duration":4.84},{"text":"That's approximately, I believe, 12% or something to that effect.","start":521.486,"stop":527.379,"duration":5.89},{"text":"Now, the Alaska Legislature, on the other hand, is composed 15% of natives.","start":527.379,"stop":533.034,"duration":5.65},{"text":"So I think quite obviously that these natives are not only drawing there support from there native brethren, they're being elected by whites.","start":533.034,"stop":540.188,"duration":7.15},{"text":"The President of the Senate in Alaska is a Tlingit Indian, who was elected from an election district nearly 80% white.","start":540.188,"stop":547.732,"duration":7.54},{"text":"These are Indians which are completely integrated into the society.","start":547.732,"stop":551.507,"duration":3.77},{"text":"We have been very fortunate in Alaska.","start":551.507,"stop":554.054,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"How many of them are -- have become (Inaudible)","start":554.054,"stop":558.467,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"All of them.","start":558.467,"stop":558.728,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"All of them?","start":558.728,"stop":559.934,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Everyone.","start":559.934,"stop":563.011,"duration":3.08},{"text":"In -- this Court recognized years ago in the Kagama case when it was upholding a --","start":563.011,"stop":568.587,"duration":5.58}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"They have segregated schools for Indians there now?","start":568.587,"stop":570.861,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"They do not.","start":570.861,"stop":571.913,"duration":1.05},{"text":"The BIA, I -- I should say, the Bureau of Indian Affairs does run rural schools in Indian communities where whites may not live and in that sense, there are -- it is segregated in fact, but all states schools are open for Indian and non-Indian alike and the schools in Metlakatla, Kake, and Angoon are states schools, all of them.","start":571.913,"stop":595.169,"duration":23.26},{"text":"Now, in the Kagama case, this Court recognized in upholding the federal power, that the reason, one of the reasons is, it was so important to uphold federal power was, and I -- I think use almost the Court's identical words, the citizens of the State, their neighbors in the State are often they worst enemies.","start":595.169,"stop":613.623,"duration":18.45},{"text":"There's a real problem.","start":613.623,"stop":614.884,"duration":1.26},{"text":"There was friction between Indians and other citizens in the State.","start":614.884,"stop":618.105,"duration":3.22},{"text":"We've been very fortunate in Alaska, we don't have that.","start":618.105,"stop":621.157,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Indians and white are equal in Alaska, as indeed, they must be if the State is going to grow. We can't afford to segregate people all.","start":621.157,"stop":627.76,"duration":6.6},{"text":"We need every citizen we have to develop the State.","start":627.76,"stop":631.692,"duration":3.93},{"text":"Now, there is -- I -- you may not take my word for this.","start":631.692,"stop":636.661,"duration":4.97},{"text":"There is a number of cases cited in our brief, federal court cases which have recognized consistently the complete amalgamation of the natives in Southeastern Alaska into the white population.","start":636.661,"stop":647.637,"duration":10.98},{"text":"Certainly, they live in towns which are -- these various communities Kake and Angoon.","start":647.637,"stop":651.335,"duration":3.7},{"text":"They lived in the towns of Kake and Angoon.","start":651.335,"stop":654.163,"duration":2.83},{"text":"Those aren't all native villages.","start":654.163,"stop":655.591,"duration":1.43},{"text":"There are whites living in Kake and Angoon.","start":655.591,"stop":658.297,"duration":2.71},{"text":"These are element -- these are -- these are Alaska cities.","start":658.297,"stop":660.73,"duration":2.43},{"text":"They are incorporated under municipal law -- under state law and they exercise municipal powers.","start":660.73,"stop":666.439,"duration":5.71},{"text":"These are just typical cities in which inhabitants are native.","start":666.439,"stop":669.985,"duration":3.55},{"text":"This is -- this is race were talking about here.","start":669.985,"stop":672.511,"duration":2.53},{"text":"Now -- now that the -- I want to point out -- I point out as not to claim that -- that the Federal Government has lost its jurisdiction over natives in Alaska as the -- as the Federal Government itself points out in its brief, we do not wish to confuse the existence of a power with its exercise.","start":672.511,"stop":694.482,"duration":21.97},{"text":"We recognized that natives in Alaska may well be subject to federal control.","start":694.482,"stop":698.689,"duration":4.21},{"text":"We don't con -- we don't contend that they are not.","start":698.689,"stop":701.445,"duration":2.76},{"text":"What we do contend is that the Federal Government has never sought in the past to distinguish these races and especially not in Alaska's largest industry and that it would be inconsistent with past federal policy to hold that Section 4 did so now, that where the Federal Government made distinctions in the past for subsistence or for a seal fishery or a specific reservation, that makes sense.","start":701.445,"stop":724.061,"duration":22.62},{"text":"That makes sense for the Federal Government to continue this, but it is entirely inconsistent with past federal policy to suddenly take one-half of an entire industry, segregate them on the basis of race where they never had any legal rights and say, “These Indians are now different from the rest of the citizen.”","start":724.061,"stop":741.618,"duration":17.56},{"text":"They are not subject to state regulation.","start":741.618,"stop":743.476,"duration":1.86},{"text":"They are subject to federal regulation exclusively.","start":743.476,"stop":746.425,"duration":2.95},{"text":"It just -- it -- it's just completely inconsistent with the whole history of federal -- federal policy in Alaska.","start":746.425,"stop":752.135,"duration":5.71},{"text":"What -- what that Section means, as -- as we see it, is that where Congress made distinctions, those distinctions were preserved, and they are important distinctions, but they did not make distinctions all through the commercial fisheries and not in relation to traps and those distinctions that never existed should not and were not created by Section 4, that is essentially our argument on that point.","start":752.135,"stop":774.403,"duration":22.27},{"text":"Now, as a last argument regarding the interpretation of Section 4, we wish to point out the effect that the various interpretations posed here today will have.","start":774.403,"stop":785.199,"duration":10.8},{"text":"Now, I do not say this because I want this Court to pass on the wisdom of an Act of Congress.","start":785.199,"stop":789.367,"duration":4.17},{"text":"Obviously, it cannot do that, but we do want to point out that the interpretations urged here today will result in an absurd conclusion and it is a settled point of statutory construction that the Court will not attempt to make an Act of Congress into an absurd -- give it an absurd construction.","start":789.367,"stop":808.174,"duration":18.81},{"text":"Now, I want -- I want to point out these various -- these various interpretations suggested and show to Court what will happen under.","start":808.174,"stop":815.039,"duration":6.87},{"text":"Now, let me first take the Government's view.","start":815.039,"stop":818.377,"duration":3.34},{"text":"Now, the Government really has, it seems, two views.","start":818.377,"stop":822.012,"duration":3.63},{"text":"The view in their brief was that -- that the Department of the Interior has full authority over Indian fishing to do with as it sees fit.","start":822.012,"stop":830.749,"duration":8.74},{"text":"It can authorize traps or not authorize traps.","start":830.749,"stop":833.02,"duration":2.27},{"text":"It can authorize 11 traps or it can authorize 111 traps if it wants to and I quote from the Governments brief, “The Secretary has full authority to do what he considers proper for the protection of the Indian fishing rights including enlargement of fishing rights beyond those now enjoyed subject to his consideration of other pertinent factors including -- including conservation.”","start":833.02,"stop":856.402,"duration":23.38},{"text":"This was --","start":856.402,"stop":856.692,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But that --","start":856.692,"stop":857.172,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":857.172,"stop":857.354,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But that -- that depends on the (Inaudible) rights, isn't it?","start":857.354,"stop":861.393,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":861.393,"stop":862.21,"duration":0.82},{"text":"But the Government in its brief, Mr. Justice Whittaker, said that it could expand these rights.","start":862.21,"stop":867.946,"duration":5.74},{"text":"This is what I was getting at.","start":867.946,"stop":869.763,"duration":1.82},{"text":"If -- if the Government is correct in its interpretation and -- and we are talking about traps, it could theoretically authorize 111 traps or 1111 traps.","start":869.763,"stop":881.105,"duration":11.34},{"text":"The fact we have 11 traps now is of no effect under the Government's interpretation.","start":881.105,"stop":885.073,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"So it has to be in the same area though, wasn't it?","start":885.073,"stop":886.902,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not what the Government's brief says.","start":886.902,"stop":889.754,"duration":2.85},{"text":"That is what Kake and Angoon have argued here today, aboriginal area.","start":889.754,"stop":892.951,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the Government said not only in the same area, not only that this a geographic term -- geographically bounded, but also, there would have to be an existence of the term of the Act.","start":892.951,"stop":905.826,"duration":12.88}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is what the Government said today in its oral argument, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":905.826,"stop":908.406,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not only -- they thought certainly not more than 21 sites and they quoted the Department of Interior as construing it to mean the existing available types.","start":908.406,"stop":922.938,"duration":14.53}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is absolutely --","start":922.938,"stop":923.376,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Less than 21.","start":923.376,"stop":925.228,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That is absolutely correct, Justice Frankfurter, and it's quite clear that that Justice Department and the Department of the Interior vary on their interpretations on this Act.","start":925.228,"stop":931.408,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, there's no more than 21 under any construction?","start":931.408,"stop":934.022,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Not under the Government's brief construction, Mr. -- Mr. Justice Frankfurter and it's in -- it's -- in their brief, they make it unlimited.","start":934.022,"stop":940.972,"duration":6.95},{"text":"Before the Court, they have limited it to the 21 sites, that's true.","start":940.972,"stop":945.554,"duration":4.58},{"text":"I merely pointing out that there's two interpretations the Government has urged and I want to discuss both of them to show the Court what will happen, but before I do, I want to make the Court aware of one thing.","start":945.554,"stop":956.038,"duration":10.48},{"text":"Under the White Act, as I pointed out, there were regulations authorizing areas for traps.","start":956.038,"stop":961.954,"duration":5.92},{"text":"Now, these regulations occupied no special status under the White Act.","start":961.954,"stop":966.606,"duration":4.65},{"text":"They had no more legal affect than a regulation permitting next in a particular area or a regulation closing an area to fishing, or a regulation forbidding a particular stream from being fished in a particular manner.","start":966.606,"stop":979.907,"duration":13.3},{"text":"In short, there is no legal difference between the use of fish traps and the use of any other equipment under the White Act, now I'm speaking of, or any other regulation promulgated under the White Act.","start":979.907,"stop":991.199,"duration":11.29},{"text":"If fish traps are a right protected by Section 4, all control of Indian fishing was con -- was protected under Section 4.","start":991.199,"stop":1000.73,"duration":9.53},{"text":"I cannot urge this too strongly, but the fish traps are no special device.","start":1000.73,"stop":1005.347,"duration":4.62},{"text":"They are just like any other thing that was used under the White Act.","start":1005.347,"stop":1008.445,"duration":3.1},{"text":"This controversy has arisen over fish traps and perhaps, it's -- it's ironic that it has because, the fish traps, of course, have been, as I've been pointed out for various reasons, go in the Alaskan throat, not only in the white Alaskan's throat, as you will see in our brief, the natives have constantly opposed fish traps in Alaska, too, through their authorized spokesman.","start":1008.445,"stop":1030.262,"duration":21.82},{"text":"Alaskans dislike traps intensely and I -- I'm not going to go in the -- the conservation aspects of this.","start":1030.262,"stop":1035.621,"duration":5.36},{"text":"The statute recites it's a conservation measure.","start":1035.621,"stop":1037.996,"duration":2.38},{"text":"There is evidence to -- to indicate that it is and no evidence except an opinion to indicate that that is not -- it's not on us to prove the conservation measure on -- of the statute, it's for them to disprove it, and there is no evidence on that of any kind.","start":1037.996,"stop":1051.572,"duration":13.58},{"text":"But, of course, as to the legal relevance of this matter, according to the claims made here today whether it's a conservation measure or not, it doesn't seem to make any difference if it was preserved under the Federal Government the State has no power to regulate it in any case.","start":1051.572,"stop":1065.882,"duration":14.31},{"text":"So I -- I may --","start":1065.882,"stop":1066.126,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Or vise-versa, or vise-versa or the reverse is equally true?","start":1066.126,"stop":1071.721,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"If --","start":1071.721,"stop":1071.847,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If it's not reserved, then we can't scrutinize whether your right (Inaudible)","start":1071.847,"stop":1076.674,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly correct.","start":1076.674,"stop":1077.961,"duration":1.29},{"text":"That's true.","start":1077.961,"stop":1079.943,"duration":1.98},{"text":"Now, so let me -- let me consider this question of the results of the interpretations that have been suggested today on the basis that we're not only talking about traps, we're talking about all regulations promulgated under the White Act because there's no distinction between them.","start":1079.943,"stop":1094.553,"duration":14.61},{"text":"Now, let me take an example of first, the broadest interpretation, which has been suggested today that the Gover -- if that's in the Government's brief, if the Federal Government has exclusive authority over all natives fishing in Alaska and can do what it considers proper for them, well, then you have one sovereign state regulating the White fishermen and you have the other sovereign, the Government regulating the native fishermen.","start":1094.553,"stop":1118.609,"duration":24.06},{"text":"Now, this can be disastrous in a situation and I'll give you a perfect example of it.","start":1118.609,"stop":1123.391,"duration":4.78},{"text":"In Bristol Bay, Alaska, which is the largest salmon fishery in the world, millions of salmon come into that bay in one week, and they are all caught during that period.","start":1123.391,"stop":1133.535,"duration":10.14},{"text":"Now, the State's fishing is -- if the State proposes its fishing time on the basis that a certain amount of days will be kept free of fishing so the salmon can get up -- up the streams.","start":1133.535,"stop":1143.89,"duration":10.36},{"text":"It generally allows four, five days, perhaps, in fishing and then closes it for another two.","start":1143.89,"stop":1148.44,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Well, suppose they embark on this program and then with the two days remaining in the week, they close down their fishery and the Federal Government decides that the natives haven't caught enough, so they open it.","start":1148.44,"stop":1158.586,"duration":10.15},{"text":"Then what happens?","start":1158.586,"stop":1159.276,"duration":0.69},{"text":"You have half the fishermen in the State fishing in Bristol Bay and half the fishermen not.","start":1159.276,"stop":1163.534,"duration":4.26},{"text":"The State's carefully plan program of five days and two days close goes right down the drain to the detriment of everybody.","start":1163.534,"stop":1172.115,"duration":8.58},{"text":"Now, it's true, that -- that -- it's been pointed out that the Federal Government will undoubtedly be guided by thoughts of conservation.","start":1172.115,"stop":1180.554,"duration":8.44},{"text":"This is -- this is been -- been reiterated in the briefs, but the trouble is with this that the claims are conflicting.","start":1180.554,"stop":1188.21,"duration":7.66},{"text":"The real matter -- the reason this -- these traps are been authorized is because the Secretary wants the Metlakatla cannery along with those in Kake and Angoon to have more fish than they would have otherwise.","start":1188.21,"stop":1198.401,"duration":10.19},{"text":"That's been made quite clear.","start":1198.401,"stop":1199.616,"duration":1.21},{"text":"He wants them to make -- be in economic successes.","start":1199.616,"stop":1202.86,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Well, that's just the point in Alaska.","start":1202.86,"stop":1204.686,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Too many people have made economic successes, and there are not enough fish any more.","start":1204.686,"stop":1208.957,"duration":4.27},{"text":"So they are trying to close it down.","start":1208.957,"stop":1210.401,"duration":1.44},{"text":"They are trying to close it down either in stages or whole areas, but if we can't do this, if -- if the only consideration is the economic benefit of this particular Alaskan communities, who are, as I say, full Alaskan citizens, what can we do?","start":1210.401,"stop":1224.952,"duration":14.55},{"text":"This is half the fishermen of the State we're talking about now, not -- not of little isolated Indian community off in some place, we're talking about half the fishermen of the State.","start":1224.952,"stop":1234.917,"duration":9.96},{"text":"Now that's -- that's the broadest interpretation.","start":1234.917,"stop":1236.947,"duration":2.03},{"text":"The second interpretation is taken in --","start":1236.947,"stop":1238.584,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- well I'm certain, I can infer from that that if these claims, they are sustained as fishing rights in half the industry of the State, there will similar claims of fishing rights?","start":1238.584,"stop":1253.098,"duration":14.51},{"text":"Is that what you're saying?","start":1253.098,"stop":1253.846,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"If you sustain these claims as fishing rights, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, any action taken by the Federal Government to regulate Indian fishing whether it's a trap or closing an area, opening an area will be equally an Indian fishing right.","start":1253.846,"stop":1266.376,"duration":12.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not mentioning that into actuality, does that mean that there are outstand -- there were outstanding, as of 1959, rights comparable to these rights in regard to half of the industry of the State?","start":1266.376,"stop":1281.497,"duration":15.12}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"There are -- half of the industries of the State are natives and half of the industry of the State can claim that they were using some form of equipment under the White Act in 1959.","start":1281.497,"stop":1291.875,"duration":10.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, does the State say that in fact there were in use, frozen by the claim of the Government now, fishing rights that would make the kind of divisions in -- if I may use the word again, natives and the non-natives?","start":1291.875,"stop":1309.73,"duration":17.86}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not admit that, Your Honor.","start":1309.73,"stop":1311.099,"duration":1.37},{"text":"That is what the Government claims.","start":1311.099,"stop":1312.229,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":1312.229,"stop":1313.746,"duration":1.52},{"text":"What I'm asking you is whether there are -- there's a factual basis per se that if these claims are recognized, then there are claims to the extent of half the fishing industry of Alaska, outside of the control of Alaska.","start":1313.746,"stop":1329.588,"duration":15.84},{"text":"Is that what you're saying?","start":1329.588,"stop":1331.329,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- yes, this is essentially what I am saying, Your Honor, yes.","start":1331.329,"stop":1334.136,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not hypothetically, not argumentatively --","start":1334.136,"stop":1336.909,"duration":2.77},{"text":"But in fact --","start":1336.909,"stop":1337.942,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"In fact. Because and -- and this is what I'm saying, because the regu -- the use of fish trap was no different than the use of any other form of gear and we know that half the fishermen in the State were using some form of gear, half the fishermen are natives.","start":1337.942,"stop":1352.488,"duration":14.55},{"text":"So, if this right is -- is a right -- if this is a right that we're talking about here, so was the use of nets?","start":1352.488,"stop":1358.796,"duration":6.31},{"text":"This --","start":1358.796,"stop":1358.964,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are those -- are those outlawed – would those be otherwise outlawed by the state law?","start":1358.964,"stop":1363.307,"duration":4.34}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Other -- other particular forms to fishing equipment?","start":1363.307,"stop":1365.348,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1365.348,"stop":1366.161,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"They have not been now, but they maybe -- they -- in fact they are from a time to time basis.","start":1366.161,"stop":1370.585,"duration":4.42},{"text":"For instance, in -- in various areas of the State nets of only one length are allowed.","start":1370.585,"stop":1376.221,"duration":5.64},{"text":"They are not allowed to use larger nets, you see.","start":1376.221,"stop":1378.762,"duration":2.54},{"text":"Now, if -- if we're talking about a frozen claim, theoretically the natives could go back in 1959, any native fishermen now --","start":1378.762,"stop":1384.716,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And by native, you mean, established communities like these?","start":1384.716,"stop":1387.815,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"No, by native, I mean native fishermen, any native fishermen.","start":1387.815,"stop":1389.701,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean just an Indian?","start":1389.701,"stop":1391.118,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Any Indian or for that matter --","start":1391.118,"stop":1392.333,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The individual Indian roaming in Alaska?","start":1392.333,"stop":1394.118,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"It could be that or for that matter, it could be a native community.","start":1394.118,"stop":1397.125,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But which is it?","start":1397.125,"stop":1397.973,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- well, to us --","start":1397.973,"stop":1399.745,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The claim of the Government was not -- was the operative of any fishermen who happens to be an Indian has protected right.","start":1399.745,"stop":1407.719,"duration":7.97},{"text":"I understood that was precisely not the claim that was disavowed, but you're saying that if Indian -- Indian means -- an individual Indian, that means half the fishing industry and that means half the fishing industry can be withdrawn from the state control?","start":1407.719,"stop":1422.633,"duration":14.91}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true --","start":1422.633,"stop":1422.989,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your argument?","start":1422.989,"stop":1423.832,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true, Mr. Justice Frankfurter and let me explain why I take this position.","start":1423.832,"stop":1427.457,"duration":3.63},{"text":"The Federal Government in its brief restricted its claim to Indian communities.","start":1427.457,"stop":1431.689,"duration":4.23},{"text":"It did, but the reason I don't feel this claim can be sustained is because it's inconsistent. We're talking about a right held by natives or the Federal Government for natives.","start":1431.689,"stop":1443.256,"duration":11.57},{"text":"Now, whether an individual or a community or a corporation or any organized body under the White Act used a trap or any other fishing gear, it did not give them any right.","start":1443.256,"stop":1454.779,"duration":11.52},{"text":"It didn't make any difference whether he was an individual or a community or anything.","start":1454.779,"stop":1459.23,"duration":4.45},{"text":"So what I'm saying is if you sustain it for a community you have, in a sense, sustained it for an individual, too.","start":1459.23,"stop":1463.947,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the relation of an Indian community to the Federal Government is a very different thing in the long course of Indian history -- an Indian Law history, than the relation of an emancipated individual Indian?","start":1463.947,"stop":1476.279,"duration":12.33}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's entirely correct, Your Honor, but we're not speaking here today about any Indian -- aboriginal Indian tribe as I understand it.","start":1476.279,"stop":1483.533,"duration":7.25},{"text":"The decisions of -- of every court that has ever passed on this subject has -- has decided that we are not talking about a tribal entity.","start":1483.533,"stop":1490.559,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, no, but we are talking about a community entity?","start":1490.559,"stop":1493.27,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean a community under the Wheeler-Howard Act?","start":1493.27,"stop":1495.213,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1495.213,"stop":1495.915,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is -- of course, when we speak of a community under the --","start":1495.915,"stop":1498.325,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) there's nobody knows, as you know, as well as I do, that that was better, that that was a very important measure in the evolution of Indian Law?","start":1498.325,"stop":1506.461,"duration":8.14}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Very correct, Your Honor, but the Wheeler-Howard Act provided that Indians could organize into corporations, which these appellants have done, but it was never said in their -- to their economic benefit that these corporations could fish free of the general regulations in Alaska.","start":1506.461,"stop":1522.296,"duration":15.84},{"text":"And they did not fish free of them and any corporation private or governmental that was fishing under these regulations did not gain a right through use of a fish trap.","start":1522.296,"stop":1531.241,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I fully follow your argument and I think I appreciate it.","start":1531.241,"stop":1534.718,"duration":3.48},{"text":"What I'm trying to find out is the basis from your argument in drawing the difference between an established community under the Wheeler-Howard Act and an individual Indian?","start":1534.718,"stop":1547.266,"duration":12.55}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I understand the doctrines of Indian Law, Your Honor, the fact that an Indian is no longer a member of a tribe, does not make a crucial difference.","start":1547.266,"stop":1556.529,"duration":9.26},{"text":"The power over tribes also extends to individual Indians.","start":1556.529,"stop":1560.299,"duration":3.77},{"text":"Now --","start":1560.299,"stop":1560.471,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It may -- it may?","start":1560.471,"stop":1562.079,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's true, but these Indians in Southeastern Alaska, if you are going to classify them, any form of tribe whatsoever for powers of Federal Indian Law, all of the appellants belong and every Indian, perhaps, well, I shouldn't -- I shouldn't say every Indian, I can't -- I can't make a definite statement as to the percentage of Indians that belong to this, what you would term loosely family groups connected into what we would term a tribe.","start":1562.079,"stop":1585.221,"duration":23.14},{"text":"I cannot -- (Voice Overlap) I think I see what you're asking for.","start":1585.221,"stop":1587.644,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your argument wipes out all the other any legal differentiation between the two kinds of Indian Associations (a) an individual, an Indian lawyer practicing in Juneau or (b) an editor who happens to be an Indian and these organized or establish communities.","start":1587.644,"stop":1610.904,"duration":23.26}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":1610.904,"stop":1611.044,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's you position, isn't it?","start":1611.044,"stop":1611.773,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but I need not take that position, Justice Frankfurter and if it raises the question in you mind, I need not -- I won't – won't do so.","start":1611.773,"stop":1616.537,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Don't bother about me, I'm just trying to get to what your position is.","start":1616.537,"stop":1620.635,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"If it were an Indian community, it would make no difference.","start":1620.635,"stop":1623.178,"duration":2.54},{"text":"If we take a stream in Southeastern Alaska, in which the fish come and the state program is regulated on the basis of how many fish get into that stream, and Kake as a native community under the Wheeler-Howard Act, is allowed to fish free of state regulation or for that matter the government decides to give it an additional privilege in relation to the stream, the state program is of no avail whatsoever and can't be planed at all.","start":1623.178,"stop":1645.98,"duration":22.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1645.98,"stop":1659.263,"duration":13.28}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Are not reachable by the state law?","start":1659.263,"stop":1660.914,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1660.914,"stop":1666.754,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":1666.754,"stop":1669.493,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) even if the government state law (Inaudible) --","start":1669.493,"stop":1687.1,"duration":17.61}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":1687.1,"stop":1687.568,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- even though the government (Inaudible)","start":1687.568,"stop":1689.38,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that term exclusive right in jurisdiction to the Federal Government can mean nothing else.","start":1689.38,"stop":1694.491,"duration":5.11},{"text":"I -- I agree with you completely, Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":1694.491,"stop":1696.706,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1696.706,"stop":1700.65,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":1700.65,"stop":1702.576,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Now finally, I wish to point out one last thing, I wish to let Mr. -- Attorney General Moody conclude the argument, but I do want to talk about Kake and Angoon's claim for one last minute. Kake and Angoon came -- claim aboriginal rights in an area.","start":1702.576,"stop":1716.4,"duration":13.82},{"text":"Now, I've already pointed out to this Court why I believe that aboriginal rights were extinguished, but let's assume for a moment that they were not.","start":1716.4,"stop":1724.19,"duration":7.79},{"text":"I want to show the Court the effect of this.","start":1724.19,"stop":1727.541,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Now, they have minimized their claim to aboriginal rights.","start":1727.541,"stop":1731.559,"duration":4.02},{"text":"If the Court will look in the Tlingit and Haida cases which in -- in the Court of Claims which maxed out the area claimed by these Indians, they will find that it occupies all of Southeastern Alaska.","start":1731.559,"stop":1742.37,"duration":10.81},{"text":"This isn't small area.","start":1742.37,"stop":1743.937,"duration":1.57},{"text":"This is all of southeastern Alaska.","start":1743.937,"stop":1745.848,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Now those of you who have seen a map of Alaska or been in Alaska will realize the vast expanse of area this really is.","start":1745.848,"stop":1752.444,"duration":6.6},{"text":"And it's a tremendous fishery down there, too.","start":1752.444,"stop":1755.687,"duration":3.24},{"text":"Now, if Kake and Angoon are right, in the area where Kake and Angoon fish, in that whole Southeastern Alaskan area, aboriginal area we're talking about, they can fish free of state regulations of any kind and if they can, I point out that the States' power now in Southeastern Alaska is -- is nothing.","start":1755.687,"stop":1777.607,"duration":21.92},{"text":"It can't regulate if they can only regulate half of it -- the people.","start":1777.607,"stop":1780.89,"duration":3.28},{"text":"This Court recognizes in Missouri against Holland when it was talking about migratory birds.","start":1780.89,"stop":1785.891,"duration":5},{"text":"Now, it -- if I can -- if I can draw an analogy here in -- the Court said that Missouri can't regulate migratory birds because everybody has to be bound by a scheme of conservation when you're talking about migratory animals.","start":1785.891,"stop":1798.69,"duration":12.8},{"text":"Because anyone person could destroy the whole program, but we're talking about migratory salmon here.","start":1798.69,"stop":1804.022,"duration":5.33},{"text":"These salmon pass hundreds of miles of coastline before they enter the streams.","start":1804.022,"stop":1808.156,"duration":4.13},{"text":"Now, how is the State to plan its fishing effort along those hundreds of miles of coastline if it doesn't know how the Federal Government is going to run its programs in regard to these aboriginal claims.","start":1808.156,"stop":1820.945,"duration":12.79},{"text":"In summary, I just want to say, that if the Court upholds this right today, this claimed right, Alaska's fight to gain control over its fisheries is gone.","start":1820.945,"stop":1833.463,"duration":12.52},{"text":"We -- we have gained nothing.","start":1833.463,"stop":1835.15,"duration":1.69},{"text":"We have gained a power to regulate one-half of the fishing population and that is next to nothing, if we can't regulate the other half.","start":1835.15,"stop":1844.868,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I trouble you to --","start":1844.868,"stop":1845.852,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly.","start":1845.852,"stop":1846.38,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- summarize quickly with us, concluding on the general stand, what you conceive to be the present range of authority of the Federal Government for the exercise through the Secretary of the Interior over Indians in Alaska.","start":1846.38,"stop":1865.743,"duration":19.36}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"What to -- over all Indians?","start":1865.743,"stop":1867.833,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm talking about -- not fishing.","start":1867.833,"stop":1870.98,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh!","start":1870.98,"stop":1871.097,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But what do you conceive to be the range, the scope of authority, if any, over Indians? Does that include an individual Indian who practices law in Juneau or some editor or does it relate only to organized communities, organized not in a technical sense?","start":1871.097,"stop":1888.377,"duration":17.28}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say this Justice -- Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1888.377,"stop":1891.202,"duration":2.83},{"text":"There is no question that the Federal Government retains plenary power, as it does in other areas over all Indian tribes.","start":1891.202,"stop":1899.034,"duration":7.83},{"text":"That much is clear.","start":1899.034,"stop":1900.682,"duration":1.65},{"text":"As to individual Indians, we will be faced --","start":1900.682,"stop":1902.858,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How about -- how about the non-tribal collectivities?","start":1902.858,"stop":1907.311,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Non-tribal collectivities organized under federal law?","start":1907.311,"stop":1910.19,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1910.19,"stop":1911.019,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would venture to say that -- that it probably would be impossible for non-tribal Indians to be organized under federal law as Indians.","start":1911.019,"stop":1917.921,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how about if these are the organizers of Wheeler-Howard?","start":1917.921,"stop":1920.282,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"They are -- this is a --","start":1920.282,"stop":1921.348,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They are tribes, are they?","start":1921.348,"stop":1922.545,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a different kind of organization, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1922.545,"stop":1925.381,"duration":2.84},{"text":"It is unique to the Indian groups, but it is a different type of tribe when we speak of it in the State.","start":1925.381,"stop":1930.014,"duration":4.63},{"text":"I would concede that -- that a wide leeway, in fact almost complete leeway, is giving the Federal Government in determining what shall be termed a tribe and if they decide that even Indians which I or -- or perhaps this Court might determine are non-tribal Indians or nonetheless tribal Indian – Indians, it has been the policy of this Court in the past to not argue the point with them -- with the federal authority.","start":1930.014,"stop":1951.51,"duration":21.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in Sandoval case this Court said that the Federal Government, Secretary of Interior can bring together a lot of (Inaudible) and call it an Indian tribe.","start":1951.51,"stop":1960.798,"duration":9.29}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"But in -- in the Kagama -- in the Sandoval case, it also pointed out, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, that it did not mean the Congress could make an arbitrary determination of who belong to a tribe.","start":1960.798,"stop":1970.476,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, but would -- would this control be over the individual who might take it for granted the individual Indian lawyer?","start":1970.476,"stop":1978.468,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":1978.468,"stop":1978.606,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The lawyer of Indian extraction in Juneau --","start":1978.606,"stop":1981.109,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I do --","start":1981.109,"stop":1981.365,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- are these subject to (Inaudible) control?","start":1981.365,"stop":1983.199,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I would doubt this, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":1983.199,"stop":1984.967,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I think there comes of point where the federal exercise of control becomes arbitrary within the meaning of the Kagama case and there -- and the Sandoval case and at this point, it must cease and I think this Court could so holds.","start":1984.967,"stop":1995.35,"duration":10.38},{"text":"But what I am indicating here is, we're not -- under our interpretation of Section 4, Congress did not retain control over the Indian fishing in Alaska.","start":1995.35,"stop":2003.97,"duration":8.62},{"text":"The only person that disclaimed this is the Secretary of the Interior and if his interpretation is incorrect, we are not faced with the problem of -- to what extent Congress could control the Indians, because they have expressly not done so.","start":2003.97,"stop":2016.151,"duration":12.18},{"text":"Now, if in the future they pass a statute which does so, then the question, I think, which you have posed would arise.","start":2016.151,"stop":2021.992,"duration":5.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that, of course, certainly operates on some changes?","start":2021.992,"stop":2024.785,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"It most certainly does.","start":2024.785,"stop":2025.752,"duration":0.97},{"text":"It operates on -- on various rights which I have mentioned here and certainly, the subsistence rights on the Kuskokwim River are held by tribal Indians.","start":2025.752,"stop":2034.103,"duration":8.35},{"text":"There's no question about that.","start":2034.103,"stop":2035.612,"duration":1.51},{"text":"The Karluk Reservation is for the Karluk tribe of Indians and -- and the Hynes case points this out.","start":2035.612,"stop":2040.105,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I think one must make a general decision out of that.","start":2040.105,"stop":2042.417,"duration":2.31},{"text":"I'm not saying the 50 claims, etcetera.","start":2042.417,"stop":2045.996,"duration":3.58},{"text":"That's a generalize term.","start":2045.996,"stop":2047.801,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"That's true.","start":2047.801,"stop":2048.3,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Indian rights, but therefore it must have some generalized content.","start":2048.3,"stop":2052.924,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think if there were -- but two rights, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, the clause would be satisfied.","start":2052.924,"stop":2057.958,"duration":5.03},{"text":"There would be two Indian rights and they are -- and they are of the enormous importance.","start":2057.958,"stop":2062.15,"duration":4.19},{"text":"When you say a generalized term, I think you mean it takes more than one and -- and it does.","start":2062.15,"stop":2065.835,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It takes more than two – it does two specifics?","start":2065.835,"stop":2068.692,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are not -- there are -- I believe I gave three specifics, but subsistence fishing, as you have just pointed out, is a generalized thing.","start":2068.692,"stop":2076.504,"duration":7.81},{"text":"And every tribal Indian and Alaska which possesses -- which -- which -- which has aboriginal subsistence fishing rights, I believe, would probably be entitled to retain them under this act, free of state regulation.","start":2076.504,"stop":2088.109,"duration":11.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though those subsistence rights may cut heavily into police power regulation by the State?","start":2088.109,"stop":2094.831,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Subsistence fishing rights could not do so, Mr. Justice Frankfurter --","start":2094.831,"stop":2098.219,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the State may have a different mode of dealing with those subsistence needs.","start":2098.219,"stop":2101.826,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"It may.","start":2101.826,"stop":2102.495,"duration":0.67},{"text":"It may indeed, but you have I – I'm -- this -- to my of thinking would be a valid interpretation of Section 4.","start":2102.495,"stop":2109.831,"duration":7.34},{"text":"I would be happy to see this Court say that these were not rights that were preserved under Section 4, but -- but I recognized that there maybe a valid claim if there are.","start":2109.831,"stop":2118.302,"duration":8.47},{"text":"And this is important I think, because subsistence fishing rights are at least limited by the needs of the population.","start":2118.302,"stop":2124.615,"duration":6.31},{"text":"The needs of the natives in Alaska, there food needs, but on the other hand, commercial fishing rights aren't limited by anything, except the desire to make money.","start":2124.615,"stop":2131.596,"duration":6.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But Mr. Gross, we've been recently reading a good deal about different methods of relief. Evidently -- evidently created a very serious question.","start":2131.596,"stop":2143.05,"duration":11.45},{"text":"Alaska may have a social stream of relief, greatly interfered with by what you recognized could be the regulation of the Secretary of the Interior, and might undercut their own needs program?","start":2143.05,"stop":2154.877,"duration":11.83}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- in this case, I believe it would only supplement it, Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":2154.877,"stop":2158.417,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it all depends what the -- what the conflict is between the two measures.","start":2158.417,"stop":2167.754,"duration":9.34}]},{"speakerName":"Avrum M. Gross","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there maybe instances it is true in which -- in which some program of the State may interfere with the subsistence fishing rights of natives or vice versa, I should say.","start":2167.754,"stop":2178.544,"duration":10.79},{"text":"And in -- in cases were valid retentions of federal power conflict with state police power, we would certainly recognize that the state police power must yield.","start":2178.544,"stop":2187.577,"duration":9.03},{"text":"But that I believe, this is a future question whereas today our only problem is whether we can regulate our biggest industry or not.","start":2187.577,"stop":2197.412,"duration":9.83},{"text":"At this point, I'd like to let Mr. Moody conclude the argument.","start":2197.412,"stop":2203.066,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Thank you.","start":2203.066,"stop":2203.18,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may.","start":2203.18,"stop":2204.559,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice --","start":2204.559,"stop":2205.734,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Attorney General Moody.","start":2205.734,"stop":2207.379,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"-- may it please the Court.","start":2207.379,"stop":2214.44,"duration":7.06},{"text":"There is a certain factual situation that was discussed here by counsels for the appellant Metlakatla Indian Community.","start":2214.44,"stop":2223.113,"duration":8.67},{"text":"I think we should clear it up from the standpoint as the State sees it, that is relative to the matter of support to schools and a matter of health in the State.","start":2223.113,"stop":2236.872,"duration":13.76},{"text":"Now as indicated in previous argument here, the State does operate the schools and also furnishes health facilities in the village in Metlakatla and on the island.","start":2236.872,"stop":2249.777,"duration":12.91},{"text":"And now, in one of the exhibits to the reply brief of the appellants Metlakatla, there is a letter from, I believe the Department of -- United States Department of Education which indicated that practically all of the moneys for the operation of the school in Metlakatla and as far as that is concerned in Kake and -- and Angoon were furnished by the Bureau of Indian Affairs or under the -- the – O'Malley Act.","start":2249.777,"stop":2279.441,"duration":29.66},{"text":"I believe it's another prefix term in (Inaudible).","start":2279.441,"stop":2282.751,"duration":3.31},{"text":"Now that is true –that is true in Metlakatla, that is true Kake and Angoon, that is true in regard to many of the areas of Alaska, though practically all of the school moneys are furnished by the Federal Government based upon the impact of -- of people in the federal service such as military personnel that are on Anchorage in Fairbanks and the employees living on federal lands.","start":2282.751,"stop":2307.108,"duration":24.36},{"text":"As the court realizes until statehood not more than 99% of all the lands of Alaska that was federally owned, even after -- even after the land is selected by the State, it was granted to us under the statehood act in which we have a period of 25 years to select in excess of 100-million acres of land.","start":2307.108,"stop":2328.285,"duration":21.18},{"text":"Almost 75% of the State was still owned by the Federal Government.","start":2328.285,"stop":2333.354,"duration":5.07},{"text":"So, this is not unusual in the fact that Metlakatla and in Kake and Angoon which are on federal lands furnished practically all of the school moneys by the Federal Government under an act that also allows the Federal Government to furnish mo -- money to own bay schools in Anchorage area and to the -- which are also run by the State, they are federal -- federal military reservations, schools were run by the State.","start":2333.354,"stop":2362.095,"duration":28.74},{"text":"And the -- the money is furnished by the Federal Government because it is of the impact to the federal people who are temporary in Alaska.","start":2362.095,"stop":2370.813,"duration":8.72},{"text":"Now, in the city of the Anchorage, we have many families who were living off of the (Inaudible) and who are living on – they're maybe living on the federal lands, that's not privately owned, in those -- such as the Alaska Railroad own -- owned land, people were living on that.","start":2370.813,"stop":2388.396,"duration":17.58},{"text":"The money is contributed to the Federal Government to run the schools.","start":2388.396,"stop":2390.891,"duration":2.49},{"text":"So there's nothing unique in the -- in the situation that the Federal Government either through the Bureau of Indian Affairs are -- on a similar legislation, furnishes money to the state's schools, but they are all run under the -- on direction of the State Department of Education.","start":2390.891,"stop":2412.134,"duration":21.24},{"text":"Now I believe also, in -- in his opening statement that the counsel for the appellants of Metlakatla indicated that, when Metlakatla reservation is set aside that -- that was set aside only for Indians, the language of the statute, I believe, set aside also on certain -- set aside for Eskimos and Aleuts who -- who may join the Indians from time to time.","start":2412.134,"stop":2445.804,"duration":33.67},{"text":"There are a few -- have been a few Eskimos and Aleuts on Metlakatla -- some of them in fact served on the -- on the counsel of the community.","start":2445.804,"stop":2473.784,"duration":27.98},{"text":"Now, as indicated -- indicated by the appellants, the claim of the Metlakatla Indian community is based upon three -- two Acts of Congress and one Presidential and Executive Order; the 1891 Act, the Presidential Proclamation of 1916, the reaffirmance of this proclamation of 1916 by an Act of Congress in 1934.","start":2473.784,"stop":2503.717,"duration":29.93},{"text":"A question was asked a few moments ago relative to the effect of the White Act upon the Presidential Proclamation of 1916, I think it could very well have been -- have been argued that in absence of the Act of 1934 which reaffirmed the Presidential Proclamation of 1916 setting aside the 3,000 reservations around Metlakatla, that the White Act would have done with the reservation.","start":2503.717,"stop":2535.597,"duration":31.88},{"text":"State is not contending that.","start":2535.597,"stop":2537.62,"duration":2.02},{"text":"I think -- I think it's very reasonable that -- that it can be argued and rightly so that under the 1934 Act which have ratified the presidential proclamation of the (Inaudible).","start":2537.62,"stop":2550.277,"duration":12.66},{"text":"There -- there's no question that that is still an existence because the subsequent Act (Inaudible).","start":2550.277,"stop":2562.061,"duration":11.78},{"text":"Traditionally, the Indians of Alaska have been treated, as all other Alaskans.","start":2562.061,"stop":2568.604,"duration":6.54},{"text":"They have and I am speaking her now particularly Metlakatla the -- the following.","start":2568.604,"stop":2576.287,"duration":7.68}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"May I see if I understood you in that opinion you made.","start":2576.287,"stop":2579.492,"duration":3.21},{"text":"Is that the (Inaudible) does not distinguish by the White Act (Inaudible) that still exists?","start":2579.492,"stop":2598.17,"duration":18.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"We're not conceding that.","start":2598.17,"stop":2599.414,"duration":1.24},{"text":"I am saying that the -- I'm saying it's possible to argue that it -- that it made -- that it may have been extinguished by the White Act, but it could also be very possibly argued that the 1934 Act would have reinstituted it and -- and kept it in to -- in effect.","start":2599.414,"stop":2618.966,"duration":19.55}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"What position (Inaudible) is taking on the point?","start":2618.966,"stop":2622.647,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course the position that we take – that we take on this point is that even if the reservation is still in existence and for the purpose of this argument, we're conceding it may still be in existence, but only -- but the reservation is only an area reservation which gives them the exclusive right to fish but does not give them -- does not give the Federal Government the exclusive right to regulate, in other words, an area in which only the Metlakatlas can fish.","start":2622.647,"stop":2655.114,"duration":32.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the right to regulate depends on what, Section 4 of the Statehood Act?","start":2655.114,"stop":2663.725,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it -- it would depend upon the interpretation of Section 4.","start":2663.725,"stop":2666.834,"duration":3.11},{"text":"We contend however that the -- that the matter of -- that the rights reserved under Section 4 in the Statehood Act is a right to fish exclusively in there as against anyone other than the members of the Metlakatla tribe, but that it does not go so far as to say that it preserved their method and means of fishing.","start":2666.834,"stop":2692.48,"duration":25.65}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"So if the language reserved (Inaudible) absolute control over the jurisdictions (Inaudible) over the land of other property including fishing rights done by Angoons, then that wouldn't leave, does it, any power at all to have jurisdiction (Inaudible) on the part of Alaskans?","start":2692.48,"stop":2726.095,"duration":33.61}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think this -- I think there are similar factors we can consider there to sustain the State's view.","start":2726.095,"stop":2732.993,"duration":6.9},{"text":"First is that before Statehood, all territorial laws which were passed to the Territorial Legislature as distinguished from Acts of Congress were enforced against the Metlakatlans, criminal and civil, without any distinction, not only the major crimes act, but all crimes, misdemeanors, and felonies were enforced under that.","start":2732.993,"stop":2756.35,"duration":23.36},{"text":"Now, I think we have to look at Section 60 of the Statehood Act also and look at the intent of Congress in this matter of what was fishing rights -- what they had in mind with these fishing rights at the time they passed the Statehood Act.","start":2756.35,"stop":2770.089,"duration":13.74},{"text":"Under Section 6 (e) of the Statehood Act, Congress turned over to this new state of Alaska all equipment used in the co -- in the regulation and conservation of the fisheries which they then had.","start":2770.089,"stop":2784.465,"duration":14.38},{"text":"It appears to me, we could not reasonably say that Congress would have turned over all their necessary equipment to conserve and regulate the fisheries if they were going to retain half of the fisheries in the State, or any portion of the fisheries, but they turned over all of the equipment.","start":2784.465,"stop":2802.734,"duration":18.27}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you were talking only however about Metlakatla now and not this Indian fishing, but fishing rights in the sense of comity?","start":2802.734,"stop":2812.403,"duration":9.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is true.","start":2812.403,"stop":2813.458,"duration":1.06},{"text":"However, that would -- that would limit it -- speaking only of Metlakatla, that would limit the effect of turning over all the equipment but by the same token, we've got several thousand square miles of -- of area to be policed to keep up out third parties as against the -- as against the Metlakatlans, plus you've got that area to regulate as to whether they're fishing in there was other type of the -- what the types of equipment they're fishing with.","start":2813.458,"stop":2842.499,"duration":29.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is there any dispute here between the parties of that matter is exclusively within state jurisdiction?","start":2842.499,"stop":2850.914,"duration":8.42}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean the regulation of the --","start":2850.914,"stop":2851.812,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2851.812,"stop":2852.915,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean the -- the regulation of the --","start":2852.915,"stop":2854.351,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"This is not the third party that you mentioned about?","start":2854.351,"stop":2856.225,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the water area?","start":2856.225,"stop":2857.301,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2857.301,"stop":2858.066,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Apparently, that is obviously one of the questions -- one of the questions involved here because we have -- we have tried to eliminate the fish trap.","start":2858.066,"stop":2868.843,"duration":10.78},{"text":"Now, the other -- another question that came up is to the other type of fishing, insofar as I know -- insofar as I know they have – the State has been regulating the other types of fisheries in there.","start":2868.843,"stop":2881.75,"duration":12.91},{"text":"There's been -- no question has been raised.","start":2881.75,"stop":2884.17,"duration":2.42},{"text":"In fact, this is not for the Court within the last two years, we have had a couple of Metlakatlans for fishing wi -- without licenses in the area before the state courts.","start":2884.17,"stop":2898.648,"duration":14.48},{"text":"There are no -- no question has been raised, so far that question may be raised.","start":2898.648,"stop":2901.97,"duration":3.32},{"text":"I mean, I'm not saying it won't be -- but to the present time, it hasn't been raised.","start":2901.97,"stop":2906.952,"duration":4.98},{"text":"We have -- we have complete jurisdiction both civil and criminal, and always have had prior to the statehood and have at the present time.","start":2906.952,"stop":2914.034,"duration":7.08},{"text":"They've never questioned it.","start":2914.034,"stop":2915.378,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- your position I gather under Section 4 is that the only effect of it was to prevent Alaska from giving fishing rights in the Metlakatlans -- Metlakatlan territory to anybody except Metlakatlan.","start":2915.378,"stop":2928.602,"duration":13.22}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct and we think, Mr. Justice, it's a very, very valuable right, a very valuable right in the economic standpoint of Metlakatla and we think that's all that Congress intended.","start":2928.602,"stop":2937.613,"duration":9.01},{"text":"Now, we concede they could have gone further but we -- but we -- we contend this that Congress had intended to give them -- give them more, they should have set it out clearly and would have set it out clearly.","start":2937.613,"stop":2949.101,"duration":11.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I wonder if you would just suggest, how Congress could more (Inaudible) expressed its will than to say absolute jurisdiction and control is reserved?","start":2949.101,"stop":2965.276,"duration":16.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Over all rights, that's -- that's the question we are here to determine, as I understand, as to what the right is.","start":2965.276,"stop":2971.562,"duration":6.29},{"text":"Where --","start":2971.562,"stop":2971.938,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"What – whatever the rights are that made it – and this is a question about (Inaudible) but whatever they are, they are reserved exclusively to the United States?","start":2971.938,"stop":2980.401,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2980.401,"stop":2980.87,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And if they are, Alaska has no power over them, isn't that right?","start":2980.87,"stop":2985.215,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's right but the -- but the -- I'm assuming here that the only right granted was a right -- the right to -- for them to fish exclusively and not the right that Congress did not reserve the right to regulate.","start":2985.215,"stop":2997.348,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then we get down to a question of always as to what is meant by fishing rights in the context used by Congress in Section 4?","start":2997.348,"stop":3005.657,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"That's exactly right.","start":3005.657,"stop":3007.561,"duration":1.9},{"text":"And of -- of course, as indicated in the previous arguments here, the Secretary of Interior has never made any distinction in the past whether it's in this area of Metlakatla or whether it's in the area of Kake and Angoon, wherever it might be as to the method, the times and -- of fishing, but whether be by Indians, non-Indians, or whoever they might be.","start":3007.561,"stop":3031.609,"duration":24.05},{"text":"And we think its -- that we think that -- that our proposed interpretation to what a fishing right is in this regard relative to the fish traps is consistent with the long interpretation or the long policy of Congress with Department of Interior, in connection with the Indians and their fishing rights in Alaska.","start":3031.609,"stop":3060.931,"duration":29.32},{"text":"Now, going little more into the background as to the relationship of the Metlakatla Community in the State of Alaska, and we have set this out in our -- our brief, I may want to call the Court's attention again is the fact that traditionally, the Alaska legislature, because of depressed areas in the State have set -- have set aside to the executive at each legislative session certain funds for depressed areas to be given up by the executive as the situation arises.","start":3060.931,"stop":3090.889,"duration":29.96},{"text":"In the year 1961, the appellant community was granted $8,000 economic aid from State General funds and there were some 20 communities involved and Metlakatla was approximately 1,000 inhabitants, got this second highest allotment of -- of any of the communities in Alaska.","start":3090.889,"stop":3122.064,"duration":31.17},{"text":"So they've been treated by the legislature, by the executive all along on equal footing from the standpoint of economic aid, from the standpoint of citizens, from the standpoint of the courts, and their jurisdiction over them.","start":3122.064,"stop":3135.822,"duration":13.76},{"text":"And this is the first time, this is first time under territorial status or under states status that the Metlakatla which we have conceded for the purposes of this argument is a reserve, has never raised the question of any state jurisdiction in regards to civil or criminal matters of whatever nature and it appears, to me, to be inconsistent with the -- the long policy of the Federal Government and the Department of Interior by the position they are now taking.","start":3135.822,"stop":3176.499,"duration":40.68},{"text":"As indicated previously, we -- we concede that Federal Government has power to treat Indian Reservations in the State or territory which we feel are all regula -- regulatory authorities, but in this case, we feel that the Congress does not seem fit to go the full distance on the merit.","start":3176.499,"stop":3194.788,"duration":18.29},{"text":"That that they have only set aside an area exclusively for the use of these people in fishing, but they left the matter of regulation with the State which have been through in many instances, and many phases of economic and social life in Alaska throughout the years.","start":3194.788,"stop":3213.275,"duration":18.49}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your legislature formally accepted jurisdiction under the 1953 Act?","start":3213.275,"stop":3222.331,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph E. Moody","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't believe (Inaudible).","start":3222.331,"stop":3223.952,"duration":1.62},{"text":"There was no question ever raised, it would always had full jurisdiction over it.","start":3223.952,"stop":3227.412,"duration":3.46},{"text":"As I understand the 1953 Act, only gave that right to take jurisdiction where it never existed before.","start":3227.412,"stop":3234.754,"duration":7.34},{"text":"We've are always had -- we always had that authority.","start":3234.754,"stop":3237.95,"duration":3.2},{"text":"It's never been questioned.","start":3237.95,"stop":3239.916,"duration":1.97},{"text":"So no action has been taken.","start":3239.916,"stop":3248.576,"duration":8.66},{"text":"In the answering brief of the appellant Metlakatla Community in this case on page 2 and 3 of their reply brief, they asked the State to indicate what federal authorities has made the decisions that fishing within reserves to be regulated on a uniform system of regulation.","start":3248.576,"stop":3267.126,"duration":18.55},{"text":"Although, we do not feel that this is incumbent upon us, the appellees in the matter, we're certainly be glad to indicate our -- our thoughts in the matter.","start":3267.126,"stop":3282.006,"duration":14.88},{"text":"We point to the Presidential Proclamation of 1916 which is Number 1332, set out in 39, Statute 1777 where it was stated that lands were reserved for the benefit of the Metlakatlans and such other Alaskan natives as of -- joined them or may join them, and residents on these (Inaudible) to be used by them under the General Fisheries Laws and Regulations of the United States as administered by the Secretary of Commerce, of course which was changed under the reorganization by the Secretary of Interior.","start":3282.006,"stop":3317.619,"duration":35.61},{"text":"And the -- then the Act of 1934 which in part says, “And any reservation heretofore made by any Act of Congress or executive order or proclamation for the benefit of said Indians, shall continue in full force and effect and shall continue to be subject to modification, alteration, or appeal by Congress or the President, respectively.”","start":3317.619,"stop":3344.7,"duration":27.08},{"text":"Now, the -- the -- this President Proclamation, this Act of 1934 is still in effect and it's -- if you will look at the -- on page 20 -- 43 of the appellants reply in -- in their brief, not the reply brief, but in their original brief, they state, “Moreover, the Congressional ratification of the Proclamation in 1934, most clearly placed Executive action, our statute on par with the 1891 Law.”","start":3344.7,"stop":3383.16,"duration":38.46},{"text":"We agree with this statement and we agree that the Act of 1934 confirmed the Presidential Proclamation of 1916 which said that the fishing in these waters would be on -- on par with all other fishers -- fishermen in the area.","start":3383.16,"stop":3413.399,"duration":30.24},{"text":"Now they've indicated -- the appellants have indicated that they're, “We may not regulate fisheries in reserve on the Doctrine of Preemption.”","start":3413.399,"stop":3420.443,"duration":7.04},{"text":"They suggest an irreconcilable conflict has arisen between the two sovereigns, and as a result the state power must yield to federal authority.","start":3420.443,"stop":3427.954,"duration":7.51},{"text":"The fallacy of this argument is – the will -- the Secretary of Interior does not constitute the will of Government.","start":3427.954,"stop":3434.045,"duration":6.09},{"text":"The Secretary has not based his regulation on his own desire he says, but in the way he believes to be the will of Congress that is expressed in Section 4 of the Statehood Act.","start":3434.045,"stop":3444.098,"duration":10.05},{"text":"Now as to his own authority, he said he has, Section 4 of the Statehood Act as to, in regard to any rights that they might have been established under White Act.","start":3444.098,"stop":3454.118,"duration":10.02},{"text":"Mr. Gross has covered that and we contend no right was established under the White Act.","start":3454.118,"stop":3458.481,"duration":4.36},{"text":"The only thing that was established under White Act in connection with these fishers were that they fish on par with everyone else in the Alaskan waters.","start":3458.481,"stop":3466.982,"duration":8.5},{"text":"If the State suggests interpretation of Section 4 of Statehood Act is correct, that only Congress preserved the status quo, that is the only the right (Inaudible) exclusive use of the waters to fish in, subject to Statehood Act to regulate the manner and means of taking its -- taking it on the on the General Fisheries Law, it follows the Secretary's interpretation is invalid, and no question of preemption arise.","start":3466.982,"stop":3489.76,"duration":22.78},{"text":"There must be clear and equivocal expression of congressional will by Congress, if state power is to be preemptive and we submit that there has been no clear congressional action in this case.","start":3489.76,"stop":3503.315,"duration":13.55},{"text":"We submit that the policy of Congress, the Secretary of Interior prior to Statehood has just -- has been just opposite to what the Secretary's action was in this case in allowing along the fish trap.","start":3503.315,"stop":3516.551,"duration":13.24},{"text":"And we contend therefore that the -- any regulation he has promulgated to allow fish traps is invalid and of no effect and therefore, the state has a right to regulate.","start":3516.551,"stop":3530.238,"duration":13.69},{"text":"We therefore respectfully ask the Court to affirm the judge's dismissal.","start":3530.238,"stop":3538.24,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Cragun.","start":3538.24,"stop":3538.88,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":3538.88,"stop":3541.371,"duration":2.49},{"text":"Because of calculated risk, I find myself with more things to respond to than I have time, but I would like to answer a few things.","start":3541.371,"stop":3551.618,"duration":10.25},{"text":"One questions from the Court, Mr. Justice Douglas, taking up the statement from the Supreme Court of Alaska that a fish trap catches up to 600,000 fish whereas a seiner takes some 2,000 to 10,000, comes from a 1918 opinion of this Court.","start":3551.618,"stop":3574.024,"duration":22.41},{"text":"Things have changed since then.","start":3574.024,"stop":3575.263,"duration":1.24},{"text":"I asked the manager of the Kake cannery about it.","start":3575.263,"stop":3582.676,"duration":7.41},{"text":"The average catch of a trap is 65,000.","start":3582.676,"stop":3585.962,"duration":3.29},{"text":"The average catch of big seiner is 45,000 a season.","start":3585.962,"stop":3591.47,"duration":5.51},{"text":"Maximum possible for a fish trap is about 150,000 of fish and for a big seiner about 75,000 fish.","start":3591.47,"stop":3599.792,"duration":8.32},{"text":"This is not the ‘big against the small' anymore.","start":3599.792,"stop":3602,"duration":2.21},{"text":"It might have been at one time.","start":3602,"stop":3605.041,"duration":3.04},{"text":"With respect to the argument of Alaska, I take it that the -- yes, the Federal Government does have powers in Indian affairs to grant them money.","start":3605.041,"stop":3615.728,"duration":10.69},{"text":"I should say that Mr. Schifter's client, Metlakatla, gets aid from the Federal Government for Indian schools under the Impacted Areas Statute, he has quoted the letter in the appendix to his brief, on the ground that these are Indians.","start":3615.728,"stop":3632.225,"duration":16.5},{"text":"This is a federal area.","start":3632.225,"stop":3633.81,"duration":1.59},{"text":"The State comes in, wants money on that ground because this is an exclusive problem under Federal Government.","start":3633.81,"stop":3639.754,"duration":5.94},{"text":"With regard to Kake and Angoon, they got money under a different Act, the Johnson-O'Malley Act which applies solely and exclusively to Indians so that in both cases, they are getting money from the Federal Government because these are Indians in Indian community.","start":3639.754,"stop":3653.14,"duration":13.39},{"text":"Mr. Gross thought that the right to use fish traps was not given to the Indians.","start":3653.14,"stop":3661.482,"duration":8.34},{"text":"It was given to just anybody, but if we take that shore, both whites and Indians have the right to use fish traps if they have the wherewithal to do it, and the Indians ordinarily didn't until Congress have told them, the United States bought these few traps for them.","start":3661.482,"stop":3677.309,"duration":15.83},{"text":"They were using them as the matter of right.","start":3677.309,"stop":3680.546,"duration":3.24},{"text":"When Statehood came, what they were using was not wrongful at all.","start":3680.546,"stop":3685.671,"duration":5.13},{"text":"It's more than -- I was thinking last night, I should have thought of it earlier, Professor (Inaudible) in his lecture on Fundamental Legal Conceptions said that a bare oral license to walkover Blackacre is an interesting land.","start":3685.671,"stop":3700.643,"duration":14.97},{"text":"It's a right.","start":3700.643,"stop":3701.766,"duration":1.12},{"text":"He uses it as an example of a right in land.","start":3701.766,"stop":3705.17,"duration":3.4},{"text":"Now, here, these Indians have a right in the use of those fish traps, and the United States said that it reserved to itself the exclusive -- no, the absolute jurisdiction and control until disposed of by Congress.","start":3705.17,"stop":3720.137,"duration":14.97},{"text":"Many of the other arguments I take to be ad hominem, about how difficult it would be for Alaska to reduce -- regulating here if a number of fishermen are not subject to its jurisdiction.","start":3720.137,"stop":3733.31,"duration":13.17},{"text":"But that is not an argument to make to this Court, but they should go to Congress with that and ask Congress to terminate the absolute jurisdiction and control which Congress retained that -- with the consent of the State.","start":3733.31,"stop":3750.561,"duration":17.25},{"text":"The form that I've attempted to go into this question of what aboriginal rights there are, I'd like to say that Kake is a tribe so as Angoon.","start":3750.561,"stop":3761.047,"duration":10.49},{"text":"They are tribes of Tlingit Indians who were a very closely related people, but Kake and Angoon are just little islands in this whole Southeast Alaska.","start":3761.047,"stop":3771.02,"duration":9.97},{"text":"We do not assert, and I take it, we could not assert that we could go over all Tlingit territory simply because we are members of the larger Tlingit ethnography.","start":3771.02,"stop":3781.755,"duration":10.74},{"text":"We are Kake -- the Kake tribe was so described in this charter which was obtained from the United States.","start":3781.755,"stop":3788.118,"duration":6.36},{"text":"The Kake, a tribe of Indians back --","start":3788.118,"stop":3791.293,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Cragun, I think that the time you have is little, but I would like to have you tell us whether I correctly understood Mr. Gross' dissent that these rights are Kake and Angoon had been sued for, the taking of them, and the judgment had been recovered in the Court of Claims, is that right or not?","start":3791.293,"stop":3810.793,"duration":19.5}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it's correct that Kake and Angoon have brought an action, a suit to the Court of Claims, and have been impelled and entitled to recover for the taking of all their aboriginal rights, but that's only as part of the Tlingit group.","start":3810.793,"stop":3823.179,"duration":12.39},{"text":"Congress authorizes by the Tlingit and the Ida the overall of groups and the overwhelming bulk of their land was taken not later than the time of the establishment of the Congress National (Inaudible), so the Court of Claims held.","start":3823.179,"stop":3838.215,"duration":15.04},{"text":"And with that, of course, vanished their rights to the over overwhelming bulk of their aboriginal lands.","start":3838.215,"stop":3844.81,"duration":6.59},{"text":"Kake is a little village, it's got a little property.","start":3844.81,"stop":3847.477,"duration":2.67},{"text":"Angoon has a little village.","start":3847.477,"stop":3848.793,"duration":1.32},{"text":"They are aboriginal sites, it's all that's left, together with their fish traps of what once was a very vast aboriginal holding.","start":3848.793,"stop":3856.312,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did the claim advanced in the Court of Claims embrace the same rights as here reasserted by Kake and Angoon?","start":3856.312,"stop":3865.182,"duration":8.87}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, to the extent that white people took over the fishing rights that have been exclusively those of the Tlingit and Haida Indians.","start":3865.182,"stop":3872.76,"duration":7.58},{"text":"The claim did embrace them and it was found that white people had with the permission of Congress taken them, that they have lost their -- their exclusive right of fisheries in the whole Southeast of Alaska.","start":3872.76,"stop":3884.637,"duration":11.88}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I would be interested to hear you say how you can have compensation for that right to the Court of Claims and yet rely on it here?","start":3884.637,"stop":3895.565,"duration":10.93}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think we can get compensation for what we lost.","start":3895.565,"stop":3898.846,"duration":3.28},{"text":"We can get for no more than what we have lost.","start":3898.846,"stop":3901.002,"duration":2.16},{"text":"I say that here, there is a thread which never has been lost.","start":3901.002,"stop":3904.288,"duration":3.29},{"text":"It's trifling by the side of our aboriginal right, trifling indeed.","start":3904.288,"stop":3909.338,"duration":5.05},{"text":"It's merely of thread left of what once was the vast fishery that has been taken from the exclusive use and control of Tlingit Indians.","start":3909.338,"stop":3916.379,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"What is that thread?","start":3916.379,"stop":3918.21,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"The thread is a pitiful 11 fish traps out of their whole vast Southeast Alaskan exclusive use and occupancy when the white men arrived.","start":3918.21,"stop":3930.099,"duration":11.89}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But that was embraced as I understood you, I maybe misunderstood you, in the claim you've made for the Court of Claims.","start":3930.099,"stop":3937.282,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Court of Claims we sued -- I say we, I'm not the attorney in that case, the Tlingit Indians -- the Tlingit and Haida Indians sued for what was lost and that, at least, is the overwhelming -- they claim that everything was lost.","start":3937.282,"stop":3954.406,"duration":17.12},{"text":"The Court of Claims did say that they have lost their valuable right of fisheries.","start":3954.406,"stop":3960.841,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that mean --","start":3960.841,"stop":3961.173,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"But I -- I don't believe that these seven fish traps, its seven not 11 and I erroneously mentioned that these seven fish traps were brought to the attention of the Court of Claims, they are really de minimis in the terms of the overall aboriginal picture.","start":3961.173,"stop":3980.06,"duration":18.89}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the citation, the Court of Claims opinion (Inaudible)?","start":3980.06,"stop":3983.897,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- not officially published this yet.","start":3983.897,"stop":3989.392,"duration":5.49},{"text":"It's -- appears in federal supplement -- 177 Federal Supplement 452.","start":3989.392,"stop":3999.9,"duration":10.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well this -- I gather, I know nothing about it except what you've just told us, but this claim by this tribe, what's the name of it, Tlingos?","start":3999.9,"stop":4009.227,"duration":9.33}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"The Tlingit.","start":4009.227,"stop":4009.978,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Tlingit tribe, is like the claim we've had before, decided on this Court, by other tribes who claimed the extinction of rights, which they claim for compensable rights and on which the Court (Inaudible) divided, it's one of those cases, isn't it?","start":4009.978,"stop":4026.7,"duration":16.72}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes it's a tribal both claim --","start":4026.7,"stop":4028.27,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A tribal claim --","start":4028.27,"stop":4028.828,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Or it's like a tribal claim.","start":4028.828,"stop":4030.079,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or the extinction of what was deemed to be vested or at least compensable property interest.","start":4030.079,"stop":4037.376,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":4037.376,"stop":4038.567,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And this Court has -- divided on whether you make out such a case or not.","start":4038.567,"stop":4044.324,"duration":5.76},{"text":"I don't quite to be fair enough for this case.","start":4044.324,"stop":4046.723,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they -- the point I believe that which have been made by Mr. Justice Whittaker is that if you lost clearly you didn't have anything here for Congress to retain absolute jurisdiction and control over.","start":4046.723,"stop":4058.699,"duration":11.98},{"text":"Am I misreading Your Honor's question?","start":4058.699,"stop":4062.16,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They haven't yet won that case at least ultimately.","start":4062.16,"stop":4065.225,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"John W. Cragun","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no, it hasn't gone to final judgment and when they get to (Inaudible) I have no doubt that the Department of Justice, Mr. Davis' colleague will come in and say, “Ah, but here is a little that you didn't lose and we're not going to pay for it.”","start":4065.225,"stop":4081.209,"duration":15.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) for that?","start":4081.209,"stop":4085.027,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":4085.027,"stop":4129.856,"duration":44.83}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 13, 1961","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren7/oral_argument_audio/23711","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 2, Metlakatla Indian Community, Annette Islands Reserve, Appellant, versus Egan, Governor of Alaska et al and Number 3, Organized Village of Kake et al., Appellants, versus Egan, Governor of Cal -- of Alaska.","start":0,"stop":26.048,"duration":26.05},{"text":"Mr. Schifter, you may proceed.","start":26.048,"stop":28.796,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":28.796,"stop":32.036,"duration":3.24},{"text":"This controversy was before this Court, was before at the 1959 term, at that time on appeal from the interim District Court for the State of Alaska.","start":32.036,"stop":44.239,"duration":12.2},{"text":"This Court noted at that time that another appeal from the same trial court decision was pending in the Alaska Supreme Court and ordered appellants to pursue their remedies in the Alaska Supreme Court.","start":44.239,"stop":61.97,"duration":17.73},{"text":"This has been done.","start":61.97,"stop":63.221,"duration":1.25},{"text":"The Alaska Supreme Court has affirmed the District Court and we are now on appeal from the Alaska Supreme Court.","start":63.221,"stop":70.993,"duration":7.77},{"text":"As we return to this Court, the substantive record is identical with the one that was before the Court in 1959.","start":70.993,"stop":79.755,"duration":8.76},{"text":"What has been added is the opinion of the Alaska Supreme Court.","start":79.755,"stop":85.85,"duration":6.09},{"text":"As I shall try to point out later on with regard to this opinion, the opinion of the Alaska Supreme Court, as far as Metlakatla is concerned, the State of Alaska, one week ago, when it filed its brief in this Court, stopped defending the theory of law on which the Alaska Supreme Court decided the case and has advanced now a new theory for the first time in this litigation.","start":85.85,"stop":110.877,"duration":25.03},{"text":"And in this context, may it please the Court, I would like to call your particular attention to our reply brief, which is now addressed to the Alaska -- to the State of Alaska’s new theory as distinct from our opening brief addressed to the decision below which is no longer defended by the State of Alaska as far as Metlakatla is concerned.","start":110.877,"stop":132.507,"duration":21.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is that (Voice Overlap)","start":132.507,"stop":134.975,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The green.","start":134.975,"stop":135.601,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That (Inaudible) small blue brief.","start":135.601,"stop":139.278,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"The green brief.","start":139.278,"stop":140.453,"duration":1.18},{"text":"I filed it yesterday, Your Honor.","start":140.453,"stop":142.222,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I had only six days in which to (Voice Overlap)","start":142.222,"stop":144,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But there was an earlier one (Inaudible)","start":144,"stop":146.145,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was last time --","start":146.145,"stop":147.086,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That was last time.","start":147.086,"stop":147.423,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Three years ago.","start":147.423,"stop":148.51,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, can you just state shortly, you only have five minutes left.","start":148.51,"stop":152.185,"duration":3.68},{"text":"What the switch in position is?","start":152.185,"stop":153.666,"duration":1.48},{"text":"I haven't (Voice overlap)","start":153.666,"stop":154.403,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":154.403,"stop":155.41,"duration":1.01},{"text":"The Alaska Supreme Court decided this case on -- by holding certain federal statutes invalid either because of some defect in them, in the statute itself namely the 1891 Act which established the Reservation, the Presidential Proclamation of 1916, Section 4 of the Alaska Statehood Act and all the way through -- entered as unconstitutionality of the statutes, incidentally, even -- even though this Court in 1918 sustained the 1891 Act.","start":155.41,"stop":189.665,"duration":34.25},{"text":"The Alaska -- State of Alaska under the new theory no longer challenges the constitutionality or validity of any of these statutes and now says that what we are dealing with here is a question of congressional intent as I understand the -- the argument when Congress passed Section 4 of the Alaska Statehood Act.","start":189.665,"stop":210.332,"duration":20.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean it's so -- it's narrow now.","start":210.332,"stop":212.179,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"It is much narrower now.","start":212.179,"stop":213.351,"duration":1.17},{"text":"As a matter fact, the way the Alaska Supreme Court decided this case and my theory of it is that Alaska might go back wrapped under it because it would pull out the reasons for federal financial support to Indians in Alaska.","start":213.351,"stop":229.414,"duration":16.06},{"text":"The way the Alaska Supreme Court decided the case, conceivably this reservation, the Metlakatla Reservation no longer exists.","start":229.414,"stop":236.745,"duration":7.33},{"text":"This is no longer suggested by the State of Alaska and as a matter fact in their brief they say that they don't have to go as far as the Alaska Supreme Court did.","start":236.745,"stop":245.097,"duration":8.35},{"text":"So we have two theories, one the theory of the Alaska Supreme Court, the other one a much narrower one.","start":245.097,"stop":250.479,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the significance you've just suggested of federal aid?","start":250.479,"stop":256.022,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"If it -- if the Alaska Supreme Court was right and Metlakatla for example is no longer a federal reserve, to be quite specific, it would not be entitled to federal assistance for school as it's now is at a very substantial rate.","start":256.022,"stop":271.429,"duration":15.41},{"text":"Subs -- there are not heath services rendered by the federal government to natives of Alaska.","start":271.429,"stop":277.107,"duration":5.68},{"text":"The constitutionality of any kind of special federal aid for Indians or natives of Alaska would be questioned under the Alaska Supreme Court decision.","start":277.107,"stop":285.958,"duration":8.85},{"text":"And --","start":285.958,"stop":286.57,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you suggesting that this was the reason for the shift of (Inaudible)?","start":286.57,"stop":289.488,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I wonder whether they haven't recognized that, yes, Your Honor.","start":289.488,"stop":295.561,"duration":6.07},{"text":"The basic question involved here is the fact that these three Indian fishing communities in Alaska have been authorized many years and continued to be authorized by the Secretary of Interior to maintain a fishing device known as a fish trap.","start":295.561,"stop":318.852,"duration":23.29},{"text":"The State of Alaska has attempted to outlaw the use of fish traps and has under the decision of the Alaska Supreme Court now, applied that statute to the fish traps maintained by the three fishing communities involving this case, Metlakatla, Kake and Angoon.","start":318.852,"stop":338.383,"duration":19.53},{"text":"The controversy is therefore one in which the Indian Communities and the United States find themselves on one side and the State of Alaska on the other.","start":338.383,"stop":347.516,"duration":9.13},{"text":"There is a distinct difference in the way the rights of Metlakatla on one hand and Kake and Angoon were arrived at and for the rest of my argument, I would confine myself to the matter in which Metlakatla derived its rights.","start":347.516,"stop":363.998,"duration":16.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this statute apply merely to these three Indian communities?","start":363.998,"stop":368.558,"duration":4.56}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which statute, Your Honor, the 1891?","start":368.558,"stop":371.348,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The prohibitions against the use of traps.","start":371.348,"stop":373.602,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, to everyone -- to everyone.","start":373.602,"stop":375.328,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Only these three?","start":375.328,"stop":376.49,"duration":1.16},{"text":"Are there any other?","start":376.49,"stop":377.895,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"Only these three maintain fish traps.","start":377.895,"stop":379.558,"duration":1.66},{"text":"Only these three have been authorized by the Secretary of Interior to maintain fish traps.","start":379.558,"stop":383.134,"duration":3.58},{"text":"They're all together and only 11 fish traps involved, four for Metlakatla and seven for Kake and Angoon combined.","start":383.134,"stop":392.539,"duration":9.4},{"text":"Metlakatla, as a community, was first organized in 18 -- and you may trace the background of it, they're first organized in 1887.","start":392.539,"stop":401.155,"duration":8.62},{"text":"At that time, the Annette Islands were completely uninhabited.","start":401.155,"stop":404.472,"duration":3.32},{"text":"The Metlakatla group was invited by the United States Government to settle on the Annette Islands, and after some search, did select this particular group of islands.","start":404.472,"stop":416.037,"duration":11.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) curiosity but why did the United States invite to come to British Columbia?","start":416.037,"stop":422.122,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"Richard Schifter","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume that there was a special interest at that time in attracting stable people to settle in the general area.","start":422.122,"stop":430.551,"duration":8.43},{"text":"I'm going to assume that this was --","start":430.551,"stop":432.257,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":432.257,"stop":438.227,"duration":5.97}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Dec  13 - 14, 1961","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"3","citation":"369 US 60 (1962)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/369/60","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 5, 1962"}